{"title_page": "Christina Aguilera", "text_new": "{{About|the singer|her eponymous debut album|Christina Aguilera (album)}}\n{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American singer, songwriter, actress, and television personality}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Christina Aguilera\n| image           = Liberation Tour (45997616942) (cropped).jpg\n| caption         = Aguilera on her [[Liberation Tour]] in 2018\n| birth_name      = Christina Mar\u00eda Aguilera\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1980|12|18}}\n| birth_place     = {{nowrap|[[New York City]]<!--No boroughs/neighborhoods, just cities per format.-->, U.S.}}<!--As per WP:LINKDIRECT and Template:infobox person, birthplace indicates CITY, state, then country. No need to spell out \"United States; 'U.S.' is fine.-->\n| home_town       = {{plain list|\n* [[Rochester, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n* [[Wexford, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n}}\n| occupation      = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|actress|television personality}}\n| spouse          = {{marriage|Jordan Bratman|2005|2011|reason=divorced}}\n| partner         = Matthew Rutler (2010\u2013present; engaged)\n| children        = 2\n| years_active    = 1992\u2013present\n| net_worth       = <!-- Do NOT add info from \"Celebrity Net Worth\" as it is unreliable -->\n| awards          = [[List of awards and nominations received by Christina Aguilera|Full list]]\n| website         = {{URL|christinaaguilera.com}}\n| module          = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background      = solo_singer\n| instrument      = Vocals\n| Genre           = {{flatlist|\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[dance-pop]]\n* [[Soul music|soul]]}}\n| label           = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| associated_acts = <!-- before adding please see [[Template:Infobox musical artist/doc#associated acts]] for appropriate additions-->\n}}\n| signature      = Christina Aguilera Signature PNG.png\n}}\n'''Christina Mar\u00eda Aguilera''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u00e6|\u0261|\u026a|\u02c8|l|\u025b\u0259r|\u0259}}, {{IPA-es|a\u0263i\u02c8le\u027ea|lang}};<ref>{{cite AV media|people=W magazine|date=May 16, 2018|title=Christina Aguilera Breaks Down Her Most Iconic Music Video Looks|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=doXqDkzFEkQ|time=0:01}}</ref> born December 18, 1980) is an American singer, songwriter, actress and television personality. Her [[List of awards and nominations received by Christina Aguilera|accolades]] include five [[Grammy Award]]s, one [[Latin Grammy Award]], and a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]]. Aguilera ranked at number 58 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s list of 100 Greatest Singers of All Time in 2008, and was included on ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s annual list of the [[Time 100|100 most influential people in the world]] in 2013. With estimated sales of 75 million records, she is one of the world's [[List of best-selling music artists|best-selling music artists]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/music/christina-aguilera-at-3arena-dublin-everything-you-need-to-know-1.4066866|title=Christina Aguilera at 3Arena, Dublin: Everything you need to know|first=Tony|last=Clayton-Lea|work=[[The Irish Times]]|date=November 3, 2019|accessdate=November 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Staten Island]] of [[New York City]] and raised in [[Pennsylvania]], Aguilera appeared on television shows in her early years, before gaining a recording contract with [[RCA Records]] in 1998. Her [[Christina Aguilera (album)|self-titled debut album]], released in 1999, reached number one in the US and spawned three US number-one singles: \"[[Genie in a Bottle]]\", \"[[What a Girl Wants (Christina Aguilera song)|What a Girl Wants]]\", and \"[[Come On Over Baby (All I Want Is You)]]\". While recognized as a prominent figure in the contemporary [[teen pop]] scene, Aguilera sought to assume artistic control with ''[[Stripped (Christina Aguilera album)|Stripped]]'' (2002) and its lead single \"[[Dirrty]]\", which displayed her sexually emancipated persona and generated considerable controversy. The second single from the album, \"[[Beautiful (Christina Aguilera song)|Beautiful]]\", received favorable response for its empowering lyrics and became an anthem for the [[LGBT community]].\n\nAguilera scored her second US number-one album with ''[[Back to Basics (Christina Aguilera album)|Back to Basics]]'' (2006), which drew inspiration from early 20th-century [[jazz]], [[soul music|soul]], and [[blues]], and spawned the top-ten singles \"[[Ain't No Other Man]]\", \"[[Hurt (Christina Aguilera song)|Hurt]]\", and \"[[Candyman (Christina Aguilera song)|Candyman]]\". Her next three albums, ''[[Bionic (Christina Aguilera album)|Bionic]]'' (2010), ''[[Lotus (Christina Aguilera album)|Lotus]]'' (2012), and ''[[Liberation (Christina Aguilera album)|Liberation]]'' (2018), all experimented with various musical styles and reached the top ten in the US. Besides solo materials, Aguilera earned chart-topping entries with collaborations including \"[[Lady Marmalade#Moulin Rouge! version|Lady Marmalade]]\", \"[[Moves like Jagger]]\", \"[[Feel This Moment]]\", and \"[[Say Something (A Great Big World song)|Say Something]]\". Alongside her music career, Aguilera starred in the film ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'' (2010) and was a coach on six seasons of the singing competition television series ''[[The Voice (American TV series)|The Voice]]'' from 2011 to 2016.\n\n==Life and career==\n===1980\u20131998: Early life and career beginnings===\nChristina Mar\u00eda Aguilera was born in [[Staten Island]], [[New York City]], on December 18, 1980, to musician Shelly Loraine Kearns (n\u00e9e Fidler) and [[United States Army]] soldier Fausto Xavier Aguilera.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wang|first1=Julia|title=Christina Aguilera Biography|url=http://www.people.com/people/christina_aguilera/biography/|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|access-date=September 28, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331213217/https://people.com/people/christina_aguilera/biography/|archive-date=31 March 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Her father {{cl-span|is Ecuadorian|date=October 2019|reason=I guess he was in the army to GAIN citizenship but failed? Or is he ACTUALLY an American citizen of Ecuadorian descent?}}, and her mother has German, Irish, Welsh, and Dutch ancestry.{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|p=2}}<ref name=\"Early life\">{{cite journal|last1=Gregory|first1=Sophfronia Scott|last2=Ferguson|first2=Hayes|title=Uncorking the Genie|journal=People|date=September 27, 1999|volume=52|issue=12|pages=75\u201376|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20129327,00.html|access-date=September 28, 2014|issn=0093-7673}}</ref> Her family moved frequently because of her father's military service, and lived in places including New Jersey, Texas, New York, and Japan.<ref name=\"WashingtonPost\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPcap/2000-02/13/003r-021300-idx.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621070136/https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPcap/2000-02/13/003r-021300-idx.html|title=Christina Aguilera's Fast Track|last=Harrington|first=Richard|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=February 13, 2000|archive-date=June 21, 2018|url-status=dead|access-date=August 25, 2017}}</ref> Aguilera alleged that her father was physically and emotionally [[child abuse|abusive]].<ref name=\"mtv3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/aguilera_christina/news_feature_080906/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140805022136/http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/aguilera_christina/news_feature_080906/|archive-date=August 5, 2014|title=Christina Aguilera's Old Soul|first=Jennifer|last=Vineyard|access-date=July 21, 2013}}</ref> To cope with her turbulent household, she used music as a form of escape.<ref name=\"WMagazine\"/> Following her parents' divorce when she was six years old, Aguilera, her younger sister Rachel, and her mother moved into her grandmother's home in [[Rochester, Pennsylvania|Rochester]], a suburb in the [[Pittsburgh]] area.<ref name=\"Early life\"/> Her mother later remarried and had one more child.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Helligar|first=Jeremy|last2=Majewski|first2=Lori|date=February 3, 2003|title=Christina's World|journal=[[Us Weekly]]}}</ref> After years of estrangement, Aguilera expressed interest in reconciling with her father in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://b96.cbslocal.com/2012/02/09/christina-aguilera-wants-to-reconcile-with-estranged-father/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730035712/http://b96.cbslocal.com/2012/02/09/christina-aguilera-wants-to-reconcile-with-estranged-father/|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 30, 2014|title=Christina Aguilera Wants To Reconcile With Estranged Father|publisher=[[CBS Local Media]]|date=February 9, 2012|access-date=July 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs a child, Aguilera was drawn to [[soul music|soul]] and [[blues]] records her grandmother bought and would practice singing, which earned her a reputation as \"the little girl with the big voice\" in her neighborhood.<ref name=\"newsweek\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/christina-aguilera-comes-age-112341|title=Christina Aguilera Comes of Age|last=Ali|first=Lorraine|date=July 30, 2006|work=[[Newsweek]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120135330/http://www.newsweek.com/christina-aguilera-comes-age-112379|archive-date=January 20, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> She aspired to be a singer, and won her first talent show at age eight with a rendition of [[Whitney Houston]]'s \"[[I Wanna Dance with Somebody (Who Loves Me)]]\".<ref name=\"WashingtonPost\"/> Aged 10, she performed \"[[A Sunday Kind of Love]]\" on the competition show ''[[Star Search]]'', and was eliminated during the semi-final round.<ref name=\"WMagazine\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wmagazine.com/people/celebrities/2011/07/christina-aguilera-cover-story|title=From the Vaults: The Fall & Rise of Christina Aguilera|last=Hirschberg|first=Lynn|work=[[W (magazine)|W]]|date=July 2011|access-date=July 29, 2014}}</ref> She performed the song again on [[KDKA-TV]]'s ''Wake Up with [[Larry Richert]]''.{{sfn|Kimpel|2006|p=2}} During her youth in the Pittsburgh area, Aguilera sang the US national anthem, \"[[The Star-Spangled Banner]]\", before [[Pittsburgh Penguins]] hockey, [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] football, and [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] baseball games, and the [[1992 Stanley Cup Finals]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://triblive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/sports/penguins/s_623827.html|title=Anthem singer fires up Mellon crowd|last=Grupp|first=John|newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Tribune-Review]]|date=May 6, 2009|access-date=February 5, 2010}}</ref> She attended [[Rochester Area School District]] in Rochester and [[Marshall Middle School (Pittsburgh)|Marshall Middle School]] near [[Wexford, Pennsylvania|Wexford]], and briefly attended [[North Allegheny Intermediate High School]] before being homeschooled to avoid being bullied.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ca.movies.yahoo.com/person/christina-aguilera/biography.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812193158/https://ca.movies.yahoo.com/person/christina-aguilera/biography.html|archive-date=August 12, 2014|title=Christina Aguilera Biography|publisher=[[Yahoo! Movies]]|access-date=July 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, Aguilera auditioned for a position on ''[[The Mickey Mouse Club#1990s revival, The All-New Mickey Mouse Club (MMC)|The Mickey Mouse Club]]'', although she did not meet its age requirements. She joined the television series two years later, where she performed musical numbers and [[sketch comedy]] until its cancellation in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/interview/12043048|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070401032341/http://music.yahoo.com/read/interview/12043048|title=Dreaming of Genie|last=Goldstein|first=Rob|publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]]|date=May 15, 1999|archive-date=April 1, 2007}}</ref> Fellow cast members included [[Ryan Gosling]], [[Keri Russell]], [[Britney Spears]], and [[Justin Timberlake]].<ref name=\"AguileraBiographyPeople\">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/christina_aguilera|title=Christina Aguilera Biography|work=People|access-date=December 8, 2010}}</ref> After the show ended, Aguilera moved to Japan and recorded her first song, \"All I Wanna Do\", a duet with Japanese singer [[Keizo Nakanishi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,2044752,00.html|title=Christina Aguilera: Biography|date=September 15, 2001|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=June 25, 2019|first=Kevork|last=Djansezian}}</ref> In 1998, Aguilera returned to the US to seek a recording contract. She approached [[RCA Records]], who told her to contact [[Walt Disney Records|Disney]] instead because they were having financial difficulties.{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|p=43}} She sent her [[cover version]] of Whitney Houston's \"[[Run to You (Whitney Houston song)|Run to You]]\" to Disney in hopes of being selected to record the theme song \"[[Reflection (song)|Reflection]]\" for their animated film ''[[Mulan (1998 film)|Mulan]]'' (1998).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,84715,00.html|title=Club Kid|last=Willman|first=Chris|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=October 11, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150103052149/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0%2C%2C84715%2C00.html|archive-date=January 3, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Aguilera was ultimately selected to sing \"Reflection\"; the song was released in June 1998 and charted on the [[Hot Adult Contemporary Tracks|''Billboard'' Adult Contemporary]] chart at number 15.{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|p=44}}\n\n===1999\u20132001: ''Christina Aguilera'', ''Mi Reflejo'', and ''My Kind of Christmas''===\nAfter \"Reflection\", Aguilera attracted the attention of RCA's A&R [[Ron Fair]] and was signed with the label quickly afterwards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/the-christina-aguilera-story-so-far-19991028|title=The Christina Aguilera Story (So Far)|first=Anthony|last=Bozza|work=Rolling Stone|date=October 28, 1999|access-date=January 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Smith|first=Andy|title=One talented teen|work=[[The Providence Journal]]|date=August 15, 1998}}</ref> RCA was pressured by the contemporary [[teen pop]] craze evoked by Aguilera's peer Britney Spears, leading to the label rushing production of the album and aligning Aguilera to be part of the teen pop trend.{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|p=45}} They released the lead single off the album, \"[[Genie in a Bottle]]\", a trendy [[pop music|pop]] and [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] track, in June 1999.{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|p=45}} The single catapulted Aguilera to stardom, peaking atop the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and charts of 20 other countries.<ref name=\"GeniePeak21\">{{cite journal|title=Portrait of an Artist: Christina Aguilera|work=Billboard|date=January 20, 2000|volume=112|issue=5|pages=6\u20137}}</ref> It has sold over seven million copies as of 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chartsinfrance.net/Christina-Aguilera/news-93194.html|title=L'histoire d'un tube : 'Genie in a Bottle' de Christina Aguilera f\u00eate ses 15 ans|publisher=Charts in France|language=French|date=August 17, 2014|access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> Aguilera's [[Christina Aguilera (album)|eponymous debut album]] followed in August 1999 and peaked at number one on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref name=\"WashingtonPost\"/> It was certified [[RIAA certification|eight times platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA),<ref name=\"RIAA\"/> and had moved 17 million copies worldwide by 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/7682705/Christina-Aguileras-eye-on-the-prize.html|title=Christina Aguilera's 'eye on the prize'|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|access-date=August 26, 2017|first=Craig|last=McLean|date=May 7, 2010}}</ref> The album produced three other singles: two US number-one singles\u2013\"[[What a Girl Wants (Christina Aguilera song)|What a Girl Wants]]\" and \"[[Come On Over Baby (All I Want Is You)]]\", and one US top-five single\u2013\"[[I Turn to You (All-4-One song)#Christina Aguilera cover|I Turn to You]]\", a cover of [[All-4-One]]'s song.<ref name=\"AguileraBBCharts\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/299251/Christina+Aguilera/chart?f=379|title=Chart history for Christina Aguilera|work=Billboard|access-date=June 20, 2014}}</ref> At the [[42nd Annual Grammy Awards]] in February 2000, Aguilera won [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/story/12051721|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528131603/http://music.yahoo.com/read/story/12051721|title=Christina Aguilera Wins Best New Artist|last=Rosen|first=Craig|publisher=Yahoo! Music|date=February 24, 2000|archive-date=May 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAguiera's two following studio albums, ''[[Mi Reflejo]]'' and ''[[My Kind of Christmas]]'', were released in September and October 2000, respectively.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Charts and retail notas|journal=Billboard|volume=112|issue=45|page=47|date=November 4, 2000|first=Leila|last=Cobo}}</ref> The former, a Spanish-language album consisting of re-recorded versions of tracks on Aguilera's debut album and several original songs, topped the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums|''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums]] for 19 consecutive weeks and was certified six times platinum in the [[Latin music|Latin]] field by the RIAA.<ref name=\"RIAA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=Christina+Aguilera|title=Gold & Platinum \u2013 Christina Aguilera|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726142412/http://www.billboard.com/charts/2001-02-03/latin-albums|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/2001-02-03/latin-albums|title=Top Latin Albums: February 3, 2001|work=Billboard|archive-date=July 26, 2014}}</ref> It won [[Latin Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Album|Best Female Pop Vocal Album]] at the [[2nd Annual Latin Grammy Awards]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/christina-wins-latin-grammy-20011030|title=Christina Wins Latin Grammy|last=Saraceno|first=Christina|work=Rolling Stone|date=October 30, 2001|access-date=December 4, 2012}}</ref> The latter contains covers of [[Christmas music|Christmas]] popular songs and a few original [[dance-pop]] tunes,{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|p=108}} and was certified platinum by the RIAA.<ref name=\"RIAA\"/> In support of her albums, Aguilera embarked on her first concert tour, [[Christina Aguilera in Concert]], from mid-2000 to early 2001. The tour visited North America, Europe, South America, and Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1424807/aguilera-to-play-prom-in-augusta-georgia/|title=Aguilera To Play Prom In Augusta, Georgia|first=David|last=Basham|publisher=MTV News|date=August 21, 2000|access-date=July 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010330211536/http://www.christina-a.com/christinainjapan.html|url=http://www.christina-a.com/christinainjapan.html|title=Christina Aguilera Live in Japan|publisher=Christina Aguilera website|date=February 9, 2001|archive-date=March 30, 2001}}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' in 2000 recognized Aguilera as the Top Female Pop Act of the Year.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Year in Music 2000|journal=Billboard|page=58|date=December 30, 2000|volume=112|issue=53}}</ref> Despite the successes, Aguilera was displeased with the music and image her manager Steve Kurtz had aligned her to, feeling unable to control her own image.<ref name=\"NotYourPuppet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/aguilera_christina/news_feature_feb_02/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090305024500/http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/aguilera_christina/news_feature_feb_02/|archive-date=March 5, 2009|title=Christina Aguilera: Not Your Puppet|last=Stitzel|first=Kim|publisher=MTV News|date=February 2002|access-date=January 29, 2009}}</ref> In October 2000, she filed a breach of [[fiduciary duty]] lawsuit against Kurtz for improper, undue and inappropriate influence over her professional activities. After terminating Kurtz's services, RCA hired [[Irving Azoff]] as Aguilera's new manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/story?id=114375&page=1|title=Aguilera's Ex-Manager Fires Back|publisher=ABC News|date=October 19, 2000|access-date=December 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAguilera took her first steps in artistic control with the 2001 ''[[Moulin Rouge! Music from Baz Luhrmann's Film|Moulin Rouge!]]'' version of [[Labelle]]'s \"[[Lady Marmalade]]\" (1974), a collaboration with [[Pink (singer)|Pink]], [[Mya (singer)|Mya]], and [[Lil Kim]], produced by [[hip hop music|hip hop]] musicians [[Missy Elliott]] and [[Rockwilder]].<ref name=\"newsweek\"/> RCA executives initially opposed to Aguilera recording \"Lady Marmalade\" because it was \"too [[urban music|urban]]\", but Aguilera ultimately managed to record the song of her own accord.<ref name=\"NotYourPuppet\"/> The collaboration topped the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 for five weeks based on airplay alone, becoming the first airplay-only track in history to remain on the chart's top spot for more than one week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/lady-marmalade-mw0000424595|title=Lady Marmalade \u2013 Song Review|website=AllMusic|first=Jose|last=Promis|access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Hot 100 Spotlight|work=Billboard|date=June 2, 2001|first=Silvio|last=Pietroluongo|page=123|volume=113|issue=22}}</ref> It won [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Collaboration with Vocals|Best Pop Collaboration with Vocals]] at the [[44th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/The-2002-Grammy-winners-2868670.php|title=The 2002 Grammy winners|work=San Francisco Chronicle|date=February 28, 2002|access-date=July 7, 2014}}</ref> In mid-2001, [[Warlock Records]] released ''[[Just Be Free]]'', a compilation of [[demo (music)|demo]] tracks Aguilera recorded in 1994 and 1995, when she was looking forward to an album release after the end of ''The Mickey Mouse Club''. Aguilera filed a suit against Warlock Records and the album's producers to stop the release.{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|page=34}} The two parties came to a confidential settlement to release the album, in which Aguilera lent out her name, likeness, and image for an unspecified amount of damages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/A/Aguilera_Christina/2001/07/03/pf-742790.html|title=Disputed Aguilera album to be released|last=McGrath|first=Stephanie|publisher=[[Jam!]]|date=July 3, 2001|access-date=May 25, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===2002\u20132003: ''Stripped''===\n[[File:Stripped Tour CH - cropped.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Aguilera performing on [[The Stripped Tour]] in 2003]]\nWhen planning her fourth studio album, Aguilera leaned towards a new artistic direction that she felt had more musical and lyrical depth.<ref name=\"USAToday\">{{cite news|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2002-10-23-christina-aguilera_x.htm|title=Aguilera's image is 'Stripped'|last=Gardner|first=Elysa|newspaper=USA Today|date=October 24, 2002|access-date=October 19, 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160301144224/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2002-10-23-christina-aguilera_x.htm|archive-date=March 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> She named the album ''[[Stripped (Christina Aguilera album)|Stripped]]'' and explained that the title represented \"a new beginning, a re-introduction of [herself] as a new artist in a way\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1458433/christina-stands-up-for-the-ladies-discusses-fathers-abuse/|title=Christina Stands Up For The Ladies, Discusses Father's Abuse|first=Jennifer|last=Vineyard|publisher=MTV News|date=October 30, 2002|access-date=July 7, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera served as the album's [[executive producer]] and co-wrote most of the songs.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=[[Stripped (Christina Aguilera album)|Stripped]]|others=Christina Aguilera|year=2002|type=CD liner notes|publisher=[[RCA Records]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Vice_Stripped\">{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_ca/article/d3dpby/christina-aguilera-stripped-gender-equality-15-anniversary|title=15 Years After Christina Aguilera's 'Stripped,' We're Still Nowhere Near Gender Equality|first=Sophie|last=Willkinson|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|date=October 27, 2017|access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> To present her new persona, Aguilera chose to release \"[[Dirrty]]\" as the lead single from the album in September 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/28/arts/28iht-chris.2322180.html|title=Aguilera Aims for Edgy, bur Richer, Sound|work=[[The New York Times]]|first=Lola|last=Ogunnaike|date=July 28, 2006|access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> Its accompanying music video generated controversy for depicting overtly sexual fetishes.<ref>{{cite web|last=Edwards|first=Tanya L|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1458275/20021022/aguilera_christina.jhtml|title=How Dirty Is 'Dirrty'? X-posing The Kinks In X-tina's Video|publisher=MTV News|date=October 23, 2002|access-date=June 16, 2007}}</ref> Aguilera's new image presented in the video was widely criticized by the public that it began to overshadow her music.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tryangiel|first=Josh|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1376243-1,00.html|title=Welcome to my Bubble|work=Time|date=August 27, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012211218/http://time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C1376243-1%2C00.html|archive-date=October 12, 2007|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dark|first=Jane|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2002-11-12/music/siren-wailing/|title=Siren Wailing|work=[[The Village Voice]]|date=November 11, 2002|access-date=June 18, 2007|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041209030356/http://www.villagevoice.com/issues/0246/dark.php|archive-date=December 9, 2004|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"blender\">{{cite web|last=Duerden|first=Nick|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/67285/good-bad-dirrty.html|title=The Good, the Bad and the Dirrty|work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|date=November 15, 2003|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090807060733/http://www.blender.com/guide/67285/good-bad-dirrty.html|archive-date=August 7, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> She defended her new image: \"I'm in the power position, in complete command of everything and everybody around me. To be totally balls-out like that is, for me, the measure of a true artist.\"<ref name=\"blender\"/>\n\n''Stripped'' was released in October 2002.<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/stripped/christina-aguilera/critic-reviews|title=Critic Reviews for Stripped|website=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> The album incorporates various genres from R&B and [[flamenco]] to [[rock music|rock]], and lyrically revolves around the theme of [[self-esteem]] while also discussing [[sex]] and [[gender equality]].<ref name=\"Vice_Stripped\"/><ref name=\"rs_Stripped\"/> It received mixed reviews from music critics, who viewed the employment of various musical styles incoherent, but praised Aguilera's vocals.<ref name=\"MC\"/><ref name=\"rs_Stripped\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/stripped-20021105|title=Stripped|work=Rolling Stone|first=Jancee|last=Dunn|author-link=Jancee Dunn|date=November 6, 2002|access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> The album peaked at number two on the ''Billboard'' 200 and has sold over 4.3 million copies in the US as of 2014.<ref name=\"AskBillboardCareer\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6236538/ask-billboard-taylor-swift-out-shakes-mariah-carey?page=0%2C3|title=Ask Billboard: Taylor Swift Out-'Shake's Mariah Carey|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=September 1, 2014|work=Billboard|access-date=February 10, 2015}}</ref> In the UK, the album has sold two million copies as of 2017 and was the second highest-selling album by an American female artist during the 2000s decade, behind [[Norah Jones]] with ''[[Come Away with Me]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/official-charts-flashback-2002-christina-aguilera-reinvents-herself-with-dirrty-at-number-1__21081/|title=Official Charts Flashback 2002: Christina Aguilera reinvents herself with Dirrty at Number 1|date=November 23, 2017|access-date=January 20, 2018|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|first=Rob|last=Copsey}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media|date=December 28, 2009|title=Best-Selling of the Noughties|medium=radio news|publisher=[[BBC Radio 1]]/Official Charts Company}}</ref> By 2006, ''Stripped'' had sold over 12 million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/10699242/scott_storchs_outrageous_fortune/print|title=Scott Storch's Outrageous Fortune|work=Rolling Stone|author=Tour\u00e9|date=June 29, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080419055040/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/10699242/scott_storchs_outrageous_fortune/print|archive-date=April 19, 2008}}</ref> The second single from the album, the ballad \"[[Beautiful (Christina Aguilera song)|Beautiful]]\", received universal acclaim for its empowering lyrics about embracing inner beauty, and became an anthem for the [[LGBT community]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/song-stories/beautiful-christina-aguilera|title=Beautiful by Christina Aguilera|magazine=Rolling Stone|access-date=April 2, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327020233/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/song-stories/beautiful-christina-aguilera|archive-date=March 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Beautiful,' Damn It|work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|first=Larry|last=Flick|date=January 20, 2004|page=90|url=https://books.google.co.jp/books?id=72QEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA90&|issue=906}}</ref> It was the album's best-charting single, peaking at number two on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=\"AguileraBBCharts\"/> The song won [[Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Performance|Best Female Pop Vocal Performance]] at the [[46th Annual Grammy Awards]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/02/09/arts/the-grammy-award-winners-of-2004.html|title=The Grammy Award Winners of 2004|work=The New York Times|date=February 9, 2004|access-date=October 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n''Stripped'' was followed by three other singles: \"[[Fighter (Christina Aguilera song)|Fighter]]\", \"[[Can't Hold Us Down]]\", and \"[[The Voice Within]]\", all of which were released in 2003 and entered the top 40 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=\"AguileraBBCharts\"/> During promotion of ''Stripped'', Aguilera cultivated a new image by adopting the [[alter ego]] Xtina, dyeing her hair black, and debuting several tattoos and piercings.<ref name=\"CareerBiggest\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/christina_aguilera/0,,,00.html|title=Christina Aguilera: Five Fun Facts|work=People|access-date=October 19, 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022140434/http://www.people.com/people/christina_aguilera/0,,,00.html|archive-date=October 22, 2013}}</ref> She co-headlined the [[Justified and Stripped Tour]] alongside Justin Timberlake from June to September 2003 in support of ''Stripped'' and Timberlake's album ''[[Justified (album)|Justified]]'' (2002), before embarking on her solo [[The Stripped Tour|Stripped Tour]] until December.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/justin-timberlake-and-christina-aguilera-double-trouble-20030626|title=Justin Timberlake and Christina Aguilera: Double Trouble|first=Jancee|last=Dunn|work=Rolling Stone|date=June 26, 2003|access-date=October 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.frontiertouring.com/index.php?action=retail&form_name=view_retail&merchant_id=595&sectionID=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325202833/http://www.frontiertouring.com/index.php?action=retail&form_name=view_retail&merchant_id=595&sectionID=|title=Frontier Touring: The Stripped Tour|publisher=Frontier Touring|archive-date=March 25, 2012}}</ref> Aguilera attended the [[2003 MTV Video Music Awards]] in August, where she and Britney Spears kissed [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] during their performance of \"[[Like a Virgin (song)|Like a Virgin]]\" and \"[[Hollywood (Madonna song)|Hollywood]]\", which received considerable media attention.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/madonna-magic-at-mtv-awards/|title=Madonna Magic At MTV Awards|last=Moody|first=Nekesa Mumbi|publisher=CBS News|date=August 29, 2003|access-date=February 22, 2013}}</ref> She was the host of the [[2003 MTV Europe Music Awards]], where she won [[MTV Europe Music Award for Best Female|Best Female]] award, in November.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1480240/its-justins-night-as-christina-kelly-osbourne-fight-at-mtv-europe-awards/|title=It's Justin's Night As Christina, Kelly Osbourne Fight At MTV Europe Awards|first=Jon|last=Wiederhorn|publisher=MTV News|date=November 6, 2003|access-date=October 20, 2013}}</ref> ''Billboard'' announced Aguilera as the Top Female Pop Act of 2003.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Year in Music 2003|journal=Billboard|page=68|volume=115|issue=52|date=December 27, 2003}}</ref>\n\n===2004\u20132009: Marriage, ''Back to Basics'', and first child===\n[[File:Christina Aguilera Sanremo.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Aguilera performing at the [[Sanremo Music Festival]] in 2006]]\nIn 2004, Aguilera recorded a [[Car Wash (song)#Christina Aguilera and Missy Elliott version|revised version]] of [[Rose Royce]]'s \"[[Car Wash (song)|Car Wash]]\" (1976) with Missy Elliott for the animated film ''[[Shark Tale]]'', in which she was a voice actress,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1491393/christina-aguilera-is-poisonous-in-video-with-missy-elliott/|title=Christina Aguilera Is Poisonous In Video With Missy Elliott|first=Jennifer|last=Vineyard|publisher=MTV News|date=September 24, 2004|access-date=October 21, 2013}}</ref> and contributed vocals to [[Nelly]]'s single \"[[Tilt Ya Head Back]]\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Singles: Essential Reviews|first=Michael|last=Paoletta|work=Billboard|date=September 25, 2004|volume=116|issue=39|page=55}}</ref> She was a featured artist on [[Herbie Hancock]]'s 2005 cover of [[Leon Russell]]'s \"[[A Song for You]]\" (1970), which was nominated for Best Pop Collaboration with Vocals at the [[48th Annual Grammy Awards]] in February 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/music/bal-grammys-winners0209-htmlstory.html|title=Complete list of 2006 Grammy winners|newspaper=The Baltimore Sun|date=February 9, 2006|access-date=July 7, 2014}}</ref> During this time, Aguilera started working on her follow-up studio album and embraced a new image inspired by figures of the [[Classic Hollywood cinema|Classic Hollywood era]] such as [[Marilyn Monroe]], [[Marlene Dietrich]], and [[Mary Pickford]], debuting blonde curly hair and retro-styled makeup.<ref name=\"EW2004\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2004/08/30/highlights-2004-mtv-video-music-awards/|title=Highlights of the 2004 MTV Video Music Awards|first=Brian|last=Hiatt|date=August 30, 2004|access-date=January 22, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"HelloMag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/music/2004/10/20/christinaaguliera/|title=Christina turns Hollywood pin-up in latest shoot|work=Hello!|date=October 20, 2004|access-date=October 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAguilera became engaged with marketing executive Jordan Bratman, with whom she had dated since 2003, in February 2005.<ref name=\"Marries\">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1131176,00.html|title=Christina Aguilera Marries|work=People|date=November 18, 2005|access-date=October 21, 2013}}</ref> They married on November 19, 2005, at an estate in [[Napa County, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/music/celebrity/christina-aguileras-highs-and-lows/ss-BBgQqMJ#image=9|title=Christina Aguilera's Highs and Lows|publisher=[[MSN]]|access-date=February 23, 2015}}</ref> Aguilera released the lead single from her fifth studio album, \"[[Ain't No Other Man]]\", in June 2006.<ref name=\"mtvnews4\">{{cite news|last=Vineyard|first=Jennifer|title='Ain't No Other Man' Video Has Christina Singing The Blues|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1534591/video-has-christina-singing-blues.jhtml|access-date=April 25, 2012|publisher=MTV News|date=June 19, 2006}}</ref> The song, like the majority of the album, was inspired by Aguilera's marriage and incorporates elements of early 20th-century soul, blues, and [[jazz]].<ref name=\"mtvnews\">{{cite news|last=Moss|first=Corey|title=Christina's New Split-Personality Album Is Mature And 'Dirrty'|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1529698/christinas-new-album-mature-dirrty.jhtml|access-date=April 25, 2012|publisher=MTV News|date=April 28, 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"ewb2b\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1225303,00.html|title=Back to Basics Review|first=Jody|last=Rosen|date=August 14, 2006|work=Entertainment Weekly|access-date=June 21, 2013}}</ref> It reached number six on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and has sold 1.7 million digital copies in the US as of 2014.<ref name=\"AguileraBBCharts\"/><ref name=\"AskBillboardCareer\"/> Its music video saw Aguilera debuting her new alter ego, Baby Jane, inspired by the thriller film ''[[What Ever Happened to Baby Jane? (1962 film)|What Ever Happened to Baby Jane?]]'' (1962).<ref name=\"mtvnews4\"/>\n\nThe album, titled ''[[Back to Basics (Christina Aguilera album)|Back to Basics]]'', was released in August 2006. Aguilera described the record, a [[double album]], as a \"throwback\" to jazz, blues, and soul music of the 1920s, 1930s, and 1940s that incorporates \"a modern twist.\"<ref name=\"B2BMusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1533622/christina-makes-her-comeback-twice-as-nice-by-expanding-basics-into-double-lp/|title=Christina Makes Her Comeback Twice As Nice By Expanding Basics Into Double LP|first1=Corey|last1=Moss|first2=Jeff|last2=Cornell|publisher=MTV News|date=June 6, 2006|access-date=October 22, 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141012115058/http://www.mtv.com/news/1533622/christina-makes-her-comeback-twice-as-nice-by-expanding-basics-into-double-lp/|archive-date=October 12, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> She was much inspired by works of such classic blues and soul singers as [[Otis Redding]], [[Millie Jackson]], and [[Nina Simone]] during the recording sessions.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JhYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA26|title=Old School|first=Melinda|last=Newman|work=Billboard|page=26|volume=118|issue=30|date=July 29, 2016|access-date=January 22, 2018}}</ref> ''Back to Basics'' received generally positive reviews from critics, who commented that the retro-oriented production complements Aguilera's vocals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/back-to-basics/christina-aguilera/critic-reviews|title=Critic Reviews for Back to Basics|website=Metacritic|access-date=January 22, 2018}}</ref> It debuted atop the ''Billboard'' 200 and has sold 1.7 million copies in the US.<ref name=\"AskBillboardCareer\"/> At the [[49th Annual Grammy Awards]] in February 2007, Aguilera won Best Female Pop Vocal Performance for \"Ain't No Other Man\", and performed \"[[It's a Man's Man's Man's World]]\" in tribute of the late [[James Brown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2007/SHOWBIZ/Music/02/11/grammy.awards/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021075431/http://edition.cnn.com/2007/SHOWBIZ/Music/02/11/grammy.awards/|title=A 'Nice' night for the Dixie Chicks|first=Todd|last=Leopold|publisher=CNN|date=February 12, 2007|archive-date=October 21, 2012}}</ref> ''Back to Basics'' was succeeded by two international top-ten singles: \"[[Hurt (Christina Aguilera song)|Hurt]]\" and \"[[Candyman (Christina Aguilera song)|Candyman]]\". Two other singles, \"[[Slow Down Baby]]\" and \"[[Oh Mother]]\", were released exclusively in Australia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sonybmg.com.au/news/details.do?newsId=20030829004728|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070904081540/http://sonybmg.com.au/news/details.do?newsId=20030829004728|title=Christina Aguilera Arrives In Town This Week!|publisher=Sony Music Australia|date=July 12, 2007|archive-date=September 4, 2007}}</ref> and Europe,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radioandrecords.com/formats/charts/euro/Switzerland.asp|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013015718/http://www.radioandrecords.com/formats/charts/euro/Switzerland.asp|title=Radio & Records: Swiss Top 20 Chart|work=Radio & Records|date=September 21, 2007|archive-date=October 13, 2007}}</ref> respectively. In support of ''Back to Basics'', Aguilera embarked on the [[Back to Basics Tour]], which ran from November 2006 to October 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1540564/christina-aguilera-reveals-european-tour-next-up-us-clubs/|title=Christina Aguilera Reveals European Tour \u2014 Next Up, U.S. Clubs|first=Jennifer|last=Vineyard|publisher=MTV News|date=September 11, 2006|access-date=October 23, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2008/11/145_5365.html|title=Christina Aguilera Shows Off Impressive Vocals|first=Cathy|last=Garcia|work=[[The Korea Times]]|date=June 25, 2007|access-date=June 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/aguilera-set-for-middle-east-debut|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810070829/http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/aguilera-set-for-middle-east-debut|title=Aguilera set for Middle East debut|work=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]|first=Melanie|last=Swan|location=Abu Dhabi|date=October 23, 2008|archive-date=August 10, 2011}}</ref> With US$48.1 million grossed, the tour was the highest-grossing solo female tour of 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1047044/the-police-score-top-grossing-tour-of-07|title=The Police Score Top-Grossing Tour Of '07|date=December 13, 2007|work=Billboard|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007050948/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1047044/the-police-score-top-grossing-tour-of-07|archive-date=October 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2008, Aguilera gave birth to her child with Bratman, a son.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1579535/christina-aguilera-gives-birth-to-baby-boy/|title=Christina Aguilera Gives Birth to Baby Boy|publisher=MTV News|date=January 13, 2008|access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> Later that year, she appeared in the [[Martin Scorsese]] documentary ''[[Shine a Light (film)|Shine a Light]]'' chronicling a two-day [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]] concert in New York City's [[Beacon Theatre (New York City)|Beacon Theatre]], in which Aguilera performs \"[[Live with Me]]\" alongside the band's lead vocalist [[Mick Jagger]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmreviews/3672481/Film-reviews-Shine-a-Light-and-21.html|title=Film reviews: Shine a Light and 21|first=David|last=Gritten|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=April 11, 2008|access-date=August 28, 2013}}</ref> In commemoration of a decade-long career in the music industry, Aguilera released a [[greatest hits album]] titled ''[[Keeps Gettin' Better: A Decade of Hits]]'' exclusively through [[Target Corporation|Target]] in November 2008, in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1044276/target-scores-aguilera-hits-album-exclusive|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140831165331/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1044276/target-scores-aguilera-hits-album-exclusive|title=Target Scores Aguilera Hits Album Exclusive|first=Katie|last=Hasty|work=Billboard|date=September 3, 2008|archive-date=August 31, 2014|url-status=dead|access-date=July 8, 2014}}</ref> In addition to previous singles, it includes four original [[electropop]]-oriented songs, two of which are remade versions of two previous singles.<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707142741/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/christina-aguilera/albumguide|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/christina-aguilera/albumguide|title=Christina Aguilera: Album Guide|work=Rolling Stone|archive-date=July 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1043616/hits-set-tees-up-next-christina-aguilera-album|title=Hits Set Tees Up Next Christina Aguilera Album|work=Billboard|date=October 31, 2008|first=Mariel|last=Conception|access-date=May 24, 2011}}</ref> Aguilera commented that the newly-recorded tracks' \"futurisic, robotic sound\" served as a preview for her follow-up studio album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1043491/christina-aguilera-better-and-better|title=Christina Aguilera: Better And 'Better'|first=Michael|last=Concepcion|date=November 14, 2008|access-date=January 24, 2018|work=Billboard}}</ref> ''Keeps Gettin' Better'' peaked at number nine on the ''Billboard'' 200, and its titular single \"[[Keeps Gettin' Better]]\" charted at number seven on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=\"AguileraBBCharts\"/> ''Billboard'' in 2009 recognized Aguilera as the 20th most successful artist of the 2000s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/266420/artists-of-the-decade|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140608034041/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/266419/artists-of-the-decade-page-two|title=Artists of the Decade|work=Billboard|archive-date=June 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2010\u20132011: ''Bionic'', ''Burlesque'', and ''The Voice''===\n[[File:Christina Aguilera (at premiere of \"To John With Love\", September 2010).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Aguilera at a [[Montblanc (company)|Montblanc]] event in 2010]]\nAguilera began work on her sixth studio album during pregnancy, when she frequently listened to [[electronic music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1641039/christina-aguilera-brings-new-songs-classic-hits-today-show.jhtml|title=Christina Aguilera Brings New Songs, Classic Hits To 'Today' Show|publisher=MTV News|first=James|last=Dinh|date=June 8, 2010|access-date=July 18, 2013}}</ref> The lead single from the album, \"[[Not Myself Tonight]]\", was released in March 2010.<ref name=\"releases\">{{cite web|url=http://www.clevelandleader.com/node/13444|title=New Christina Aguilera Album \"Bionic\" Out June 8th|first=Eugene|last=McCormick|newspaper=[[The Cleveland Leader]]|date=March 25, 2010|access-date=March 17, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203005849/http://www.clevelandleader.com/node/13444|archive-date=December 3, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Heavily influenced by electronic genres, the song signaled Aguilera's musical experiments on her forthcoming album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/christina-aguilera-hits-the-dance-floor-with-not-myself-tonight-20100331|title=Christina Aguilera Hits the Dance Floor With Not Myself Tonight|first=Daniel|last=Kreps|work=Rolling Stone|date=March 31, 2010|access-date=March 17, 2014}}</ref> It peaked at number 23 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=\"AguileraBBCharts\"/> The album, titled ''[[Bionic (Christina Aguilera album)|Bionic]]'', was released in June 2010. Categorized as a R&B-flavored [[futurepop]] album by critics,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2010/06/album-review-christina-aguileras-bionic.html|title=Album review: Christina Aguilera's 'Bionic'|date=June 7, 2010|first=Margaret|last=Wappler|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=August 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-christina-aguilera-bionic-rca-1991440.html|title=Album: Christina Aguilera, Bionic (RCA)|first=Andy|last=Gill|work=The Independent|date=June 4, 2010|access-date=August 8, 2014}}</ref> ''Bionic'' lyrically revolves around sexual themes while also discussing [[feminism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jun/06/christina-aguilera-bionic-cd-review|title=Bionic {{!}} CD Review {{!}} Music|work=[[The Observer]]|first=Kitty|last=Empire|date=June 6, 2010|access-date=August 10, 2014}}</ref> Critical reaction to the album was mixed; reviewers commended Aguilera's experimentation with new styles, but found it forced and unnatural.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/bionic/christina-aguilera/critic-reviews|title=Critic Reviews for Bionic|website=Metacritic|access-date=January 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/07/arts/music/07choice.html?pagewanted=1&sq=bionic&st=cse&scp=1|title=New CD's|first=Jon|last=Pareles|author-link=Jon Pareles|work=The New York Times|date=June 7, 2010|access-date=August 8, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jun/03/christina-aguilera-bionic-cd-review|title=Christina Aguilera \u2013 Bi-On-Ic {{!}} CD Review|work=The Guardian|date=June 3, 2010|first=Alexis|last=Petridis|access-date=August 8, 2014}}</ref> The album peaked at number three on the ''Billboard'' 200 and has sold 332,000 copies in the US as of 2019. <ref name=salesupdate2019>{{cite web|title=Ask Billboard: A Supersized Mailbag in Honor of Lil Nas X & Billy Ray Cyrus' Record Run Atop the Hot 100|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/business/chart-beat/8528273/lil-nas-x-billy-ray-cyrus-christina-aguilera-ask-billboard-mailbag |work=Billboard |first=Gary |last=Trust |date=August 24, 2019 |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |accessdate=August 24, 2019}}</ref> The album spawned one other international single, \"[[You Lost Me]]\". Two other singles from the album, \"[[Woohoo (Christina Aguilera song)|Woohoo]]\" featuring rapper [[Nicki Minaj]] and \"[[I Hate Boys]]\", were released in the US and Europe,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=69239|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6QujmdbEt?url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=69239|title=Airplay Archive|work=FMQB|archive-date=July 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/be/album/woohoo-feat-nicki-minaj-single/id374246489|title=Woohoo \u2013 Single\n|publisher=iTunes Store Belgium|access-date=July 8, 2014}}</ref> and Australia, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themusicnetwork.com/music-releases/singles/2010/06/28/issue-793/Christina-Aguilera--i-Hate-Boys/|title=Christina Aguilera \u2013 I Hate Boys \u2013 Issue 793|work=[[The Music Network]]|date=June 28, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406144504/http://www.themusicnetwork.com/music-releases/singles/2010/06/28/issue-793/Christina-Aguilera--i-Hate-Boys/|archive-date=April 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAguilera starred alongside [[Cher]] in the musical film ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/dec/11/cher-christina-aguilera-burlesque|title=Cher could teach Christina Aguilera a thing or two in Burlesque|work=The Guardian|first=John|last=Patterson|date=December 11, 2010|access-date=August 29, 2013}}</ref> Written and directed by [[Steve Antin]], the film was released in theaters in November 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2010-11-22-burlesque24_VA_N.htm|title=Director Antin had stars in his eyes when he cast 'Burlesque'|work=USA Today|first=Susan|last=Wloszczyna|date=November 23, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715104549/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2010-11-22-burlesque24_VA_N.htm|archive-date=July 15, 2014|url-status=dead|access-date=July 8, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera played Ali Rose, who quits her bar service job and moves to Los Angeles, where she aspires to be a performer in a [[American burlesque|burlesque]] club owned by Tess Scali (Cher). ''Burlesque'' grossed US$90 million in the box office<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=burlesque.htm|title=Burlesque (2010)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|access-date=August 25, 2013}}</ref> and received mixed reviews from critics, who found it [[clich\u00e9]]d but praised Aguilera's acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/burlesque|title='Burlesque' Reviews|website=Metacritic|access-date=May 2, 2014}}</ref> The film received a nomination for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] at the [[68th Golden Globe Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/env-2011-globes-nom-list-scorecard-html-htmlstory.html|title=2011 Golden Globes nominees & winners|work=Los Angeles Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715024803/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/env-2011-globes-nom-list-scorecard-html-htmlstory.html|archive-date=July 15, 2014|url-status=dead|access-date=July 8, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera recorded eight tracks for the film's ten-track [[Burlesque: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|accompanying soundtrack]], and Cher performed the other two.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|others=Christina Aguilera, Cher|title=Burlesque: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|year=2010|type=inlay cover|publisher=Screen Gems, Inc|page=iTunes Digital Booklet}}</ref> The soundtrack reached number 18 on the ''Billboard'' 200 and was certified gold by the RIAA.<ref name=\"RIAA\"/><ref name=\"AguileraBBCharts\"/>\n\nAt the [[Super Bowl XLV]] in February 2011, Aguilera omitted a few lines while performing the US national anthem.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1657367/christina-aguilera-super-bowl/|title=Christina Aguilera Apologizes For Super Bowl National Anthem Flub|first=Gil|last=Kaulfman|publisher=MTV News|date=July 2, 2011|access-date=February 23, 2015}}</ref> She apologized for the incident, saying: \"I got so caught up in the moment of the song that I lost my place.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/entertainment/music/2011/02/07/17179721-wenn-story.html|title=Aguilera sorry for Super Bowl fumble|work=[[Toronto Sun]]|date=December 12, 2010|access-date=February 7, 2011}}</ref> At the [[53rd Annual Grammy Awards]], she performed alongside [[Jennifer Hudson]], [[Martina McBride]], [[Yolanda Adams]], and [[Florence Welch]], in a segment that paid tribute to soul singer [[Aretha Franklin]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Semigran|first=Aly|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1657852/christina-aguilera-jennifer-hudson-aretha-franklin-grammy-tribute/|title=Christina Aguilera, Jennifer Hudson Belt Out Aretha Franklin Grammy Tribute|publisher=MTV News|date=February 13, 2011|access-date=December 4, 2012}}</ref> Aguilera finalized her divorce from Jordan Bratman, from whom she had been separated since September 2010, on April 15, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/celebrity/2011-04-15/christina-aguileras-divorce-finalized-today/|title=Christina Aguilera's Divorce Finalized Today|publisher=VH1|first=Liz|last=Black|date=April 15, 2011|access-date=February 23, 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224150211/http://www.vh1.com/celebrity/2011-04-15/christina-aguileras-divorce-finalized-today/|archive-date=February 24, 2015}}</ref> She concurrently started dating Matthew Rutler, an assistant on the set of ''Burlesque''.<ref name=\"EngagedNY\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/christina-aguilera-engaged-boyfriend-matt-rutler-article-1.1615176|title=Christina Aguilera engaged to boyfriend Matt Rutler, reveals massive ring on Twitter|work=New York Daily News|location=New York|first=Nina|last=Golgowski|date=February 14, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140215032645/http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/christina-aguilera-engaged-boyfriend-matt-rutler-article-1.1615176|archive-date=February 15, 2014}}</ref> From April 2011 to December 2012, Aguilera served as a coach on the first three seasons of the television competition series ''[[The Voice (American TV series)|The Voice]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6281721/christina-aguilera-gwen-stefani-shakira-voice-poll|title=Christina Aguilera, Gwen Stefani or Shakira|work=Billboard|date=October 14, 2014|first=Katie|last=Atkinson|access-date=February 23, 2015}}</ref> During the first season, Aguilera was featured on [[Maroon 5]]'s single \"[[Moves like Jagger]]\" upon the invitation of the group's lead vocalist and Aguilera's fellow ''The Voice'' coach [[Adam Levine]]. The single peaked atop the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and has sold seven million digital copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1172581/maroon-5-and-christina-aguileras-moves-like-jagger-struts-to-no-1-on|title=Maroon 5 and Christina Aguilera's 'Moves Like Jagger' Struts To No. 1 on Billboard Hot 100|work=Billboard|date=August 31, 2011|first=Gary|last=Trust|access-date=August 31, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/bruno-mars-claims-2-best-selling-digital-songs-of-2011/047866|title=Bruno Mars claims 2 best-selling digital songs of 2011|work=[[Music Week]]|date=January 23, 2012|access-date=March 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2012\u20132017: ''Lotus'', second child, and television projects===\n[[File:Christina Aguilera - Breakthrough Prize Scientists, 2014.jpg|thumb|Christina during a performance in 2014]]\nUpon the third season of ''The Voice'' in September 2012, Aguilera released \"[[Your Body (Christina Aguilera song)|Your Body]]\" as the lead single from her seventh studio album.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474983/christina-aguilera-billboard-cover-story?page=0%2C1|title=Christina Aguilera: Billboard Cover Story|work=Billboard|first=Andrew|last=Hampp|date=September 21, 2012|access-date=September 1, 2013}}</ref> The single charted on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 at number 34.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474916/maroon-5-still-tops-hot-100-psy-one-step-from-no-1|title=Maroon 5 Still Tops Hot 100, PSY One Step From No. 1|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=September 26, 2012|access-date=September 7, 2013}}</ref> The album, titled ''[[Lotus (Christina Aguilera album)|Lotus]]'', followed in November 2012. Aguilera described the record as a \"rebirth\" of herself after the personal struggles she had overcome.<ref name=\"CareerBiggest\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/list/474045/christina-aguileras-top-10-biggest-career-moments?page=0%2C2|title=Christina Aguilera's Top 10 Biggest Career Moments|work=Billboard|date=November 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140613130053/http://www.billboard.com/articles/list/474045/christina-aguileras-top-10-biggest-career-moments?page=0%2C2|archive-date=June 13, 2014|first=Jason|last=Lipshutz|url-status=dead|access-date=June 20, 2014}}</ref> Contemporary reviewers found the album generic and conventional, as opposed to Aguilera's previous experimental ventures.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Review: Lotus|journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|location=London|date=January 2013|issue=318|page=101}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Caramanica|first1=Jon|last2=Pareles|first2=Jon|author-link2=Jon Pareles|last3=Ratliff|first3=Ben|date=November 13, 2012|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/13/arts/music/albums-by-christina-aguilera-soundgarden-and-brian-eno.html?_r=0|title=Albums by Christina Aguilera, Soundgarden and Brian Eno|page=34|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=November 17, 2012}}</ref> ''Lotus'' peaked at number seven on the ''Billboard'' 200 and has sold 303,000 copies in the US as of 2019. <ref name=salesupdate2019>{{cite web|title=Ask Billboard: A Supersized Mailbag in Honor of Lil Nas X & Billy Ray Cyrus' Record Run Atop the Hot 100|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/business/chart-beat/8528273/lil-nas-x-billy-ray-cyrus-christina-aguilera-ask-billboard-mailbag |work=Billboard |first=Gary |last=Trust |date=August 24, 2019 |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |accessdate=August 24, 2019}}</ref> The album was supported by one other single, \"[[Just a Fool]]\" featuring Aguilera's fellow ''The Voice'' coach [[Blake Shelton]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/reality-check/474076/christina-aguilera-blake-shelton-unveil-just-a-fool-on-the|title=Christina Aguilera, Blake Shelton Unveil 'Just a Fool' on 'The Voice'|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|first=Jeff|last=Benjamin|date=November 20, 2012|access-date=June 18, 2013}}</ref> In December 2012, Aguilera was replaced by [[Shakira]] for the [[The Voice (U.S. season 4)|fourth season]] of ''The Voice''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474926/the-voice-locks-in-fourth-fifth-seasons-on-nbc|first=David|last=Greenwald|title='The Voice' Locks In Fourth, Fifth Seasons on NBC|work=Billboard|date=September 25, 2012|access-date=June 20, 2014}}</ref> She returned for the [[The Voice (U.S. season 5)|fifth season]] in September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/462458/the-voice-season-5-premiere-coaches-christina-aguilera-and-cee-lo-green-make-a-triumphant-return|title=The Voice Season 5 Premiere: Coaches Christina Aguilera and Cee Lo Green Make a Triumphant Return|first=Leanne|last=Aguilera|publisher=E!|date=September 23, 2013|access-date=June 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Aguilera scored three international top-ten singles. She was featured on rapper [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]]'s \"[[Feel This Moment]]\", which peaked at number eight on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and was certified platinum by the RIAA.<ref name=\"RIAA\"/><ref name=\"AguileraBBCharts\"/> She subsequently appeared on Mexican singer [[Alejandro Fern\u00e1ndez]]'s cover of [[Miguel Gallardo]]'s \"[[Hoy Tengo Ganas de Ti#Alejandro Fern\u00e1ndez version|Hoy Tengo Ganas de Ti]]\" (1976), which earned a diamond certification in Mexico.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amprofon.com.mx/certificaciones-amprofon.php?key=Alejandro+Fern%C3%A1ndez&action=Buscar&anio=&disquera=&tipoAlbum=&tipoCertificacion=|title=Certificaciones Amprofon|language=es|publisher=[[Asociaci\u00f3n Mexicana de Productores de Fonogramas y Videogramas]]|access-date=February 6, 2018|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20141022235531/http://www.amprofon.com.mx/certificaciones-amprofon.php?key=Alejandro+Fern%C3%A1ndez&action=Buscar&anio=&disquera=&tipoAlbum=&tipoCertificacion=|archive-date=October 22, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera collaborated with [[A Great Big World]] on the ballad \"[[Say Something (A Great Big World song)|Say Something]]\", which earned a six-time platinum certification from the RIAA<ref name=\"RIAA\"/> and won [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Duo/Group Performance|Best Pop Duo/Group Performance]] at the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/57th-annual-grammy-awards|title=57th Annual Grammy Awards|publisher=[[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]]|access-date=February 6, 2018}}</ref> Aguilera temporarily withdrew from ''The Voice'' for the [[The Voice (U.S. season 6)|sixth]] and [[The Voice (U.S. season 7)|seventh]] seasons, citing her desire to devote her time to her family. She was respectively replaced by Shakira and [[Gwen Stefani]] during the two seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/shakira-usher-return-voice-season-6-article-1.1551737|title=Shakira, Usher returning to 'The Voice' for Season 6|first=Zayda|last=Rivera|work=New York Daily News|date=December 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140906051505/http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/shakira-usher-return-voice-season-6-article-1.1551737|archive-date=September 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/christina-aguilera-gwen-stefani-the-voice-confirms-coach-2014294|title=Christina Aguilera Welcomes Gwen Stefani to The Voice, Confirms Singer's Role as Season 7 Coach|work=Us Weekly|date=April 29, 2014|access-date=February 23, 2015}}</ref> After her engagement to Matthew Rutler in February 2014 and the birth of their daughter in August,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-christina-aguilera-baby-girl-name-matthew-rutler-20140818-story.html|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=August 18, 2014|access-date=August 18, 2014|title=Christina Aguilera welcomes, names new baby girl with Matthew Rutler|first=Christie|last=D'Zurilla}}</ref> she returned for the [[The Voice (U.S. season 8)|eighth season]] in October.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/6281700/christina-aguilera-returning-the-voice-season-8|title=Goodbye, Gwen: Christina Aguilera Returning to 'The Voice'|date=October 14, 2014|work=Billboard|first=Joe|last=Lynch|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> Aguilera's one more season with ''The Voice'' was the [[The Voice (U.S. season 10)|tenth]], in which she won with her contestant [[Alisan Porter]] in May 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/alisan-porter-makes-christina-aguilera-first-winning-female-voice-coach/|title=Alisan Porter makes Christina Aguilera first winning female 'Voice' coach|publisher=CBS News|last=Park|first=Andrea|date=May 25, 2016|access-date=May 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAguilera played a recurring role as singer Jade St. John, a pop singer who tries to venture out to [[country music]], on the [[Nashville (season 3)|third season]] of [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s musical drama series ''[[Nashville (2012 TV series)|Nashville]]'' in April 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Berman|first1=Eliza|title=Watch Christina Aguilera Vamp It Up on a Sneak Peak From Nashville|work=Time|date=April 9, 2015|url=http://time.com/3816030/christina-aguilera-nashville/|access-date=May 1, 2015}}</ref> She and her partner Rutler served as executive producers for a music-based game show, ''Tracks'', which aired on [[Spike TV]] in March 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wagmeister|first1=Elizabeth|title=Christina Aguilera Producing Music Game Show for Spike TV|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/tracks-game-show-christina-aguilera-spike-tv-1201730419/|access-date=March 16, 2016|work=Variety|date=March 15, 2016}}</ref> Aguilera recorded a song titled \"[[Change (Christina Aguilera song)|Change]]\", which she dedicated to the victims of the [[2016 Orlando nightclub shooting]] as well as [[Christina Grimmie]], who was fatally shot in Orlando the day before the nightclub shooting. The proceedings were donated to the National Compassion Fund to benefit the victims' families.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/watch-christina-aguilera-belt-orlando-tribute-change-on-kimmel-20160624|title=Watch Christina Aguilera Belt Orlando Tribute 'Change' on 'Kimmel'|work=Rolling Stone|first=Ryan|last=Reed|date=June 24, 2016|access-date=February 6, 2018}}</ref> Her other works included recording a [[disco]] song titled \"[[Telepathy (Christina Aguilera song)|Telepathy]]\" featuring [[Nile Rodgers]] for the soundtrack of [[Netflix]] original series ''[[The Get Down]]'' (2016),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/08/11/christina-aguilera-telepathy/|title=Christina Aguilera's Telepathy: Xtina returns to the dance floor|first=Joey|last=Nolfl|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=August 11, 2016|access-date=February 6, 2018}}</ref> being a voice actress for ''[[The Emoji Movie]]'' (2017),<ref>{{cite news|last1=French|first1=Megan|last2=Blynn|first2=Jamie|title=Meet Christina Aguilera's 'Emoji Movie' Character Akiko Glitter: First Pic!|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/meet-christina-aguileras-emoji-movie-character-first-pic-w482253|access-date=May 15, 2017|work=Us Weekly|date=May 15, 2017}}</ref> and starring in the romantic science fiction film ''[[Zoe (film)|Zoe]]'' (2018).<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Christina Aguilera, Theo James, Rashida Jones Join Sci-Fi Romance 'Zoe'|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/christina-aguilera-theo-james-rashida-jones-romance-zoe-1202404532/|access-date=May 2, 2017|work=Variety|date=May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2018\u2013present: ''Liberation'' and The Xperience===\n[[File:Liberation Tour (31108487277).jpg|thumb|Christina Aguilera performing at the Pepsi Center on October 19, 2018 on her Liberation Tour]]\nAguilera started work on her new album in the summer of 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6457974/christina-aguilera-next-album-pharrell-williams|title=Christina Aguilera Talks Next Album, Working with Pharrell Williams on New Music|last=Lipshut|first=Jason|date=January 30, 2015|work=Billboard|access-date=May 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.papermag.com/christina-aguilera-transformation-2553214651.html|title=Christina Aguilera Is Back With a New Transformation|last1=Lodi|first1=Marie|date=March 26, 2018|work=[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]|access-date=May 6, 2018}}</ref> Its release was preceded by two singles: \"[[Accelerate (Christina Aguilera song)|Accelerate]]\" featuring [[Ty Dolla Sign]] and [[2 Chainz]] and \"[[Fall in Line]]\" featuring [[Demi Lovato]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/5264447/christina-aguileras-accelerate/|title=Christina Aguilera Is Back With a New Rap-Forward Single|date=May 3, 2018|work=Time|access-date=May 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-christina-aguileras-fall-in-line-with-demi-lovato-w520357|title=Hear Christina Aguilera's Empowering New Song 'Fall in Line' With Demi Lovato|last=Kreps|first=Daniel|date=May 16, 2018|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=May 19, 2018}}</ref> The album, titled ''[[Liberation (Christina Aguilera album)|Liberation]]'', was released in June 15, 2018 to favorable reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/liberation/christina-aguilera|title=Reviews for Liberation by Christina Aguilera|website=Metacritic|access-date=October 31, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/christina-aguileras-liberation-w521561|title=Review: Christina Aguilera Flexes Her Diva Power on the Excellent 'Liberation'|last=Spanos|first=Brittany|date=June 14, 2018|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/13/arts/music/christina-aguilera-liberation-review.html|title=Christina Aguilera Exults in Her Voice on \u2018Liberation\u2019|last=Pareles|first=Jon|date=June 13, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref> Aguilera heavily incorporated R&B and hip hop on the album to represent her desire for freedom from what she described as the \"churning hamster wheel\" that was ''The Voice''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/magazine-feature/8446904/christina-aguilera-new-album-liberation-interview-cover-story-2018|title=Christina Aguilera on 'Longing for Freedom' & Her Hip-Hop-Inspired Return to Music|last=Jones|first=Allie|date=May 3, 2018|work=Billboard|access-date=July 1, 2019}}</ref> ''Liberation'' debuted at number six on the ''Billboard'' 200 chart, becoming Aguilera's seventh US top-ten album.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8462423/5-seconds-of-summer-third-no-1-album-billboard-200-chart|title=5 Seconds of Summer Earn Third No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart With 'Youngblood'|last1=Caulfield|first1=Keith|date=June 24, 2018|work=Billboard|access-date=July 13, 2018}}</ref> At the [[61st Annual Grammy Awards]], \"Fall in Line\" was nominated for Best Pop Duo/Group Performance, and the album track \"[[Like I Do (Christina Aguilera song)|Like I Do]]\", which featured [[GoldLink]] was nominated for [[Best Rap/Sung Performance]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/61st-annual-grammy-awards|title=61st Annual GRAMMY Awards|date=December 6, 2018|publisher=National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences|access-date=December 14, 2018}}</ref> \n\nTo promote ''Liberation'', Aguilera embarked on a US tour, the [[Liberation Tour]], which ran from September to November 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8455203/christina-aguilera-liberation-tour-dates|title=Christina Aguilera Announces Liberation Tour, First Outing Since 2008|date=May 9, 2018|access-date=May 9, 2018|first=Kaufman|last=Gil|work=Billboard}}</ref> and a European tour, [[The X Tour (Christina Aguilera)|The X Tour]], which ran from July to December 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7714327/christina-aguilera-announces-the-x-tour?chrome=1|title=She's Coming, Europe! Christina Aguilera Announces 'The X Tour'|first=Mike|last=Nied|website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|date=March 4, 2019|access-date=June 29, 2019}}</ref> She also headlined [[The Xperience]], a 25-date concert residency at the [[Zappos Theater]] in [[Las Vegas]] beginning in May and concluding in March 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8495496/christina-aguilera-brings-the-xperience-to-las-vegas|title=Christina Aguilera Brings 'The Xperience' to Las Vegas|date=January 29, 2019|work=Billboard|first=Melinda|last=Sheckells}}</ref> In 2019, Aguilera received [[Disney Legend|The Disney Legends Awards]] for \"her remarkable contributions to the Disney legacy\".<ref>https://d23.com/2019-disney-legends/?disney2</ref> In October 2019, Aguilera released the song \"Haunted Heart\" from the soundtrack of the computer-animated ''[[The Addams Family (2019 film)|Addams Family]]'' film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/snoop-dogg-and-migos-share-new-song-for-the-addams-family-listen/|title=Snoop Dogg and Migos Share New Song for The Addams Family: Listen|website=Pitchfork|last=Moreland|first=Quinn|date=September 13, 2019|accessdate=September 14, 2019}}</ref>. On March 6, 2020, Aguilera released \"Loyal Brave True\" as a promotional single from the upcoming live action remake of ''[[Mulan (2020 film)|Mulan]]''<ref>cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/christina-aguilera-mulan-new-song-loyal-brave-true-964115/amp/|title=Christina Aguilera Returns to Her Disney Roots with New Song}}</ref>. She has also announced that she will release a re-recording of \"Reflection\" during her Xperience show.\n\n==Artistry==\n===Voice===\nAguilera is a [[soprano]],<ref name=\"GuardianSexual\">{{cite news|first=Hermione|last=Hoby|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jun/13/christina-aguilera-interview-bionic|title=Christina Aguilera: 'I'm a very sexual person by nature'|work=The Guardian|date=June 13, 2010|access-date=November 5, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"EverythingSinging\">{{Cite book|title=The Everything Singing Book with CD: From Mastering Breathing Techniques to Performing Live\u2014all You Need to Hit the Right Notes|last=Sheppard|first=Bettina|author-link=|year=2008|publisher=Everything Books|location=|isbn=|page=100|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=FQ4ItFJXHEwC&pg=PA100&lpg=PA100&dq=Christina+Aguilera+AND+soprano#v=onepage&q=Christina%20Aguilera%20AND%20soprano|access-date=November 18, 2017|df=mdy-all}}{{dead link|date=October 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2011/aug/26/home/la-hm-hotprop-christina-aguilera-20110826|title=Christina Aguilera sells Sunset Strip-area home|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=August 26, 2011|access-date=February 21, 2018|first=Lauren|last=Beale}}</ref> possessing a four-octave [[vocal range]] spanning from [[C (musical note)|C<sub>3</sub>]] to [[C\u266f (musical note)|C\u266f<sub>7</sub>]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Gayles|first=Contessa|title=10 Things You Didn't Know About 'The Voice' Coach and 'Dirrty' Pop Star Christina Aguilera|url=http://blog.music.aol.com/2011/05/24/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-voice-christina-aguilera/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110601042700/http://blog.music.aol.com/2011/05/24/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-voice-christina-aguilera|archive-date=June 1, 2011|date=May 24, 2011|publisher=[[AOL]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/105319/compare-vocal-ranges-of-worlds-greatest-singers/|title=This Interactive Chart Compares the Vocal Ranges of the World's Greatest Singers|first=Samantha|last=Grossman|date=May 20, 2014|access-date=July 21, 2014|work=Time}}</ref> Since the start of her career Aguilera's voice has been compared to that of [[Mariah Carey]] and [[Whitney Houston]].<ref name=\"NYTimesVoice\"/> [[David Browne (journalist)|David Browne]] writing for ''The New York Times'' noted that Aguilera's vocal performance was highly influenced by Carey and Houston, sharing that \"Aguilera has been one of the foremost practitioners of the overpowering, Category 5 vocal style known as [[melisma]]\", and \"Ms. Carey, Ms. Houston and Ms. Aguilera, to name its three main champions, are most associated with the period from the late '80s through the late '90s\".<ref name=\"NYTimesVoice\">{{cite news|last=Browne|first=David|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 24, 2010|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/26/arts/music/26browne.html|title=Trilling Songbirds Clip Their Wings|access-date=January 4, 2010}}</ref> A journal by Ann Powers for the ''Los Angeles Times'' said there are influences of [[Barbra Streisand]], [[Gladys Knight]] and [[Aretha Franklin]] on Aguilera's vocal style, opining that the \"Aguilera's Streisand-esque tendencies\" \"[help Aguilera] figure out how to become the 'great singer' she's been dubbed since she released her first single, the wise-beyond-its-years 'Genie in a Bottle', at 18\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Powers|first=Ann|work=Los Angeles Times|date=August 15, 2006|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2006/aug/15/entertainment/et-christina15|title=Old-school? Her?|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130301065054/http://articles.latimes.com/2006/aug/15/entertainment/et-christina15|archive-date=March 1, 2013}}</ref> [[Sasha Frere-Jones]] wrote in ''[[The New Yorker]]'', \"Aguilera doesn't need to reincarnate [[Sarah Vaughan]] to be a serious singer. She already is one, in the tradition of nineteen-nineties pop and R&B, skillfully deploying [[melisma]] for razzle-dazzle\".<ref name=\"NewYorker\">{{cite news|last=Frere-Jones|first=Sasha|title=Sex Symbols|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2006/09/04/sex-symbols|access-date=August 12, 2013|work=[[The New Yorker]]|date=September 4, 2006}}</ref> In 2003, Aguilera was placed fifth on MTV's \"Best Voices in Music Ever\" list,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ranker.com/list/mtv_s-best-voices-in-music-ever-v1/music-lover|title=MTV's Best Voices in Music Ever|work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|date=March 1, 2003|access-date=July 31, 2015}}</ref> while ranking atop both COVE and Latina magazine's best Pop and Latina vocalist of all time in 2004 and 2013, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://popdirt.com/christina-aguilera-named-best-vocalist-by-cove/33315/|title=Christina Aguilera Named Best Vocalist By Cove|publisher=Popdirt|date=October 5, 2004|access-date=July 31, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latina.com/entertainment/music/best-latin-singers-pop-stars-all-time|title=THE 50 BEST LATINO SINGERS OF ALL TIME!|work=Latina Magazine|date=February 8, 2013|access-date=July 31, 2015}}</ref> In a review for ''Liberation'', [[Jon Pareles]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' commented on Aguilera's vocal versatility: \"Nothing less than high drama suits Christina Aguilera's voice. She can be brassy, tearful, sultry, gritty, breathy, sweet or furious. She can belt and she can tease; she can aim a note as directly as a missile or turn its trajectory into an aerobatic spiral of leaping, quivering, scalloping melismas. Her voice is not an instrument for making modest statements; it's about peaks of self-affirmation, indescribable sensual pleasures, steely counterattacks and abysses of sorrow\".<ref name=\"liberationreview\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/13/arts/music/christina-aguilera-liberation-review.html|title=Christina Aguilera Exults in Her Voice on 'Liberation'|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 13, 2018|access-date=June 14, 2018|first=Jon|last=Parales}}</ref>\n\nAguilera has, however, been criticized for her excessive use of melisma and [[oversinging]] on songs and in concerts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-17039208|title=Whitney Houston and the art of melisma|first=Lauren|last=Everitt|work=BBC News|date=February 15, 2012|access-date=July 11, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"EWOver\">{{cite web|last=William|first=Chris|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=December 11, 2001|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,91277,00.html|title=Genie at Full Throttle|access-date=July 11, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"MTVOver\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1523040/the-scourge-of-american-idol-oversingers/|title=The Scourge Of 'American Idol': Oversingers|first=Corey|last=Moss|publisher=MTV News|date=February 2, 2006|access-date=July 11, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"SeattleOver\">{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/entertainment/2003633250_oversinging26.html|title=Wo-o-o, whoa: Stop oversinging!|first=Preston|last=Jones|work=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]|date=March 26, 2007|access-date=July 11, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fseattletimes.com%2Fhtml%2Fentertainment%2F2003633250_oversinging26.html&date=2013-02-02|archive-date=February 2, 2013}}</ref> John Eskow of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' named Aguilera a main proponent for \"oversouling\", described as the \"gratuitous and confected melisma\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Eskow|first=John|title=Christina Aguilera and the Hideous Cult of Oversouling|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/john-eskow/christina-aguilera-and-th_b_819979.html|access-date=December 5, 2012|work=HuffPost|date=February 8, 2011}}</ref> Lucy Davies, a writer for [[BBC Music]], opined that although Aguilera had \"a stunning voice\", she \"could be more varied, simply by cutting out some of the 'y-e-e-eeeh, woah yeh's'\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Davies|first1=Lucy|title=Christina Aguilera Back to Basics Review|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/4g25|publisher=[[BBC Music]]|access-date=June 15, 2014|date=August 14, 2006}}</ref> Longtime producer [[Linda Perry]], who wrote the song \"Beautiful\", revealed about the recording sessions with Aguilera, \"I tried to keep it straight. I told her to get rid of the finger waves. Every time she'd start going into 'hoo-ha', I'd stop the tape. I'm like, 'You're doing it again'\". Perry ended up using the song's first take adding, \"She had a hard time accepting that as the final track. She's a perfectionist. She knows her voice really well, and she knows what's going on. She can hear things that nobody else would catch.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Hiatt|first=Brian|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=October 29, 2002|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,385297_2,00.html|title='Dirrty' Work (page 2)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070619120647/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0%2C%2C385297_2%2C00.html|archive-date=June 19, 2007|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> An editor from ''Entertainment Weekly'', Chris Willman, stated that the oversinging on Aguilera's albums was inspired by Carey, writing that \"the Mariah venerators don't get away with it so easily. Aguilera, for one thing, has a slightly nasal tone that really only becomes obvious when she's overselling a song\".<ref name=\"EWOver\"/>\n\n===Influences===\n[[File:Etta James 2006.jpg|thumb|upright|Aguilera cites [[Etta James]] ''(pictured)'' as her main influence]]\nAguilera has credited blues singer [[Etta James]] as her main influence and inspiration, elaborating, \"Etta is my all-time favorite singer. I've said it for the last seven years \u2013 since I had my first debut record out \u2013 in every interview\".<ref name=\"EttaJames\">{{cite news|last=Vineyard|first=Jennifer|date=June 28, 2006|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1535359/christina-aguilera-can-die-happy-shes-bonded-with-bad-girl-idol-etta-james/|title=Christina Aguilera Can Die Happy \u2013 She's Bonded With 'Bad Girl' Idol Etta James|publisher=MTV News|access-date=June 12, 2014}}</ref> Following James' death in 2012, Aguilera was asked to perform \"[[At Last]]\" at James' funeral.<ref>{{cite news|last=Martinez|first=Michael|title=Etta James remembered as an authentic voice at funeral|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/01/28/showbiz/etta-james-funeral/index.html|publisher=CNN|access-date=January 29, 2012|date=January 28, 2012}}</ref> Prior to the performance, Aguilera revealed, \"There's a line in this song that says 'I found a dream that I could speak to.' And for me that dream, all my life, has been Etta James\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Farley|first=Christopher|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=January 29, 2012|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2012/01/29/christina-aguilera-sings-at-last-at-etta-james-funeral/|title=Christina Aguilera Sings 'At Last' at Etta James Funeral|access-date=June 12, 2014}}</ref> Other classic artists, including [[Billie Holiday]], [[Otis Redding]], [[Aretha Franklin]], [[Nina Simone]], and [[Ella Fitzgerald]], are also Aguilera's major influences; her fifth studio album ''Back to Basics'' is inspired by vintage jazz, blues and soul music records by them.<ref>{{cite news|last=Moss|first=Corey|title=Christina's New Split-Personality Album Is Mature And 'Dirrty'|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1529698/christinas-new-split-personality-album-is-mature-and-dirrty/|access-date=June 15, 2014|publisher=MTV News|date=April 27, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Vineyard|first1=Jennifer|last2=Norris|first2=John|last3=Edwards|first3=Luc|title=Christina Aguilera's Old Soul|url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/aguilera_christina/news_feature_080906/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140805022136/http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/aguilera_christina/news_feature_080906/|archive-date=August 5, 2014|access-date=June 15, 2014|publisher=MTV News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1531567/for-the-record-quick-news-on-christina-aguilera-jennifer-lopez-snoop-dogg-jessica-simpson-bjork-more/|title=For The Record: Quick News On Christina Aguilera, Jennifer Lopez, Snoop Dogg, Jessica Simpson, Bjork & More|publisher=MTV News|date=May 11, 2006|access-date=February 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAguilera mentions [[Whitney Houston]] as another influence,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stylist.co.uk/home/whitney-houston-singers-she-inspired|work=[[Stylist (magazine)|Stylist]]|title=Whitney Houston's prot\u00e9g\u00e9es: Christina Aguilera|access-date=June 18, 2014|first=Anna|last=Pollitt|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714185522/http://www.stylist.co.uk/home/whitney-houston-singers-she-inspired|archive-date=July 14, 2014}}</ref> having performed many of her songs in her early years during talent shows.<ref name=\"WashingtonPost\"/> She also cites [[Mariah Carey]] and [[Celine Dion]] as an inspiration, and covered the latter's songs: \"These Are the Special Times\" on ''[[My Kind of Christmas]]'', and \"[[The Prayer (Celine Dion and Andrea Bocelli song)|The Prayer]]\" on the NBC reality singing competition ''[[The Voice (U.S. season 2)|The Voice]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Matter of Time Christina Aguilera Says She'll Leave The Pack, Including Britney Spears in the Dust|work=[[Hartford Courant]]|last=Catlin|first=Roger|page=10|date=August 31, 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UoINJdqVsdw|title=Christina Aguilera talks about Celine Dion|via=YouTube|date=April 26, 2013|access-date=April 18, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera's debut album producer Ron Harris revealed that Aguilera during her recording sessions for ''[[Christina Aguilera (album)|Christina Aguilera]]'' would constantly listen to [[Brandy Norwood|Brandy]]'s music, studying and trying to replicate her adlibs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bS2ncjBBC2k|title=Film & Music Industry Forum - Ron Harris 3-7-16|last=Loyola University Film and Music Industry Studies|date=May 3, 2016|access-date=June 21, 2018|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> According to author Pier Dominguez of the book ''Christina Aguilera: A Star Is Made'', Aguilera stated that Carey and her debut single, \"[[Vision of Love]]\" (1990), had the biggest influence on her vocal style.<ref>{{harvnb|Dominguez|2003|page=134}}</ref> Aguilera points out the musical film ''[[The Sound of Music (film)|The Sound of Music]]'' and its lead actress, [[Julie Andrews]], as her first inspiration for singing and performing.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rosen|first=Craig|url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/story/12058962|title=Christina Aguilera Climbs Every Mountain For 'My Kind Of Christmas'|publisher=Yahoo! Music|date=September 29, 2000|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524205307/http://music.yahoo.com/read/story/12058962|archive-date=May 24, 2011}}</ref> At the age of six, the film helped Aguilera cope with her violent childhood, \"Bad things happened in my home; there was violence. ''The Sound of Music'' looked like a form of release.\"<ref name=\"WMagazine\"/> Aguilera credits [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] and [[Janet Jackson]] as two biggest inspirations for her image, \"for being re-inventive and being brave as strong females, to explore whatever, even if they do get bad press. It's just like they were fearless.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sculley|first=Alan|title=What Christina wants|newspaper=[[The Patriot Ledger]]|page=17|date=September 8, 2000}}</ref> During the promotion of ''Back to Basics'', her image was also inspired by the \"Golden age of Hollywood\" actresses including [[Marlene Dietrich]], [[Marilyn Monroe]], [[Carole Lombard]], [[Greta Garbo]] and [[Veronica Lake]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Moss|first=Corey|title=Christina Channels Marilyn Monroe For Intimate Album Cover|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1535431/christina-channels-marilyn-monroe-for-intimate-album-cover/|access-date=June 15, 2014|publisher=MTV News|date=June 29, 2006}}</ref> Aguilera is also inspired by her ''Burlesque'' co-star, [[Cher]]: \"I have always had tremendous respect for her. She is a woman who did everything before anyone else did it. She is an icon and she inspired me through some of my career. We've had similar costumes too!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/offbeat/articles/2010/02/08/20100208christina-aguilera.html|title=Christina Aguilera inspired by Cher|work=[[The Arizona Republic]]|date=February 8, 2010|access-date=July 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Musical style and themes===\n[[File:Understand - Christina Aguilera.jpg|thumb|upright|Aguilera performing during her [[Back to Basics Tour]] in 2006]]\nAguilera frequently blends elements of pop, [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[dance-pop]] and [[soul music|soul]] music into her projects,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/07/arts/music/07choice.html|title=New CDs|first=Jon|last=Pareles|author-link=Jon Pareles|newspaper=The New York Times|date=June 6, 2010|access-date=June 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dallasobserver.com/2004-03-04/music/ladies-night-out-tour/|title=Ladies Night Out Tour|work=[[Dallas Observer]]|quote=With all the attention lavished on female R&B stars like [...] Christina Aguilera|date=March 4, 2004|first=Mikael|last=Wood|access-date=February 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Genie out of a bottle|first=Peter|last=Holder|first2=Jo|last2=Casamento|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|location=Australia|page=16|date=March 10, 2000}}</ref> and her records typically include a combination of ballads and uptempo tracks.<ref name=\"NYTimesShrunk\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/17/arts/music/17sann.html|title=Honey They've Shrunk the Pop Stars (but Christina Aguilera Fights On)|first=Kelefa|last=Sanneh|work=The New York Times|date=August 17, 2006|access-date=July 9, 2014}}</ref> ''Christina Aguilera'' (1999) prominently displayed [[teen pop]] and dance-pop music,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/christina-aguilera-mw0000244313|title=Christina Aguilera \u2013 Christina Aguilera|first=Stephen Thomas|last=Erlewine|website=AllMusic|access-date=July 9, 2014}}</ref> while ''Mi Reflejo'' (2000) takes inspiration from [[Latin music (genre)|Latin music]].<ref name=\"MiReflejoNYPost\">{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2000/09/12/christinas-a-winner-in-spanish-too/|title=Christina's a winner in Spanish, too|last=Aquilante|first=Dan|newspaper=New York Post|date=September 12, 2000|access-date=May 31, 2013}}</ref> Her first Christmas album, ''My Kind of Christmas'', combines covers of Christmas standards and several original dance-pop tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/my-kind-of-christmas-mw0000100386|title=My Kind of Christmas by Christina Aguilera on AllMusic|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012025651/http://www.allmusic.com/album/my-kind-of-christmas-mw0000100386|archive-date=October 12, 2012|access-date=September 13, 2012|website=AllMusic|first=Stephen|last=Erlewine|url-status=dead}}</ref> Aiming for musical diversity and artistic growth, Aguilera worked with R&B, rock, [[hip hop music|hip hop]], and Latin music for ''Stripped'' (2002).<ref name=\"NotYourPuppet\"/><ref name=\"Stripped\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,384149~4~0~stripped,00.html|title=Stripped Review|last=Browne|first=David|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=November 1, 2002|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012121321/http://ew.com/ew/article/0%2C%2C384149~4~0~stripped%2C00.html|archive-date=October 12, 2007|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> David Browne from ''Entertainment Weekly'' credited the release with distancing Aguilera from her pop contemporaries.<ref name=\"Stripped\"/> Aguilera leaned towards R&B, [[blues]], jazz, and [[Soul music|soul]] on ''Back to Basics'' (2006).<ref name=\"B2BMusic\"/><ref name=\"LATimes\">{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2007/mar/07/entertainment/et-aguilera7|title=Props mistress|last=Powers|first=Ann|work=Los Angeles Times|date=March 7, 2007|access-date=May 28, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"TheObserver\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2006/aug/13/shopping.christinaaguilera|title=Christina Aguilera, Back to Basics|first=Paul|last=Flynn|newspaper=[[The Observer]]|date=August 12, 2006|access-date=May 3, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn contrast, ''Bionic'' (2010) sees significant use from futuristic [[electronic music]], described as an [[electropop]] album.<ref name=\"ElectronicBionic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1641039/christina-aguilera-brings-new-songs-classic-hits-to-today-show/|title=Christina Aguilera Brings New Songs, Classic Hits To 'Today' Show|first=James|last=Dinh|publisher=MTV News|date=June 8, 2010|access-date=July 8, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/bionic-mw0001989957|title=Bionic \u2013 Christina Aguilera {{!}} Overview|website=[[AllMusic]]|first=Thomas|last=Stephen Erlewine|author-link=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|access-date=August 8, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120711102448/http://www.allmusic.com/album/bionic-mw0001989957|archive-date=July 11, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D05E6D71230F934A35752C1A9669D8B63|title=For Gays, New Songs of Survival (page 2)|work=[[The New York Times]]|first=Alex|last=Hagwood|date=November 7, 2010|access-date=August 16, 2014}}</ref> The soundtrack for her 2010 feature film ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'' (2010) was influenced by ''Cabaret'', and featured several established songs that were redone as dance numbers in a fashion similar to ''Moulin Rouge!'' (2001).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2007/film/news/screen-gems-enlists-antin-for-burlesque-1117974104/|title=Screen Gems enlists Antin for 'Burlesque'|work=Variety|date=October 15, 2007|first=Michael|last=Fleming|access-date=February 23, 2015}}</ref> Aguilera partnered with mainstream producers including [[Shellback (producer)|Shellback]] and [[Max Martin]] during production of ''Lotus'' (2012); when discussing her interactions with the latter, she commented that \"He's known about me but we haven't crossed paths,\" adding \"Those records were the kind I wanted to stray apart from. If you look at what I did in the past (after my debut), I always try to do things that will challenge me and challenge the listener, too.\"<ref name=\"Billboard Cover\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474983/christina-aguilera-billboard-cover-story|title=Christina Aguilera: Billboard Cover Story|last=Hampp|first=Andrew|work=Billboard|date=September 21, 2012|access-date=July 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAguilera stated that she feels a sense of responsibility to reference portions of her personal life so that \"people that can relate might not feel as alone in the circumstance.\" Many of her works consequently discuss love; she has also co-written two tracks which dealt with the domestic abuse throughout her childhood.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/57547/basic-instinct|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114034718/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/57547/basic-instinct|title='Basic' Instinct|work=Billboard|date=August 13, 2006|archive-date=January 14, 2009}}</ref> Aguilera has frequently mentioned [[feminism]] in her music; she has expressed her belief that sexuality is \"very empowering\", and has commented that \"If I want to be sexual, it's for my own appreciation and enjoyment! That's why I like to talk about the fact that sometimes I am attracted to women. I appreciate their femininity and beauty.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20393540,00.html|title=Christina Aguilera: Why I'm Sometimes Attracted to Women|last=Oh|first=Eunice|work=People|date=June 11, 2010|access-date=May 11, 2013}}</ref> She has alluded to her physical attractions to women in other interviews as well.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stein|first1=Joshua David|title=Christina Aguilera Reclaims The Fame|url=https://www.out.com/entertainment/music/2010/05/16/christina-aguilera-reclaims-fame|work=Out Magazine|publisher=Here Publishing Inc.|date=May 16, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bendix|first1=Trish|title=Christina Aguilera: What she's said about her sexuality|url=http://www.afterellen.com/people/80238-christina-aguilera-what-shes-said-about-her-sexuality|work=After Ellen|publisher=Evolve Media LLC|date=October 15, 2010|quote=Two women are way sexier than two men in bed. We have a better feel for our bodies. I love experimenting with my sexuality. [...] If that means girls then so be it. It would be wrong to hide this side of my personality. [...] I don't get to kiss all the girls and the boys, but my husband knows that I get into girls. I think it's fun to be open and play. ... I definitely love women. I think they're more attractive to the naked eye.}}</ref> Her \"Can't Hold Us Down\" from ''Stripped'' denounces gender-related [[double standard]]s, in which men are applauded for their sexual behaviors, while women who behave in a similar fashion are disdained.<ref>{{harvnb|Railton|Watson|2011|page=88}}</ref> The main theme of ''Bionic'' was also about woman empowerment; Hermione Hoby from ''[[The Guardian]]'' opined that \"she incites more of a sisterly spirit of collaboration, including riot grrrl feminists [[Le Tigre]]. Aguilera's not shy of the odd feministic declaration herself.\"<ref name=\"GuardianSexual\"/> In regards to production, Aguilera has often verbalized her preference of working with more \"obscure\" collaborators, and noted that she is not necessarily inclined to contact \"the No.1 chart-toppers in music\" because of their popular demand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/58465/new-aguilera-album-set-for-august|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114030752/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/58465/new-aguilera-album-set-for-august|title=New Aguilera Album Set For August|last=Cohen|first=Jonathan|work=Billboard|date=June 11, 2006|archive-date=January 14, 2009}}</ref> ''The New York Times''{{'}} Kelefa Sanneh described her decision to work with [[DJ Premier]] on ''Back to Basics'' as \"a decision to snub some of the big-name producers on whom pop stars often rely.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/17/arts/music/17sann.html|title=Honey They've Shrunk the Pop Stars|last=Sanneh|first=Kelefa|newspaper=The New York Times|date=August 17, 2006|access-date=July 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Image==\nAguilera has reinvented her public image on numerous occasions throughout her career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.chron.com//handstamp/2007/02/christina-aguilera-claims-her-pop-throne/|title=Christina Aguilera claims her pop throne|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|first=Joey|last=Guerra|date=February 20, 2007|access-date=July 17, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6WEW0UaKu?url=http://blog.chron.com//newswatch/2011/04/ktru-station-off-air-but-still-broadcasting-online/|archive-date=February 10, 2015}}</ref> In the later 1990s, her then-manager Steve Kurtz marketed her as a bubblegum pop entertainer to capitalize on the genre's financial lure,<ref name=\"USAToday\"/> which earned her recognition as a [[teen idol]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/the_greatest/episode.jhtml?episodeID=67297|title=50 Greatest Teen Idols|publisher=VH1|access-date=July 19, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120209143618/http://www.vh1.com/shows/the_greatest/episode.jhtml?episodeID=67297|archive-date=February 9, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Aguilera introduced her [[alter ego]] \"Xtina\" during 2002 and 2003, which presented an increasingly provocative persona.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/10/29/1035683410806.html|title=Aguilera sheds teen pop image, alongside clothes|date=October 30, 2002|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=July 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.virginmedia.com/music/features/alter-egos.php?page=6|title=Christina Aguilera=Xtina|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223111841/http://www.virginmedia.com/music/features/alter-egos.php?page=6|archive-date=February 23, 2015|url-status=dead|access-date=February 23, 2015}}</ref> During this time, she dyed her hair black, debuted several piercings, and participated in several nude pictorials for publications.<ref name=\"CareerBiggest\"/> In 2004, Aguilera embraced a more \"mature\" image with retro-styled hair and makeup, which was inspired by classic movie stars including Marilyn Monroe, [[Marlene Dietrich]] and [[Mary Pickford]].<ref name=\"HelloMag\"/> This reinvention was named \"Baby Jane\" in 2006, an alter ego which was taken from the 1962 film ''[[What Ever Happened to Baby Jane? (1962 film)|What Ever Happened to Baby Jane?]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1539161/christina-clip-got-a-boost-from-outkast-role-playing-dancers-vmas-behind-the-camera/|title=Christina Clip Got A Boost From Outkast, Role-Playing Dancers|publisher=MTV News|first=Jennifer|last=Vineyard|date=August 23, 2006|access-date=June 23, 2013}}</ref> Aguilera received widespread criticism over her curvy figure from gaining weight in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/christina-aguilera-fat-girl-article-1.1171905|title=Christina Aguilera on her curvy, controversial figure: 'I got tired of being a skinny, white girl'|first=Joyce|last=Chen|work=Daily News|location=New York|date=October 1, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014134839/http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/christina-aguilera-fat-girl-article-1.1171905|archive-date=October 14, 2014}}</ref> She later received favorable media attention after a significant weight loss in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/christina-aguilera-weight-loss-how-did-she-do-it-1411294|title=Christina Aguilera Weight Loss: How Did She Do It?|work=[[International Business Times]]|first=Amethyst|last=Tate|date=September 26, 2013|access-date=July 19, 2014}}</ref> In 2018, Aguilera appeared bare-faced without makeup and [[photo manipulation|retouching]] on the cover of ''[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]'' magazine and received widespread praise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisinsider.com/christina-aguilera-no-makeup-paper-magazine-cover-shaming-2018-3|title=People are praising Christina Aguilera for her makeup-free photoshoots|date=March 27, 2018|work=INSIDER}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/26/entertainment/christina-aguilera-no-makeup-paper-magazine/index.html|title=Christina Aguilera goes makeup free for Paper|date=March 27, 2018|publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Aguilera Madame Tussauds.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Wax figure of Aguilera at [[Madame Tussauds]] in London]]\nAguilera is considered a pop icon,<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/04/02/idUS169214+02-Apr-2012+PRN20120402|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6NCNMPoOJ?url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/04/02/idUS169214+02-Apr-2012+PRN20120402|title=Superstar Songstress Britney Spears Will Battle Fellow Pop Princess Christina Aguilera This Week in the Championship Round of the Celebrity Bowling Hall of Fame Tournament|agency=Reuters|date=April 2, 2012|archive-date=February 7, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> and has frequently garnered comparisons to Britney Spears.<ref name=\"VirginMedia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.virginmedia.com/music/features/christina-aguilera-v-britney-spears.php|title=Christina Aguilera v Britney Spears: Who's the best popstar?|first=Matthew|last=Horton|date=August 11, 2012|access-date=July 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"EWCompare\">{{cite web|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2011/08/16/britney-spears-christina-aguilera-showdown/|title=Britney Spears vs. Christina Aguilera: Who's the greater turn-of-the-millennium pop diva?|first=Melissa|last=Maerz|date=August 16, 2013|work=Entertainment Weekly|access-date=July 19, 2014}}</ref> David Browne of ''Entertainment Weekly'' said that Aguilera is \"too eager not to offend\" in her mild-mannered music, making her a \"good girl pretending to be bad\", and also said that Spears' \"artificial-sweetener voice\" was a welcome change of pace from Aguilera's \"numbing vocal gymnastics\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,64697,00.html|title=Oops!... I Did It Again Review|first=David|last=Browne|work=Entertainment Weekly|access-date=July 17, 2009|date=May 19, 2000}}</ref> Matthew Horton from [[Virgin Media]] suggested that Aguilera was a more impressive performer than Spears despite her lower sales figures.<ref name=\"VirginMedia\"/> Aguilera has also been regarded as a [[sex symbol]].<ref name=\"NewYorker\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Sanneh|first=Kelefa|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/08/arts/the-new-season-music-idol-returns-her-image-remade.html|title=The New Season/Music Idol Returns|work=The New York Times|date=February 13, 2012|access-date=May 13, 2013}}</ref> A 2003 issue of ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]'' magazine that she covered became its best-selling issue;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maxim.com/girls-of-maxim/christina-aguilera|title=Christina Aguilera|work=Maxim|date=April 24, 2007|access-date=July 19, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301161931/http://www.maxim.com/girls-of-maxim/christina-aguilera|archive-date=March 1, 2012}}</ref> Aguilera was named \"Sexiest Woman of the Year\" by its subscribers later that year,<ref name=\"Maxim\">{{cite web|url=http://www.maxim.com/hot-100/2003-hot-100|title=2003 Hot 100 \u2013 Christina Aguilera {{!}} Maxim|work=[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]|date=May 1, 2003|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301161931/http://www.maxim.com/girls-of-maxim/christina-aguilera|archive-date=March 1, 2012}}</ref> and also earned the magazine its best-selling issue after posing on the cover that year.<ref>{{cite news|title=MAXIM Magazine Unveils the 'Hot 100' for 2003|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/maxim-magazine-unveils-the-hot-100-for-2003-55695342.html|access-date=February 3, 2017|agency=PR Newswire|date=May 16, 2003}}</ref> Additionally recognized as a gay icon,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1458472/christina-gwen-stefani-dita-von-teese-help-bring-back-burlesque/|title=Christina, Gwen Stefani, Dita Von Teese Help Bring Back Burlesque|last=Edwards|first=Tanya|publisher=MTV News|date=November 4, 2004|access-date=October 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/arts-entertainment/music/2012/11/28/christina-aguilera-says-lgbt-fans-held-her-when-she-could-not|title=Christina Aguilera Says LGBT Fans Held Her Up When She Couldn't Stand|first=Diane|last=Anderson-Minshall|work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|date=November 28, 2012|access-date=July 19, 2014}}</ref> she was the first honoree on [[The Abbey (club)|The Abbey]]'s Gay Walk of Fame for her contributions to the [[LGBT]] community.<ref name=\"Abbey\">{{cite web|last=Bain|first=Becky|url=http://idolator.com/5832331/christina-aguilera-the-abbey-gay-walk-of-fame|title=Christina Aguilera Immortalized On Gay Walk Of Fame|publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|access-date=May 13, 2013}}</ref> The music video for \"Beautiful\" earned Aguilera a [[14th GLAAD Media Awards|GLAAD Media Award]] for its positive portrayal of the LGBT community.<ref name=\"GLAAD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.glaad.org/media/release_detail.php?id=3359|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050418084316/http://www.glaad.org/media/release_detail.php?id=3359|title=Eric McCormack, Todd Haynes, Christina Aguilera, The Hours, Six Feet Under Honored at 14th Annual GLAAD Media Awards Presented by Absolut Vodka in Los Angeles|publisher=GLAAD|date=April 26, 2003|archive-date=April 18, 2005}}</ref>\n\nFashion has also been a part of Aguilera's music career and image.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/photos/426310/christina-aguileras-fashion-evolution?i=43845|title=Christina Aguilera's Fashion Evolution|work=Billboard|access-date=July 25, 2014}}</ref> She has frequently worn clothes designed by [[Roberto Cavalli]], [[John Galliano]], [[Marc Jacobs]], and [[Alexander McQueen]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Alexander|first=Hilary|date=July 7, 2005|work=The Daily Telegraph|url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/article/TMG3342005/Galliano-celebrates-100-years-of-Dior-with-his-own-new-look.html|title=Galliano celebrates 100 years of Dior with his own 'new look'|access-date=November 20, 2009|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108212736/http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/article/TMG3342005/Galliano-celebrates-100-years-of-Dior-with-his-own-new-look.html|archive-date=January 8, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Morley-Cartner|first=Jess|date=June 4, 2004|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2004/jun/04/jesscartnermorleyonfashion.arts|title=The old black McQueen in London for charity|access-date=November 20, 2009}}</ref> During the Back to Basics Tour in 2006, Aguilera performed in a stole made of fur designed by Roberto Cavalli, unaware that it was made from real fur of a white fox. After receiving a video about the treatment of foxes from [[PETA]] vice president [[Dan Mathews]], Aguilera replaced it with a faux-fur stole, further stating that she was \"very upset\" because she \"only ever wears fake fur\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peta.org/blog/christina-aguileras-costume-change/|title=Christina Aguilera Costume Change|publisher=[[PETA]]|date=December 12, 2006|access-date=July 25, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera's costumes from ''Burlesque'' were featured in the [[Fashion Institute of Design & Merchandising]]'s Art of Motion Picture Costume Design exhibition.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://travel.usatoday.com/destinations/story/2011/02/Oscar-nominated-fashions-on-display-at-LA-museum/43906488/1|title=Oscar-nominated fashions on display at L.A. museum|last=Cohen|first=Sandy|newspaper=USA Today|date=February 20, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140906051939/http://travel.usatoday.com/destinations/story/2011/02/Oscar-nominated-fashions-on-display-at-LA-museum/43906488/1|archive-date=September 6, 2014}}</ref> Wax figures of Aguilera are located at [[Madame Tussauds]] wax museums in London and New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.madametussaudswaxmuseum.com/branches/madame-tussauds-london.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121205062908/http://www.madametussaudswaxmuseum.com/branches/madame-tussauds-london.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 5, 2012|title=Madame Tussauds London|publisher=Madame Tussauds|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://starpittsburgh.cbslocal.com/photo-galleries/2011/10/14/watching-christina-aguilera-grow-xtina-through-the-years/justin-christina-wax-figures-arrive-at-madame-tussauds-to-open-club-mtny/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402103020/http://starpittsburgh.cbslocal.com/photo-galleries/2011/10/14/watching-christina-aguilera-grow-xtina-through-the-years/justin-christina-wax-figures-arrive-at-madame-tussauds-to-open-club-mtny/|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 2, 2015|title=Justin & Christina Wax Figures Arrive At Madame Tussauds To Open Club MTNY|publisher=[[WBZZ-HD2]]|date=October 14, 2011|access-date=August 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n{{see also|List of awards and nominations received by Christina Aguilera}}\n[[File:Xtina star walk of fame.jpg|right|160px|thumb|Aguilera's star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]], which she received in 2010]]\nAs of 2018, Aguilera had sold over 75 million albums and singles worldwide.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://vaaju.com/romaniaeng/christina-aguilera-topless-for-the-cover-of-her-new-album-photo/|title=Christina Aguilera, topless for the cover of her new album|work=[[Mediafax]]|date=June 21, 2018|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> Aguilera's works have earned her numerous [[List of awards and nominations received by Christina Aguilera|awards and accolades]], including five [[Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/artist/christina-aguilera|title=Christina Aguilera Artist|publisher=[[Grammy Awards]]|access-date=August 3, 2014}}</ref> Various artists have noted that they were inspired by Aguilera, including [[Ariana Grande]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/16191065723764736|title=Ariana Grande wishes Christina Aguilera a \"Happy Birthday|date=December 18, 2010|work=Twitter}}{{Primary source inline|date=January 2019}}</ref> [[Tinashe]],<ref name=\"TinasheQ&A\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6386058/tinashe-video-interview-aquarius|title=Tinashe On Bringing Females Into the Mainstream: 'There's Definitely Room For More|last=Lipshutz|first=Jason|date=December 8, 2014|work=Billboard|access-date=July 8, 2015}}</ref> [[Lady Gaga]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/491950/christina-aguilera-and-lady-gaga-perform-on-the-voice-effectively-putting-feud-rumors-to-rest|title=Christina Aguilera and Lady Gaga Perform on The Voice, Effectively Putting Feud Rumors to Rest|last=Johnson|first=Zach|date=December 18, 2013|publisher=E!|access-date=January 25, 2014}}</ref> [[Sam Smith (singer)|Sam Smith]],<ref name=\"SamInterview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/sam-smith-on-lady-gaga-tom-petty-boy-george-and-his-next-album/story-e6frfn29-1227304979980|title=Sam Smith on Lady Gaga, Tom Petty, Boy George ... and his next album|last=Beth|first=Dorris|date=April 15, 2015|publisher=News Corporation Australia|access-date=July 8, 2015}}</ref> and [[Lauren Jauregui]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/lauren-jauregui-shares-playlist-of-her-life|title=Lauren Jauregui Shares the Playlist of Her Life|work=[[Teen Vogue]]|date=October 26, 2018|accessdate=December 14, 2018}}</ref> among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capecodtimes.com/article/20100523/NEWS/5230322|title=Cape songwriter pens song for the troops|last=Wysocki|first=Heather|date=May 23, 2010|access-date=April 30, 2016|newspaper=[[Cape Cod Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2267844/selena-gomez-really-naked-revival-album-cover/|title=Was Selena Gomez Really Naked On Her Revival Album Cover?|last=Garibaldi|first=Christina|date=November 9, 2015|publisher=MTV News|access-date=December 2, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"GagaEOnline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/458017/lady-gaga-defends-miley-cyrus-lighten-up-and-leave-her-alone-|title=Lady Gaga Defends Miley Cyrus: 'Lighten Up and Leave Her Alone!'|last=Johnson|first=Zach|date=September 12, 2013|publisher=E!|access-date=June 21, 2014}}</ref> Her work has also inspired some athletes, including American figure skater [[Johnny Weir]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.windycitymediagroup.com/gay/lesbian/news/ARTICLE.php?AID=30675|title=Johnny Weir lets us in his 'World'|publisher=Windy City Media Group|access-date=May 13, 2013}}</ref> and American swimmer [[Dana Vollmer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seventeen.com/health/fitness/dana-vollmer-motivation-tips|title=Dana Vollmer Success Tips (Interview)|last=Abel|first=Alex|date=February 18, 2013|work=[[Seventeen (American magazine)|Seventeen]]|access-date=May 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAguilera's use of sexual imagery has helped catalyze public discourse on sexuality and feminism. Rhiannon Lucy Cosslett, co-founder of ''[[The Vagenda]]'', opined that the provocative dance routines in Aguilera's music videos are \"empowering\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/07/miley-cyrus-music-business-women-sinead-oconnor|title=Miley Cyrus: does the music business exploit women?|date=October 7, 2013|work=The Guardian|access-date=August 2, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera is also known for her television and music video impact; in 2012, Jon Caramanica of ''The New York Times'' commented that Aguilera \"will be remembered for her glamour, her scandalous take on femme-pop and her [[Brobdingnag]]ian voice, and&nbsp;... as the person who almost single-handedly reshaped music-competition reality programming\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/18/arts/music/how-christina-aguilera-changed-judging-of-reality-tv-music.html|title=How Christina Aguilera Changed Judging of Reality TV Music|last=Caramanica|first=Jon|date=September 17, 2012|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 13, 2013}}</ref> She was considered as one of the greatest women of the music video era by VH1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/photos/gallery/?fid=1477005&page=2&thumbnails=true|title=50 Greatest Women Of the Video Era|publisher=VH1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523054154/http://www.vh1.com/photos/gallery/?fid=1477005&page=2&thumbnails=true|archive-date=May 23, 2013|url-status=dead|access-date=May 13, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nWriting for The Hampton Institute, critic Terry Young, Jr. commented that Aguilera \"redefined the 21st century female pop performer,\" adding that following the release of ''Stripped'', \"artists like Spears and [[Beyonc\u00e9]] became more comfortable expressing sexuality and no longer felt the need to sell the notion of innocence\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hamptoninstitution.org/revisiting-stripped.html|title=Revisiting ''Stripped'': How Christina Aguilera Challenged Notions of Feminism and Sexuality|last=Young, Jr.|first=Terry|date=May 22, 2014|publisher=The Hampton Institute|access-date=May 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2008, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' placed Aguilera at number 58 on its list of 100 Greatest Singers of All Time, writing that \"[Aguilera] has had the finesse and power of a blues queen ever since she was a child star\".<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-greatest-singers-of-all-time-19691231/christina-aguilera-20101202|title=100 Greatest Singers of All Time: Christina Aguilera|date=November 27, 2008|work=Rolling Stone|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140705143029/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-greatest-singers-of-all-time-19691231/christina-aguilera-20101202|archive-date=July 5, 2014}}</ref> In November 2010, Aguilera was honored with a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/950886/christina-aguilera-gets-star-on-hollywood-walk-of-fame|title=Christina Aguilera Gets Star on Hollywood Walk of Fame|date=November 15, 2010|work=Billboard|access-date=August 3, 2014}}</ref> In October 2012, Aguilera's costumes and video collection was included on the \"Women Who Rock\" exhibition by the [[National Museum of Women in the Arts]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/28/arts/artsspecial/women-who-rock-exhibit-traces-female-music-artists-in-america.html|title='Women Who Rock' Exhibit Traces Female Music Artists in America|last=Olson|first=Elizabeth|date=October 26, 2012|work=The New York Times|access-date=August 3, 2014}}</ref> That same year, [[VH1]] named Aguilera the eighth greatest woman in the music industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/music/tuner/2012-02-13/100-greatest-women-in-music/94/|title=The 100 Greatest Women In Music|last=Graham|first=Mark|date=February 13, 2012|publisher=VH1|access-date=May 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2013 People's Choice Awards]], Aguilera was awarded the People's Voice Award, which recognized her ability to reach people across various genres.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1699242/christina-aguilera-peoples-choice-awards/|title=Christina Aguilera Goes From 'The Voice' To People's Choice|first=Jocelyn|last=Vena|publisher=MTV News|date=December 20, 2012|access-date=August 1, 2014}}</ref> Also in 2013, Aguilera was one of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s 100 Most Influential People in the World. In the article for the magazine, [[Celine Dion]] wrote, \"Without a doubt, [Aguilera]'s one of the most talented artists the world has ever seen and heard, and I think she's going to continue to amaze us for many, many years to come.\"<ref name=\"Influential\">{{cite news|url=http://time100.time.com/2013/04/18/time-100/slide/christina-aguilera/|title=Christina Aguilera: The 2013 Time 100|work=Time|first=Celine|last=Dion|date=April 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130419081239/http://time100.time.com/2013/04/18/time-100/slide/christina-aguilera/|archive-date=April 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the [[Human Rights Campaign]] honored Aguilera with its \"Ally for Equality\" award. She was recognized as an \"LGBTQ icon\" who used her platform to share a message of hope and inspiration.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/christina-aguilera-to-be-honored-by-human-rights-campaign-for-lgbtq-advocacy|title=Christina Aguilera to be honored by Human Rights Campaign for LGBTQ advocacy|publisher=Fox News|access-date=March 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>https://www.hrc.org/blog/hrc-announces-senator-kamala-harris-will-speak-at-the-2019-hrc-la-dinner</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\n\n===Philanthropy===\nIn 2000, Aguilera supported a program called Come on Over and Do Something, which aimed to \"encourage kids to get involved in their communities and make a difference.\"<ref>{{cite web|access-date=April 27, 2013|url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/100200/Xpress/What_a_girl_wants__is.shtml|title=What a girl wants ... is for kids to help their community|work=[[The St. Petersburg Times]]|first=Ally|last=Sikora|date=October 2, 2000|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819090145/http://www.sptimes.com/News/100200/Xpress/What_a_girl_wants__is.shtml|archive-date=August 19, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A year later, she signed a letter from the [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals]] (PETA) to the South Korean government requesting that the country stop its alleged killing of dogs for food.<ref>{{cite news|last=Travis|first=Neal|date=September 13, 2001|title=Terror Attack Blows D.A.'s Timing|newspaper=New York Post|page=67}}</ref> In 2010, Aguilera auctioned tickets for her planned tour for [[Christie's]] A Bid to Save the Earth, which benefited the non-profit environmental groups [[Conservation International]], [[Oceana (non-profit group)|Oceana]], [[Natural Resources Defense Council]], and The Central Park Conservancy.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Manhattan Neighborhood Network]]|last=Ju|first=Siel|date=February 3, 2010|url=http://www.mnn.com/lifestyle/arts-culture/blogs/christies-celeb-studded-earth-day-auction|title=Christie's celeb-studded Earth Day auction|access-date=February 4, 2010}}</ref> Aguilera contributed US$200,000 to the [[Women's Center & Shelter of Greater Pittsburgh]] in December 2003,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2002&dat=20031223&id=q2wyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ULUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1457,6172137|title=People Watch|page=19|work=[[The Beaver County Times]]|date=December 23, 2003|access-date=April 18, 2016}}</ref> and was part of the [[Lifetime Television]]'s \"End violence against women\" campaign.<ref>{{cite web|title=Christina Aguilera, Nicole Kidman and Martina McBride Join Lifetime Television for 7th Annual Emmy Award-Winning, Multi-Platform 'End Violence Against Women' Campaign|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/christina-aguilera-nicole-kidman-and-martina-mcbride-join-lifetime-television-for-7th-annual-emmy-award-winning-multi-platform-end-violence-against-women-campaign-57825437.html|agency=PR Newswire|access-date=June 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Aguilera contributed \"Beautiful\" to the compilation album ''[[Love Rocks]]'', which proceeds benefited the [[Human Rights Campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140920235026/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/64152/love-rocks|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/64152/love-rocks|title=Love Rocks|work=Billboard|date=February 19, 2005|archive-date=September 20, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera participated in the AIDS Project Los Angeles' Artists Against AIDS \"[[What's Going On (song)|What's Going On?]]\" cover project, and became the face for [[MAC Cosmetics]] and spokesperson for MAC AIDS Fund in 2004. Singer [[Elton John]] featured Aguilera in his charity book ''4 Inches'', which benefitted the [[Elton John AIDS Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/paris-and-nicky-hilton-kimora-lee-simmons-christina-aguilera-rebecca-romijn-elle-macpherson-heidi-klum-among-44-celebrities-to-bare-all-for-new-book-to-benefit-the-elton-john-aids-foundation-54528372.html|title=Paris and Nicky Hilton, Kimora Lee Simmons, Christina Aguilera, Rebecca Romijn, Elle Macpherson, Heidi Klum Among 44 Celebrities To Bare All For New Book To Benefit The Elton John AIDS Foundation|agency=PR Newswire|date=June 5, 2005}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Secretary Clinton With David Novak and Christina Aguilera (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Aguilera (left) and Novak (right) were honored with the George McGovern Leadership Award in October 2012 for their contributions to the United Nations World Hunger Relief effort, while Clinton (center) was given a special tribute]]\n\nIn the run-up to the [[2004 United States presidential election]], Aguilera was featured on billboards for the \"Only You Can Silence Yourself\" online voter registration drive run by the [[political party|nonpartisan]], non-profit campaign \"[[Declare Yourself]]\". In these political advertisements, shot by David LaChapelle, Aguilera was shown with her mouth sewn shut to symbolize the effects of not voting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/67360/stars-declare-support-for-voting-initiative|title=Stars 'Declare' Support For Voting Initiative|date=July 13, 2004|work=Billboard|access-date=August 15, 2014}}</ref> In late 2007, Aguilera became the spokesperson for \"[[Rock the Vote]]\", through which she encouraged young people to vote in the [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 presidential election]].<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071115130951/http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/arts_entertainment/aguilera%2Bbacks%2Bvoting%2Bcampaign/1047562|url=http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/arts_entertainment/aguilera+backs+voting+campaign/1047562|title=Aguilera backs voting campaign|publisher=[[Channel 4]]|date=November 14, 2007|archive-date=November 15, 2007|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2005, Aguilera donated her wedding gifts to American charities in support of [[Hurricane Katrina]] victims,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.today.com/id/10142556/ns/today-today_entertainment/t/christina-aguilera-wed-over-weekend/|title=Christina Aguilera wed over weekend|work=[[Today (US program)|Today]]|date=December 14, 2005|access-date=August 17, 2014}}</ref> and performed at \"Unite of the Stars\" concert for Unite Against Hunger in [[Johannesburg]], South Africa and for the [[Nelson Mandela Children's Fund]] at the Coca-Cola Dome.<ref>{{cite news|title=For The Record: Quick News On Christina Aguilera, Jennifer Lopez And Marc Anthony, Madonna, Bloc Party & More|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1512314/for-the-record-quick-news-on-christina-aguilera-jennifer-lopez-and-marc-anthony-madonna-bloc-party-more/|access-date=June 15, 2014|publisher=MTV News|date=October 26, 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Aguilera headlined London's Africa Rising charity concert at the [[Royal Albert Hall]], which raised awareness for finding substantial issues facing the continent.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/hi/music/newsid_7671000/7671293.stm|title=Christina Aguilera returns to the UK|work=BBC News|date=October 15, 2008|access-date=August 17, 2014|first=Sinead|last=Garvan}}</ref> That year, Aguilera appeared on the Turkish version of ''Deal or No Deal'', ''[[Var m\u0131s\u0131n? Yok musun?]]'', and donated proceeds to a charity program for [[orphan]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Altinsas|first=E. Baris|title=A loving family for children in need of protection|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/tz-web/detaylar.do?load=detay&link=156957&bolum=101|work=[[Today's Zaman]]|date=October 26, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520083051/http://www.todayszaman.com/newsDetail_getNewsById.action?load=detay&link=156957&bolum=101|archive-date=May 20, 2011}}</ref> In 2009, Aguilera became the global spokesperson for [[World Hunger Relief]];<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Business Wire]]|url=http://www.businesswire.com/portal/site/google/?ndmViewId=news_view&newsId=20090715006146&newsLang=en|title=Aguilera Raises Awareness of Hunger Issue by Appearing in PSA, Advertising, Posters|date=July 15, 2009|access-date=July 15, 2009}}</ref> she and Bratman traveled to [[Guatemala]] with the [[World Food Programme]] to bring awareness to issues including its high [[malnutrition]] rate, and met with local families and beneficiaries of WFP's nutrition programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wfp.org/christina-aguilera|title=Christina Aguilera \u2013 A Voice for the Hungry|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130104151429/http://www.wfp.org/christina-aguilera|archive-date=January 4, 2013|publisher=[[World Food Programme]]}}</ref> Aguilera has helped raise over $148&nbsp;million for WFP and other hunger relief agencies in 45 countries.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=World Food Programme|url=http://www.wfp.org/christina-aguilera|title=Christina and the World Food Programme|access-date=January 13, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207041759/http://www.wfp.org/christina-aguilera|archive-date=December 7, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the [[2010 Haiti earthquake]], Aguilera donated a signed [[Chrysler 300]] which was auctioned for relief efforts.<ref>{{cite web|agency=PR Newswire|date=January 17, 2010|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-chrysler-brand-joins-forces-with-the-67th-annual-golden-globe-awards-to-contribute-relief-efforts-to-haiti-81918812.html|title=The Chrysler Brand Joins Forces With 'The 67th Annual Golden Globe Awards' to Contribute Relief Efforts to Haiti|access-date=January 18, 2010}}</ref> She additionally appeared on the ''[[Hope for Haiti Now: A Global Benefit for Earthquake Relief|Hope for Haiti]]'' telethon that January, where donations directly benefited [[Oxfam|Oxfam America]], [[Partners In Health]], [[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|Red Cross]] and [[UNICEF]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Karger|first=Dave|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2010/01/22/hope-for-haiti-now-the-telethons-10-best-performances/|title='Hope For Haiti Now': The telethon's 10 best performances|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=January 22, 2010|access-date=March 25, 2010}}</ref> She was featured on a public service announcement alongside former boxer [[Muhammad Ali]] to raise funds for the World Food Programme's efforts to bring food to survivors of the earthquake.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wfp.org/content/sneak-peek-christina-aguilera-and-muhammad-alis-haiti-psa|title=WFO|publisher=World Food Programme|access-date=January 31, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130807032922/http://www.wfp.org/content/sneak-peek-christina-aguilera-and-muhammad-alis-haiti-psa|archive-date=August 7, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Aguilera was nominated for a [[VH1]] Do Something Award for her work with the organization and her efforts in [[Humanitarian response to the 2010 Haiti earthquake|response to the earthquake]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/events/do_something_awards/2010/music-artist/|title=Do Something Music Artist|publisher=VH1|access-date=December 4, 2012}}</ref> In 2010, Aguilera was appointed [[United States Ambassador to the United Nations|UN ambassador]] for the World Food Programme.<ref name=\"RedBook\">{{cite news|title=Christina Aguilera Goes Solo|url=http://www.redbookmag.com/life/interviews/a6759/christina-aguilera-news-interview/|work=[[Redbook]]|access-date=February 24, 2011}}</ref> Following [[Hurricane Sandy]] in 2012, Aguilera performed \"Beautiful\" to open the ''[[Hurricane Sandy: Coming Together]]'' benefit telethon; all proceeds went to the [[American Red Cross]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Stars perform to help victims of Sandy|url=http://entertainment.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/11/02/14888295-stars-perform-to-help-victims-of-sandy|access-date=June 15, 2014|publisher=NBC News|date=November 2, 2012}}</ref> That year, Aguilera and [[David C. Novak|David Novak]] received the George McGovern Leadership Award.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wfpusa.org/world-food-programme-ambassador-christina-aguilera-and-yum-brands-chairman-david-novak-honored-state|title=World Food Program USA recognizes champions in solving global hunger; Pays special tribute to Secretary of State Hillary Clinton)|publisher=World Food Program USA|access-date=October 31, 2015|date=October 3, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131027224807/http://wfpusa.org/world-food-programme-ambassador-christina-aguilera-and-yum-brands-chairman-david-novak-honored-state|archive-date=October 27, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The following year Aguilera was honored with the Muhammad Ali Humanitarian of the Year Award.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schrenier|first=Bruce|url=http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/224454921.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922105134/http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/224454921.html|archive-date=September 22, 2013|work=[[Star Tribune]]|title=Former President Jimmy Carter headlines winners of Muhammad Ali Humanitarian Awards|date=September 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Products and endorsements===\nIn 2000, Aguilera was the face for make-up line Fetish, where she worked in choosing colors and packaging for the line.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1424798/christina-aguilera-shares-her-fetish/|title=Christina Aguilera Shares Her Fetish|publisher=MTV News|first=Curtis|last=Waller|date=July 14, 2000|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> That same year, an interactive CD-ROM was produced called ''Christina Aguilera: Follow Your Dreams'' released by [[Simon & Schuster|Simon & Schuster Interactive]] which features games and quizzes, plus Aguilera herself talking about accomplishing her goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1121534/pop-beat-carlos-santana-everlast-christina-aguilera/|title=Pop Beat: Carlos Santana, Everlast, Christina Aguilera ...|publisher=[[MTV]]|date=June 27, 2000|access-date=September 20, 2017}}</ref> Throughout her career, Aguilera has endorsed several brands, including [[Sears]], [[Levi Strauss & Co|Levi's]],<ref name=\"Sears & Levi's\">{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/sears-and-levisr-launch-new-marketing-campaign-for-sponsorship-of-christina-aguilera-summer-tour-72584442.html|work=PSNewswire|title=Sears and Levi's(R) Launch New Marketing Campaign for Sponsorship of Christina Aguilera Summer Tour|last=Galvin|first=Aubree|date=July 31, 2000|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> [[Skechers]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,478535,00.html|title=Toeing the Line|work=Entertainment Weekly|last=Susman|first=Gary|date=August 27, 2003|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> [[Mercedes-Benz]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baby-benz.com/portal/a-class-w169/137--christina-aguilera-says-an-exclusive-qhelloq-to-the-new-a-class-|title=Christina Aguilera says an exclusive 'Hello' to the new A-Class|publisher=[[Mercedes-Benz]]|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> [[Versace]],<ref name=\"Versace\">{{cite web|last=Susman|first=Gary|date=March 5, 2003|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,429223~10~0~versacesignschristinaaguilera,00.html|title=Beautiful: Designer signs new muse and model|work=Entertainment Weekly|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141019000911/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0%2C%2C429223~10~0~versacesignschristinaaguilera%2C00.html|archive-date=October 19, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Virgin Mobile]],<ref name=\"Virgin\">{{cite web|url=http://www.brandrepublic.com/article/211094/virgin-mobile-claims-aguilera-ad-its-sexiest-ever|work=Variety|title=Virgin Mobile claims Aguilera ad is its 'sexiest ever'|last=Lepper|first=Joe|date=May 18, 2004|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> [[Orange UK]], [[Oreo]],<ref>[http://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/new-oreo-campaign-reminds-you-how-delightful-dunking-cookies-can-be/ New Oreo campaign reminds you how delightful dunking cookies can be] ''Adweek''</ref> [[Sony Ericsson]] <ref name=\"Orange & Sony\">{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2006/03/03/orange-signs-sony-ericsson-christina-aguilera/|work=Engadget|title=Orange signs Sony Ericsson, Christina Aguilera|last=Blass|first=Evan|date=March 23, 2006|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> and soft drink giants [[Coca-Cola]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,109862,00.html|title=Pop Star|work=Entertainment Weekly|last=Bonin|first=Liane|date=May 17, 2001|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> and [[Pepsi]] in 2001 and 2006, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|title=For The Record: Quick News On Christina Aguilera, Game, 50 Cent, Jessica Simpson, Nelly, C. DeLores Tucker & More|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1511468/for-the-record-quick-news-on-christina-aguilera-game-50-cent-jessica-simpson-nelly-c-delores-tucker-more/|access-date=June 15, 2014|publisher=MTV News|date=October 13, 2005}}</ref> In 2004, Aguilera earned [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]200,000 (about $300,000) for opening the summer sale at London's [[Harrods]] store<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/music/2004/06/29/christinaaguilera/|title=Christina Aguilera turns on the style for Harrods opening|work=Hello!|date=June 29, 2004|access-date=January 3, 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141028043032/http://www.hellomagazine.com/music/2004/06/29/christinaaguilera/|archive-date=October 28, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and appeared in an advertisement for [[MAC Cosmetics]]' Viva Glam V campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/pamela-anderson-is-the-next-spokesperson-and-newest-face-for-the-mac-aids-funds-viva-glam-v-lipstick-advertising-campaign-54386867.html|title=Pamela Anderson is the Next Spokesperson and Newest Face for the M.A.C AIDS Fund's VIVA GLAM V Lipstick Advertising Campaign|format=press release|agency=PR Newswire|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> Following the birth of her son in 2008, she was reportedly paid $1.5 million by ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' for her baby pictures, which became the [[List of most expensive celebrity photographs|ninth most expensive celebrity baby photographs ever taken]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/07/01/michael-jackson-magazine-business-media-jackson_slide_10.html|title=In Pictures: Most Expensive Celebrity Photos|access-date=May 29, 2013|last=Rose|first=Lacey|date=July 1, 2009|journal=Forbes}}</ref> In 2008, jewelry designer [[Stephen Webster]] and friend of Aguilera released \"Shattered\", a collection of [[sterling silver]] pieces, through [[Neiman Marcus]] and [[Bergdorf Goodman]]. Aguilera, who inspired the collection, was featured as a [[Hitchcock]] heroine.<ref>{{cite web|last=Conti|first=Samantha|date=February 19, 2008|work=[[Women's Wear Daily]]|url=http://www.wwd.com/accessories-news/jewelry/christina-aguilera-inspires-stephen-webster-silver-line-465346|title=Christina Aguilera Inspires Stephen Webster Silver Line|access-date=February 19, 2008}}</ref> They reprised their work together for Webster's 2009 spring line.<ref>{{cite web|last=Brown|first=Rachel|date=December 18, 2008|work=Women's Wear Daily|url=http://www.wwd.com/media-news/fashion-memopad/aguilera-goes-retro-pamela-meets-vivienne-stella-goes-moblie-1897710?full=true|title=Aguilera Goes Retro&nbsp;... Pamela Meets Vivienne|access-date=January 16, 2009}}</ref> In 2011, Aguilera attended [[S\u00e3o Paulo Fashion Week]] to premiere her new line of clothing for Brazilian department store [[C&A]], which launched in April of that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caras.com.mx/moda/322362/christina-aguilera-presenta-coleccion-ca/|title=Christina Aguilera presenta colecci\u00f3n C&A|work=Caras|publisher=Televisa S.A. de C.V.|language=Spanish|location=Mexico|date=August 19, 2011|access-date=January 3, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150103062908/http://www.caras.com.mx/moda/322362/christina-aguilera-presenta-coleccion-ca/|archive-date=January 3, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAguilera was named the number one awarded celebrity brand, with 13 awards won globally, in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://perfumes.christinaaguilera.com/en/awards|title=Christina Aguilera No. 1 Awarded Celebrity Brand|date=October 1, 2017}}</ref> Her first fragrance, Xpose, was released in Europe in late 2004 and sold relatively well.<ref>{{cite news|title=Showbiz Gossip|work=[[The Evening Chronicle]]|page=35|publisher=Newcastle Chronicle & Journal Ltd|date=January 18, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Hazlett|first=Courtney|publisher=[[MSN]]|date=May 8, 2008|url=http://www.today.com/id/24525545|title=Aguilera's new scent|access-date=May 9, 2008}}</ref> Through [[Procter & Gamble]], Aguilera released her signature fragrance, Simply Christina, in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/christina-aguilera/28220|title=Christina Aguilera to launch fragrance|work=[[NME]]|date=May 9, 2007|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> During the Christmas period of 2007, the fragrance became the number one perfume in the United Kingdom,<ref>{{cite news|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080109000818/http://www.rcalabelgroup.co.uk/news/8020/|url=http://www.rcalabelgroup.co.uk/news/8020/|title=Christina Tops Fragrance Charts|publisher=RCA Label Group UK. [[Sony BMG]]|date=December 17, 2007|archive-date=January 9, 2008}}</ref> and later in 2009 it was the country's fourth best selling perfume.<ref name=\"vogue.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/beauty/2010/01/15/all-star-perfumes|title=All Star Perfumes (Vogue.com UK)|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] (United Kingdom)|date=January 15, 2010|access-date=September 18, 2010}}</ref> It won as the people's choice for favorite celebrity fragrance at the annual UK [[The Fragrance Foundation|Fifi Awards]] 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nymag.com/thecut/2008/04/marc_jacobs_tom_ford_christina_1.html|title=Marc Jacobs, Tom Ford, and Christina Aguilera Win Top Fragrance Awards|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=April 24, 2008|access-date=August 9, 2008}}</ref> Aguilera released her third fragrance, Inspire, accompanied with a body care collection, in September 2008.<ref>{{cite journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081203174822/http://www.fashionmagazine.com/beauty/regulararticle/544/|url=http://www.fashionmagazine.com/beauty/regulararticle/544/|title=Sweet refrain|journal=[[Fashion (magazine)|Fashion]]|issue=September 2008|archive-date=December 3, 2008|first=Michelle|last=Bilodeau}}</ref> It was her first fragrance released outside of Europe.<ref>{{cite news|last=Epiro|first=Stephanie|title=P&G Hopes Aguilera Will 'Inspire' Its Fragrance Fortunes|url=http://www.wwd.com/beauty-industry-news/beauty-features/p-g-hopes-aguilera-will-inspire-its-fragrance-fortunes-1556271|work=Women's Wear Daily|date=July 24, 2008|access-date=August 27, 2008}}</ref> Her worldwide ad campaign included a television ad shot by David LaChapelle and was released in the United States in [[Macy's]] department stores. The release coincided with Macy's 150th anniversary which featured Aguilera in commemorative photos.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Business Wire|date=July 31, 2008|type=press release|url=http://www.businesswire.com/portal/site/google/?ndmViewId=news_view&newsId=20080731005593&newsLang=en|title=Mark Seliger Captures Macy's 'Stars' for Commemorative 150th Birthday Images|access-date=July 31, 2008}}</ref> She released her fourth fragrance, By Night, in October 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Christina-Aguilera-Night-Eau-Parfum/dp/B002SKFKZU|title=Christina Aguilera By Night Eau de Parfum|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> which became the third best selling fragrance in the United Kingdom in 2009.<ref name=\"vogue.co.uk\"/> The range has been further augmented yearly by new releases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/10/25/christina-aguilera-royal-desire-ad-photoshop_n_2019309.html|title=Christina Aguilera's Royal Desire Perfume Ad Reeks Of Photoshop|first=Ellie|last=Krupnich|date=October 25, 2012|work=HuffPost|access-date=December 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-hook/474805/christina-aguilera-shows-skin-in-sinful-fragrance-ad|title=Christina Aguilera Shows Skin in Sinful Fragrance Ad|first=Gregory|last=DelliCarpini Jr.|work=Billboard|date=October 4, 2012|access-date=February 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://style.mtv.com/2013/10/18/christina-aguilera-unforgettable/|title=Christina Aguilera Reveals Unforgettable Fragrance Ad|publisher=MTV Style|first=Parry|last=Ernsberger|date=October 18, 2013|access-date=December 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7988853/christina-aguilera-perfume-ad-definition|title=Watch the High-Gloss Ad for Christina Aguilera's New Perfume, Definition|date=October 10, 2017|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Christina Aguilera discography|List of songs recorded by Christina Aguilera|l2 = songs}}\n* ''[[Christina Aguilera (album)|Christina Aguilera]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Mi Reflejo]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[My Kind of Christmas]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[Stripped (Christina Aguilera album)|Stripped]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Back to Basics (Christina Aguilera album)|Back to Basics]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Bionic (Christina Aguilera album)|Bionic]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Lotus (Christina Aguilera album)|Lotus]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Liberation (Christina Aguilera album)|Liberation]]'' (2018)\n\n==Filmography==\n{{see also|Christina Aguilera videography}}\n* ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[The Emoji Movie]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Zoe (film)|Zoe]]'' (2018)\n<!--Do NOT add television roles; this section should only list films when there is a separate page for her videography, which contains her television credits. They are also mentioned in the article body.-->\n\n==Tours and concerts==\n{{main|List of Christina Aguilera concert tours}}\n\n===Headlining tours===\n* [[Christina Aguilera in Concert]] (2000\u20132001)\n* [[The Stripped Tour]] (2003)\n* [[Back to Basics Tour]] (2006\u20132008)\n* [[Liberation Tour|The Liberation Tour]] (2018)\n* [[The X Tour (Christina Aguilera)|The X Tour]] (2019)\n\n===Co-headlining tours===\n* [[Justified and Stripped Tour]] (2003) (with [[Justin Timberlake]])\n\n===Residencies===\n* [[The Xperience]] (2019\u20132020)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Honorific nicknames in popular music]]\n* [[List of artists who reached number one in the United States]]\n* [[List of artists who reached number one on the UK Singles Chart]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{cite book|last=Dominguez|first=Pier|title=Christina Aguilera: A Star is Made: The Unauthorized Biography|publisher=Amber Communications Group, Inc|year=2003|isbn=978-0-970-222-459|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/christinaaguiler0000domi}}\n*{{cite book|last=Kimpel|first=Dan|year=2006|title=How They Made It: True Stories of How Music's Biggest Stars Went from Start to Stardom|isbn=978-0-634-076-428|publisher=[[Hal Leonard LLC]]|ref=harv|url=https://archive.org/details/howtheymadeittru0000kimp}}\n*{{cite book|first1=Diane|last1=Railton|first2=Paul|last2=Watson|title=Music Video and the Politics of Representation|year=2011|publisher=[[Edinburgh University Press]]|isbn=978-0-748-633-234|pages=88\u201390|ref=harv}}\n\n===Further reading===\n{{Wikipedia books|Christina Aguilera}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Scott|first=Kieran|title=I Was a Mousketeer!|publisher=[[Disney Press]]|year=2001|isbn=978-0-7868-4470-8}}\n\n==External links==\n<!--- PLEASE DO NOT ADD ADDITIONAL WEBSITES, SEE [[WP:EL]]. -->\n{{commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.christinaaguilera.com/}}\n* {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=christina-aguilera-mn0000780258|label=Christina Aguilera}}\n* {{Discogs artist|77855-Christina-Aguilera|Christina Aguilera}}\n* {{IMDb name|4694}}\n* {{worldcat id|lccn-no00-575}}\n<!--- PLEASE DO NOT ADD ADDITIONAL WEBSITES, SEE [[WP:EL]]. -->\n\n{{Christina Aguilera}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Christina Aguilera|Awards for Christina Aguilera]]\n| list = \n{{Grammy Award for Best New Artist}}\n{{Glamour Awards Woman of the Year}}\n{{MTV Video Music Award for Video of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aguilera, Christina}}\n[[Category:Christina Aguilera| 01]]\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:Activists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York City]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of supra-national bodies]]\n[[Category:American child singers]]\n[[Category:American contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:American dance musicians]]\n[[Category:American dancers]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Japan]]\n[[Category:American female dancers]]\n[[Category:American female pop singers]]\n[[Category:American pop singers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of Ecuadorian descent]]\n[[Category:American sopranos]]\n[[Category:American soul singers]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:American women record producers]]\n[[Category:Brit Award winners]]\n[[Category:Child pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Dance-pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Dancers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Feminist musicians]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American actresses]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American female singers]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS activists]]\n[[Category:Latin Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Latin pop singers]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Record producers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Mouseketeers]]\n[[Category:Music video codirectors]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:People from Rochester, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Staten Island]]\n[[Category:RCA Records artists]]\n[[Category:Record producers from California]]\n[[Category:Record producers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Sex-positive feminists]]\n[[Category:Singers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Singers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Singers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Singers with a four-octave vocal range]]\n[[Category:Sony BMG artists]]\n[[Category:Women in Latin music]]\n[[Category:World Food Programme people]]\n[[Category:MTV EMA winners]]\n[[Category:World Music Awards winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the singer|her eponymous debut album|Christina Aguilera (album)}}\n{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American singer, songwriter, actress, and television personality}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Christina Aguilera\n| image           = Liberation Tour (45997616942) (cropped).jpg\n| caption         = Aguilera on her [[Liberation Tour]] in 2018\n| birth_name      = Christina Mar\u00eda Aguilera\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1980|12|18}}\n| birth_place     = {{nowrap|[[New York City]]<!--No boroughs/neighborhoods, just cities per format.-->, U.S.}}<!--As per WP:LINKDIRECT and Template:infobox person, birthplace indicates CITY, state, then country. No need to spell out \"United States; 'U.S.' is fine.-->\n| home_town       = {{plain list|\n* [[Rochester, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n* [[Wexford, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n}}\n| occupation      = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|actress|television personality}}\n| spouse          = {{marriage|Jordan Bratman|2005|2011|reason=divorced}}\n| partner         = Matthew Rutler (2010\u2013present; engaged)\n| children        = 2\n| years_active    = 1992\u2013present\n| net_worth       = <!-- Do NOT add info from \"Celebrity Net Worth\" as it is unreliable -->\n| awards          = [[List of awards and nominations received by Christina Aguilera|Full list]]\n| website         = {{URL|christinaaguilera.com}}\n| module          = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background      = solo_singer\n| instrument      = Vocals\n| Genre           = {{flatlist|\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[dance-pop]]\n* [[Soul music|soul]]}}\n| label           = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| associated_acts = <!-- before adding please see [[Template:Infobox musical artist/doc#associated acts]] for appropriate additions-->\n}}\n}}\n'''Christina Mar\u00eda Aguilera''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u00e6|\u0261|\u026a|\u02c8|l|\u025b\u0259r|\u0259}}, {{IPA-es|a\u0263i\u02c8le\u027ea|lang}};<ref>{{cite AV media|people=W magazine|date=May 16, 2018|title=Christina Aguilera Breaks Down Her Most Iconic Music Video Looks|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=doXqDkzFEkQ|time=0:01}}</ref> born December 18, 1980) is an American singer, songwriter, actress and television personality. Her [[List of awards and nominations received by Christina Aguilera|accolades]] include five [[Grammy Award]]s, one [[Latin Grammy Award]], and a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]]. Aguilera ranked at number 58 on ''[[Rolling Stone]]''{{'}}s list of 100 Greatest Singers of All Time in 2008, and was included on ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s annual list of the [[Time 100|100 most influential people in the world]] in 2013. With estimated sales of 75 million records, she is one of the world's [[List of best-selling music artists|best-selling music artists]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/music/christina-aguilera-at-3arena-dublin-everything-you-need-to-know-1.4066866|title=Christina Aguilera at 3Arena, Dublin: Everything you need to know|first=Tony|last=Clayton-Lea|work=[[The Irish Times]]|date=November 3, 2019|accessdate=November 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Staten Island]] of [[New York City]] and raised in [[Pennsylvania]], Aguilera appeared on television shows in her early years, before gaining a recording contract with [[RCA Records]] in 1998. Her [[Christina Aguilera (album)|self-titled debut album]], released in 1999, reached number one in the US and spawned three US number-one singles: \"[[Genie in a Bottle]]\", \"[[What a Girl Wants (Christina Aguilera song)|What a Girl Wants]]\", and \"[[Come On Over Baby (All I Want Is You)]]\". While recognized as a prominent figure in the contemporary [[teen pop]] scene, Aguilera sought to assume artistic control with ''[[Stripped (Christina Aguilera album)|Stripped]]'' (2002) and its lead single \"[[Dirrty]]\", which displayed her sexually emancipated persona and generated considerable controversy. The second single from the album, \"[[Beautiful (Christina Aguilera song)|Beautiful]]\", received favorable response for its empowering lyrics and became an anthem for the [[LGBT community]].\n\nAguilera scored her second US number-one album with ''[[Back to Basics (Christina Aguilera album)|Back to Basics]]'' (2006), which drew inspiration from early 20th-century [[jazz]], [[soul music|soul]], and [[blues]], and spawned the top-ten singles \"[[Ain't No Other Man]]\", \"[[Hurt (Christina Aguilera song)|Hurt]]\", and \"[[Candyman (Christina Aguilera song)|Candyman]]\". Her next three albums, ''[[Bionic (Christina Aguilera album)|Bionic]]'' (2010), ''[[Lotus (Christina Aguilera album)|Lotus]]'' (2012), and ''[[Liberation (Christina Aguilera album)|Liberation]]'' (2018), all experimented with various musical styles and reached the top ten in the US. Besides solo materials, Aguilera earned chart-topping entries with collaborations including \"[[Lady Marmalade#Moulin Rouge! version|Lady Marmalade]]\", \"[[Moves like Jagger]]\", \"[[Feel This Moment]]\", and \"[[Say Something (A Great Big World song)|Say Something]]\". Alongside her music career, Aguilera starred in the film ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'' (2010) and was a coach on six seasons of the singing competition television series ''[[The Voice (American TV series)|The Voice]]'' from 2011 to 2016.\n\n==Life and career==\n===1980\u20131998: Early life and career beginnings===\nChristina Mar\u00eda Aguilera was born in [[Staten Island]], [[New York City]], on December 18, 1980, to musician Shelly Loraine Kearns (n\u00e9e Fidler) and [[United States Army]] soldier Fausto Xavier Aguilera.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wang|first1=Julia|title=Christina Aguilera Biography|url=http://www.people.com/people/christina_aguilera/biography/|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|access-date=September 28, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140331213217/https://people.com/people/christina_aguilera/biography/|archive-date=31 March 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Her father {{cl-span|is Ecuadorian|date=October 2019|reason=I guess he was in the army to GAIN citizenship but failed? Or is he ACTUALLY an American citizen of Ecuadorian descent?}}, and her mother has German, Irish, Welsh, and Dutch ancestry.{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|p=2}}<ref name=\"Early life\">{{cite journal|last1=Gregory|first1=Sophfronia Scott|last2=Ferguson|first2=Hayes|title=Uncorking the Genie|journal=People|date=September 27, 1999|volume=52|issue=12|pages=75\u201376|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20129327,00.html|access-date=September 28, 2014|issn=0093-7673}}</ref> Her family moved frequently because of her father's military service, and lived in places including New Jersey, Texas, New York, and Japan.<ref name=\"WashingtonPost\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPcap/2000-02/13/003r-021300-idx.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180621070136/https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/WPcap/2000-02/13/003r-021300-idx.html|title=Christina Aguilera's Fast Track|last=Harrington|first=Richard|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=February 13, 2000|archive-date=June 21, 2018|url-status=dead|access-date=August 25, 2017}}</ref> Aguilera alleged that her father was physically and emotionally [[child abuse|abusive]].<ref name=\"mtv3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/aguilera_christina/news_feature_080906/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140805022136/http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/aguilera_christina/news_feature_080906/|archive-date=August 5, 2014|title=Christina Aguilera's Old Soul|first=Jennifer|last=Vineyard|access-date=July 21, 2013}}</ref> To cope with her turbulent household, she used music as a form of escape.<ref name=\"WMagazine\"/> Following her parents' divorce when she was six years old, Aguilera, her younger sister Rachel, and her mother moved into her grandmother's home in [[Rochester, Pennsylvania|Rochester]], a suburb in the [[Pittsburgh]] area.<ref name=\"Early life\"/> Her mother later remarried and had one more child.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Helligar|first=Jeremy|last2=Majewski|first2=Lori|date=February 3, 2003|title=Christina's World|journal=[[Us Weekly]]}}</ref> After years of estrangement, Aguilera expressed interest in reconciling with her father in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://b96.cbslocal.com/2012/02/09/christina-aguilera-wants-to-reconcile-with-estranged-father/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140730035712/http://b96.cbslocal.com/2012/02/09/christina-aguilera-wants-to-reconcile-with-estranged-father/|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 30, 2014|title=Christina Aguilera Wants To Reconcile With Estranged Father|publisher=[[CBS Local Media]]|date=February 9, 2012|access-date=July 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs a child, Aguilera was drawn to [[soul music|soul]] and [[blues]] records her grandmother bought and would practice singing, which earned her a reputation as \"the little girl with the big voice\" in her neighborhood.<ref name=\"newsweek\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/christina-aguilera-comes-age-112341|title=Christina Aguilera Comes of Age|last=Ali|first=Lorraine|date=July 30, 2006|work=[[Newsweek]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180120135330/http://www.newsweek.com/christina-aguilera-comes-age-112379|archive-date=January 20, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> She aspired to be a singer, and won her first talent show at age eight with a rendition of [[Whitney Houston]]'s \"[[I Wanna Dance with Somebody (Who Loves Me)]]\".<ref name=\"WashingtonPost\"/> Aged 10, she performed \"[[A Sunday Kind of Love]]\" on the competition show ''[[Star Search]]'', and was eliminated during the semi-final round.<ref name=\"WMagazine\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wmagazine.com/people/celebrities/2011/07/christina-aguilera-cover-story|title=From the Vaults: The Fall & Rise of Christina Aguilera|last=Hirschberg|first=Lynn|work=[[W (magazine)|W]]|date=July 2011|access-date=July 29, 2014}}</ref> She performed the song again on [[KDKA-TV]]'s ''Wake Up with [[Larry Richert]]''.{{sfn|Kimpel|2006|p=2}} During her youth in the Pittsburgh area, Aguilera sang the US national anthem, \"[[The Star-Spangled Banner]]\", before [[Pittsburgh Penguins]] hockey, [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] football, and [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] baseball games, and the [[1992 Stanley Cup Finals]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://triblive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/sports/penguins/s_623827.html|title=Anthem singer fires up Mellon crowd|last=Grupp|first=John|newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Tribune-Review]]|date=May 6, 2009|access-date=February 5, 2010}}</ref> She attended [[Rochester Area School District]] in Rochester and [[Marshall Middle School (Pittsburgh)|Marshall Middle School]] near [[Wexford, Pennsylvania|Wexford]], and briefly attended [[North Allegheny Intermediate High School]] before being homeschooled to avoid being bullied.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ca.movies.yahoo.com/person/christina-aguilera/biography.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812193158/https://ca.movies.yahoo.com/person/christina-aguilera/biography.html|archive-date=August 12, 2014|title=Christina Aguilera Biography|publisher=[[Yahoo! Movies]]|access-date=July 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, Aguilera auditioned for a position on ''[[The Mickey Mouse Club#1990s revival, The All-New Mickey Mouse Club (MMC)|The Mickey Mouse Club]]'', although she did not meet its age requirements. She joined the television series two years later, where she performed musical numbers and [[sketch comedy]] until its cancellation in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/interview/12043048|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070401032341/http://music.yahoo.com/read/interview/12043048|title=Dreaming of Genie|last=Goldstein|first=Rob|publisher=[[Yahoo! Music]]|date=May 15, 1999|archive-date=April 1, 2007}}</ref> Fellow cast members included [[Ryan Gosling]], [[Keri Russell]], [[Britney Spears]], and [[Justin Timberlake]].<ref name=\"AguileraBiographyPeople\">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/christina_aguilera|title=Christina Aguilera Biography|work=People|access-date=December 8, 2010}}</ref> After the show ended, Aguilera moved to Japan and recorded her first song, \"All I Wanna Do\", a duet with Japanese singer [[Keizo Nakanishi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,2044752,00.html|title=Christina Aguilera: Biography|date=September 15, 2001|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=June 25, 2019|first=Kevork|last=Djansezian}}</ref> In 1998, Aguilera returned to the US to seek a recording contract. She approached [[RCA Records]], who told her to contact [[Walt Disney Records|Disney]] instead because they were having financial difficulties.{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|p=43}} She sent her [[cover version]] of Whitney Houston's \"[[Run to You (Whitney Houston song)|Run to You]]\" to Disney in hopes of being selected to record the theme song \"[[Reflection (song)|Reflection]]\" for their animated film ''[[Mulan (1998 film)|Mulan]]'' (1998).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,84715,00.html|title=Club Kid|last=Willman|first=Chris|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=October 11, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150103052149/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0%2C%2C84715%2C00.html|archive-date=January 3, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Aguilera was ultimately selected to sing \"Reflection\"; the song was released in June 1998 and charted on the [[Hot Adult Contemporary Tracks|''Billboard'' Adult Contemporary]] chart at number 15.{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|p=44}}\n\n===1999\u20132001: ''Christina Aguilera'', ''Mi Reflejo'', and ''My Kind of Christmas''===\nAfter \"Reflection\", Aguilera attracted the attention of RCA's A&R [[Ron Fair]] and was signed with the label quickly afterwards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/the-christina-aguilera-story-so-far-19991028|title=The Christina Aguilera Story (So Far)|first=Anthony|last=Bozza|work=Rolling Stone|date=October 28, 1999|access-date=January 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Smith|first=Andy|title=One talented teen|work=[[The Providence Journal]]|date=August 15, 1998}}</ref> RCA was pressured by the contemporary [[teen pop]] craze evoked by Aguilera's peer Britney Spears, leading to the label rushing production of the album and aligning Aguilera to be part of the teen pop trend.{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|p=45}} They released the lead single off the album, \"[[Genie in a Bottle]]\", a trendy [[pop music|pop]] and [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] track, in June 1999.{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|p=45}} The single catapulted Aguilera to stardom, peaking atop the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and charts of 20 other countries.<ref name=\"GeniePeak21\">{{cite journal|title=Portrait of an Artist: Christina Aguilera|work=Billboard|date=January 20, 2000|volume=112|issue=5|pages=6\u20137}}</ref> It has sold over seven million copies as of 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chartsinfrance.net/Christina-Aguilera/news-93194.html|title=L'histoire d'un tube : 'Genie in a Bottle' de Christina Aguilera f\u00eate ses 15 ans|publisher=Charts in France|language=French|date=August 17, 2014|access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> Aguilera's [[Christina Aguilera (album)|eponymous debut album]] followed in August 1999 and peaked at number one on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref name=\"WashingtonPost\"/> It was certified [[RIAA certification|eight times platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA),<ref name=\"RIAA\"/> and had moved 17 million copies worldwide by 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/7682705/Christina-Aguileras-eye-on-the-prize.html|title=Christina Aguilera's 'eye on the prize'|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|access-date=August 26, 2017|first=Craig|last=McLean|date=May 7, 2010}}</ref> The album produced three other singles: two US number-one singles\u2013\"[[What a Girl Wants (Christina Aguilera song)|What a Girl Wants]]\" and \"[[Come On Over Baby (All I Want Is You)]]\", and one US top-five single\u2013\"[[I Turn to You (All-4-One song)#Christina Aguilera cover|I Turn to You]]\", a cover of [[All-4-One]]'s song.<ref name=\"AguileraBBCharts\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/299251/Christina+Aguilera/chart?f=379|title=Chart history for Christina Aguilera|work=Billboard|access-date=June 20, 2014}}</ref> At the [[42nd Annual Grammy Awards]] in February 2000, Aguilera won [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/story/12051721|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080528131603/http://music.yahoo.com/read/story/12051721|title=Christina Aguilera Wins Best New Artist|last=Rosen|first=Craig|publisher=Yahoo! Music|date=February 24, 2000|archive-date=May 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\nAguiera's two following studio albums, ''[[Mi Reflejo]]'' and ''[[My Kind of Christmas]]'', were released in September and October 2000, respectively.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Charts and retail notas|journal=Billboard|volume=112|issue=45|page=47|date=November 4, 2000|first=Leila|last=Cobo}}</ref> The former, a Spanish-language album consisting of re-recorded versions of tracks on Aguilera's debut album and several original songs, topped the [[Billboard Top Latin Albums|''Billboard'' Top Latin Albums]] for 19 consecutive weeks and was certified six times platinum in the [[Latin music|Latin]] field by the RIAA.<ref name=\"RIAA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=Christina+Aguilera|title=Gold & Platinum \u2013 Christina Aguilera|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726142412/http://www.billboard.com/charts/2001-02-03/latin-albums|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/2001-02-03/latin-albums|title=Top Latin Albums: February 3, 2001|work=Billboard|archive-date=July 26, 2014}}</ref> It won [[Latin Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Album|Best Female Pop Vocal Album]] at the [[2nd Annual Latin Grammy Awards]] in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/christina-wins-latin-grammy-20011030|title=Christina Wins Latin Grammy|last=Saraceno|first=Christina|work=Rolling Stone|date=October 30, 2001|access-date=December 4, 2012}}</ref> The latter contains covers of [[Christmas music|Christmas]] popular songs and a few original [[dance-pop]] tunes,{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|p=108}} and was certified platinum by the RIAA.<ref name=\"RIAA\"/> In support of her albums, Aguilera embarked on her first concert tour, [[Christina Aguilera in Concert]], from mid-2000 to early 2001. The tour visited North America, Europe, South America, and Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1424807/aguilera-to-play-prom-in-augusta-georgia/|title=Aguilera To Play Prom In Augusta, Georgia|first=David|last=Basham|publisher=MTV News|date=August 21, 2000|access-date=July 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010330211536/http://www.christina-a.com/christinainjapan.html|url=http://www.christina-a.com/christinainjapan.html|title=Christina Aguilera Live in Japan|publisher=Christina Aguilera website|date=February 9, 2001|archive-date=March 30, 2001}}</ref> ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' in 2000 recognized Aguilera as the Top Female Pop Act of the Year.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Year in Music 2000|journal=Billboard|page=58|date=December 30, 2000|volume=112|issue=53}}</ref> Despite the successes, Aguilera was displeased with the music and image her manager Steve Kurtz had aligned her to, feeling unable to control her own image.<ref name=\"NotYourPuppet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/aguilera_christina/news_feature_feb_02/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090305024500/http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/aguilera_christina/news_feature_feb_02/|archive-date=March 5, 2009|title=Christina Aguilera: Not Your Puppet|last=Stitzel|first=Kim|publisher=MTV News|date=February 2002|access-date=January 29, 2009}}</ref> In October 2000, she filed a breach of [[fiduciary duty]] lawsuit against Kurtz for improper, undue and inappropriate influence over her professional activities. After terminating Kurtz's services, RCA hired [[Irving Azoff]] as Aguilera's new manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/story?id=114375&page=1|title=Aguilera's Ex-Manager Fires Back|publisher=ABC News|date=October 19, 2000|access-date=December 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAguilera took her first steps in artistic control with the 2001 ''[[Moulin Rouge! Music from Baz Luhrmann's Film|Moulin Rouge!]]'' version of [[Labelle]]'s \"[[Lady Marmalade]]\" (1974), a collaboration with [[Pink (singer)|Pink]], [[Mya (singer)|Mya]], and [[Lil Kim]], produced by [[hip hop music|hip hop]] musicians [[Missy Elliott]] and [[Rockwilder]].<ref name=\"newsweek\"/> RCA executives initially opposed to Aguilera recording \"Lady Marmalade\" because it was \"too [[urban music|urban]]\", but Aguilera ultimately managed to record the song of her own accord.<ref name=\"NotYourPuppet\"/> The collaboration topped the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 for five weeks based on airplay alone, becoming the first airplay-only track in history to remain on the chart's top spot for more than one week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/lady-marmalade-mw0000424595|title=Lady Marmalade \u2013 Song Review|website=AllMusic|first=Jose|last=Promis|access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Hot 100 Spotlight|work=Billboard|date=June 2, 2001|first=Silvio|last=Pietroluongo|page=123|volume=113|issue=22}}</ref> It won [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Collaboration with Vocals|Best Pop Collaboration with Vocals]] at the [[44th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/The-2002-Grammy-winners-2868670.php|title=The 2002 Grammy winners|work=San Francisco Chronicle|date=February 28, 2002|access-date=July 7, 2014}}</ref> In mid-2001, [[Warlock Records]] released ''[[Just Be Free]]'', a compilation of [[demo (music)|demo]] tracks Aguilera recorded in 1994 and 1995, when she was looking forward to an album release after the end of ''The Mickey Mouse Club''. Aguilera filed a suit against Warlock Records and the album's producers to stop the release.{{sfn|Dominguez|2003|page=34}} The two parties came to a confidential settlement to release the album, in which Aguilera lent out her name, likeness, and image for an unspecified amount of damages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/A/Aguilera_Christina/2001/07/03/pf-742790.html|title=Disputed Aguilera album to be released|last=McGrath|first=Stephanie|publisher=[[Jam!]]|date=July 3, 2001|access-date=May 25, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===2002\u20132003: ''Stripped''===\n[[File:Stripped Tour CH - cropped.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Aguilera performing on [[The Stripped Tour]] in 2003]]\nWhen planning her fourth studio album, Aguilera leaned towards a new artistic direction that she felt had more musical and lyrical depth.<ref name=\"USAToday\">{{cite news|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2002-10-23-christina-aguilera_x.htm|title=Aguilera's image is 'Stripped'|last=Gardner|first=Elysa|newspaper=USA Today|date=October 24, 2002|access-date=October 19, 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160301144224/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2002-10-23-christina-aguilera_x.htm|archive-date=March 1, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> She named the album ''[[Stripped (Christina Aguilera album)|Stripped]]'' and explained that the title represented \"a new beginning, a re-introduction of [herself] as a new artist in a way\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1458433/christina-stands-up-for-the-ladies-discusses-fathers-abuse/|title=Christina Stands Up For The Ladies, Discusses Father's Abuse|first=Jennifer|last=Vineyard|publisher=MTV News|date=October 30, 2002|access-date=July 7, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera served as the album's [[executive producer]] and co-wrote most of the songs.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=[[Stripped (Christina Aguilera album)|Stripped]]|others=Christina Aguilera|year=2002|type=CD liner notes|publisher=[[RCA Records]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Vice_Stripped\">{{cite web|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_ca/article/d3dpby/christina-aguilera-stripped-gender-equality-15-anniversary|title=15 Years After Christina Aguilera's 'Stripped,' We're Still Nowhere Near Gender Equality|first=Sophie|last=Willkinson|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|date=October 27, 2017|access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> To present her new persona, Aguilera chose to release \"[[Dirrty]]\" as the lead single from the album in September 2002.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/28/arts/28iht-chris.2322180.html|title=Aguilera Aims for Edgy, bur Richer, Sound|work=[[The New York Times]]|first=Lola|last=Ogunnaike|date=July 28, 2006|access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> Its accompanying music video generated controversy for depicting overtly sexual fetishes.<ref>{{cite web|last=Edwards|first=Tanya L|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1458275/20021022/aguilera_christina.jhtml|title=How Dirty Is 'Dirrty'? X-posing The Kinks In X-tina's Video|publisher=MTV News|date=October 23, 2002|access-date=June 16, 2007}}</ref> Aguilera's new image presented in the video was widely criticized by the public that it began to overshadow her music.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tryangiel|first=Josh|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1376243-1,00.html|title=Welcome to my Bubble|work=Time|date=August 27, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012211218/http://time.com/time/magazine/article/0%2C9171%2C1376243-1%2C00.html|archive-date=October 12, 2007|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Dark|first=Jane|url=http://www.villagevoice.com/2002-11-12/music/siren-wailing/|title=Siren Wailing|work=[[The Village Voice]]|date=November 11, 2002|access-date=June 18, 2007|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041209030356/http://www.villagevoice.com/issues/0246/dark.php|archive-date=December 9, 2004|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"blender\">{{cite web|last=Duerden|first=Nick|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/67285/good-bad-dirrty.html|title=The Good, the Bad and the Dirrty|work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|date=November 15, 2003|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090807060733/http://www.blender.com/guide/67285/good-bad-dirrty.html|archive-date=August 7, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> She defended her new image: \"I'm in the power position, in complete command of everything and everybody around me. To be totally balls-out like that is, for me, the measure of a true artist.\"<ref name=\"blender\"/>\n\n''Stripped'' was released in October 2002.<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/stripped/christina-aguilera/critic-reviews|title=Critic Reviews for Stripped|website=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> The album incorporates various genres from R&B and [[flamenco]] to [[rock music|rock]], and lyrically revolves around the theme of [[self-esteem]] while also discussing [[sex]] and [[gender equality]].<ref name=\"Vice_Stripped\"/><ref name=\"rs_Stripped\"/> It received mixed reviews from music critics, who viewed the employment of various musical styles incoherent, but praised Aguilera's vocals.<ref name=\"MC\"/><ref name=\"rs_Stripped\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/stripped-20021105|title=Stripped|work=Rolling Stone|first=Jancee|last=Dunn|author-link=Jancee Dunn|date=November 6, 2002|access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> The album peaked at number two on the ''Billboard'' 200 and has sold over 4.3 million copies in the US as of 2014.<ref name=\"AskBillboardCareer\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6236538/ask-billboard-taylor-swift-out-shakes-mariah-carey?page=0%2C3|title=Ask Billboard: Taylor Swift Out-'Shake's Mariah Carey|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=September 1, 2014|work=Billboard|access-date=February 10, 2015}}</ref> In the UK, the album has sold two million copies as of 2017 and was the second highest-selling album by an American female artist during the 2000s decade, behind [[Norah Jones]] with ''[[Come Away with Me]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/official-charts-flashback-2002-christina-aguilera-reinvents-herself-with-dirrty-at-number-1__21081/|title=Official Charts Flashback 2002: Christina Aguilera reinvents herself with Dirrty at Number 1|date=November 23, 2017|access-date=January 20, 2018|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|first=Rob|last=Copsey}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media|date=December 28, 2009|title=Best-Selling of the Noughties|medium=radio news|publisher=[[BBC Radio 1]]/Official Charts Company}}</ref> By 2006, ''Stripped'' had sold over 12 million copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/10699242/scott_storchs_outrageous_fortune/print|title=Scott Storch's Outrageous Fortune|work=Rolling Stone|author=Tour\u00e9|date=June 29, 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080419055040/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/10699242/scott_storchs_outrageous_fortune/print|archive-date=April 19, 2008}}</ref> The second single from the album, the ballad \"[[Beautiful (Christina Aguilera song)|Beautiful]]\", received universal acclaim for its empowering lyrics about embracing inner beauty, and became an anthem for the [[LGBT community]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/song-stories/beautiful-christina-aguilera|title=Beautiful by Christina Aguilera|magazine=Rolling Stone|access-date=April 2, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140327020233/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/song-stories/beautiful-christina-aguilera|archive-date=March 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Beautiful,' Damn It|work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|first=Larry|last=Flick|date=January 20, 2004|page=90|url=https://books.google.co.jp/books?id=72QEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA90&|issue=906}}</ref> It was the album's best-charting single, peaking at number two on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=\"AguileraBBCharts\"/> The song won [[Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Performance|Best Female Pop Vocal Performance]] at the [[46th Annual Grammy Awards]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/02/09/arts/the-grammy-award-winners-of-2004.html|title=The Grammy Award Winners of 2004|work=The New York Times|date=February 9, 2004|access-date=October 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n''Stripped'' was followed by three other singles: \"[[Fighter (Christina Aguilera song)|Fighter]]\", \"[[Can't Hold Us Down]]\", and \"[[The Voice Within]]\", all of which were released in 2003 and entered the top 40 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=\"AguileraBBCharts\"/> During promotion of ''Stripped'', Aguilera cultivated a new image by adopting the [[alter ego]] Xtina, dyeing her hair black, and debuting several tattoos and piercings.<ref name=\"CareerBiggest\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/christina_aguilera/0,,,00.html|title=Christina Aguilera: Five Fun Facts|work=People|access-date=October 19, 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022140434/http://www.people.com/people/christina_aguilera/0,,,00.html|archive-date=October 22, 2013}}</ref> She co-headlined the [[Justified and Stripped Tour]] alongside Justin Timberlake from June to September 2003 in support of ''Stripped'' and Timberlake's album ''[[Justified (album)|Justified]]'' (2002), before embarking on her solo [[The Stripped Tour|Stripped Tour]] until December.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/justin-timberlake-and-christina-aguilera-double-trouble-20030626|title=Justin Timberlake and Christina Aguilera: Double Trouble|first=Jancee|last=Dunn|work=Rolling Stone|date=June 26, 2003|access-date=October 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.frontiertouring.com/index.php?action=retail&form_name=view_retail&merchant_id=595&sectionID=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325202833/http://www.frontiertouring.com/index.php?action=retail&form_name=view_retail&merchant_id=595&sectionID=|title=Frontier Touring: The Stripped Tour|publisher=Frontier Touring|archive-date=March 25, 2012}}</ref> Aguilera attended the [[2003 MTV Video Music Awards]] in August, where she and Britney Spears kissed [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] during their performance of \"[[Like a Virgin (song)|Like a Virgin]]\" and \"[[Hollywood (Madonna song)|Hollywood]]\", which received considerable media attention.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/madonna-magic-at-mtv-awards/|title=Madonna Magic At MTV Awards|last=Moody|first=Nekesa Mumbi|publisher=CBS News|date=August 29, 2003|access-date=February 22, 2013}}</ref> She was the host of the [[2003 MTV Europe Music Awards]], where she won [[MTV Europe Music Award for Best Female|Best Female]] award, in November.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1480240/its-justins-night-as-christina-kelly-osbourne-fight-at-mtv-europe-awards/|title=It's Justin's Night As Christina, Kelly Osbourne Fight At MTV Europe Awards|first=Jon|last=Wiederhorn|publisher=MTV News|date=November 6, 2003|access-date=October 20, 2013}}</ref> ''Billboard'' announced Aguilera as the Top Female Pop Act of 2003.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Year in Music 2003|journal=Billboard|page=68|volume=115|issue=52|date=December 27, 2003}}</ref>\n\n===2004\u20132009: Marriage, ''Back to Basics'', and first child===\n[[File:Christina Aguilera Sanremo.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Aguilera performing at the [[Sanremo Music Festival]] in 2006]]\nIn 2004, Aguilera recorded a [[Car Wash (song)#Christina Aguilera and Missy Elliott version|revised version]] of [[Rose Royce]]'s \"[[Car Wash (song)|Car Wash]]\" (1976) with Missy Elliott for the animated film ''[[Shark Tale]]'', in which she was a voice actress,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1491393/christina-aguilera-is-poisonous-in-video-with-missy-elliott/|title=Christina Aguilera Is Poisonous In Video With Missy Elliott|first=Jennifer|last=Vineyard|publisher=MTV News|date=September 24, 2004|access-date=October 21, 2013}}</ref> and contributed vocals to [[Nelly]]'s single \"[[Tilt Ya Head Back]]\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Singles: Essential Reviews|first=Michael|last=Paoletta|work=Billboard|date=September 25, 2004|volume=116|issue=39|page=55}}</ref> She was a featured artist on [[Herbie Hancock]]'s 2005 cover of [[Leon Russell]]'s \"[[A Song for You]]\" (1970), which was nominated for Best Pop Collaboration with Vocals at the [[48th Annual Grammy Awards]] in February 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/entertainment/music/bal-grammys-winners0209-htmlstory.html|title=Complete list of 2006 Grammy winners|newspaper=The Baltimore Sun|date=February 9, 2006|access-date=July 7, 2014}}</ref> During this time, Aguilera started working on her follow-up studio album and embraced a new image inspired by figures of the [[Classic Hollywood cinema|Classic Hollywood era]] such as [[Marilyn Monroe]], [[Marlene Dietrich]], and [[Mary Pickford]], debuting blonde curly hair and retro-styled makeup.<ref name=\"EW2004\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2004/08/30/highlights-2004-mtv-video-music-awards/|title=Highlights of the 2004 MTV Video Music Awards|first=Brian|last=Hiatt|date=August 30, 2004|access-date=January 22, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"HelloMag\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/music/2004/10/20/christinaaguliera/|title=Christina turns Hollywood pin-up in latest shoot|work=Hello!|date=October 20, 2004|access-date=October 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAguilera became engaged with marketing executive Jordan Bratman, with whom she had dated since 2003, in February 2005.<ref name=\"Marries\">{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,1131176,00.html|title=Christina Aguilera Marries|work=People|date=November 18, 2005|access-date=October 21, 2013}}</ref> They married on November 19, 2005, at an estate in [[Napa County, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/music/celebrity/christina-aguileras-highs-and-lows/ss-BBgQqMJ#image=9|title=Christina Aguilera's Highs and Lows|publisher=[[MSN]]|access-date=February 23, 2015}}</ref> Aguilera released the lead single from her fifth studio album, \"[[Ain't No Other Man]]\", in June 2006.<ref name=\"mtvnews4\">{{cite news|last=Vineyard|first=Jennifer|title='Ain't No Other Man' Video Has Christina Singing The Blues|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1534591/video-has-christina-singing-blues.jhtml|access-date=April 25, 2012|publisher=MTV News|date=June 19, 2006}}</ref> The song, like the majority of the album, was inspired by Aguilera's marriage and incorporates elements of early 20th-century soul, blues, and [[jazz]].<ref name=\"mtvnews\">{{cite news|last=Moss|first=Corey|title=Christina's New Split-Personality Album Is Mature And 'Dirrty'|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1529698/christinas-new-album-mature-dirrty.jhtml|access-date=April 25, 2012|publisher=MTV News|date=April 28, 2006}}</ref><ref name=\"ewb2b\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1225303,00.html|title=Back to Basics Review|first=Jody|last=Rosen|date=August 14, 2006|work=Entertainment Weekly|access-date=June 21, 2013}}</ref> It reached number six on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and has sold 1.7 million digital copies in the US as of 2014.<ref name=\"AguileraBBCharts\"/><ref name=\"AskBillboardCareer\"/> Its music video saw Aguilera debuting her new alter ego, Baby Jane, inspired by the thriller film ''[[What Ever Happened to Baby Jane? (1962 film)|What Ever Happened to Baby Jane?]]'' (1962).<ref name=\"mtvnews4\"/>\n\nThe album, titled ''[[Back to Basics (Christina Aguilera album)|Back to Basics]]'', was released in August 2006. Aguilera described the record, a [[double album]], as a \"throwback\" to jazz, blues, and soul music of the 1920s, 1930s, and 1940s that incorporates \"a modern twist.\"<ref name=\"B2BMusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1533622/christina-makes-her-comeback-twice-as-nice-by-expanding-basics-into-double-lp/|title=Christina Makes Her Comeback Twice As Nice By Expanding Basics Into Double LP|first1=Corey|last1=Moss|first2=Jeff|last2=Cornell|publisher=MTV News|date=June 6, 2006|access-date=October 22, 2013|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141012115058/http://www.mtv.com/news/1533622/christina-makes-her-comeback-twice-as-nice-by-expanding-basics-into-double-lp/|archive-date=October 12, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> She was much inspired by works of such classic blues and soul singers as [[Otis Redding]], [[Millie Jackson]], and [[Nina Simone]] during the recording sessions.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JhYEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA26|title=Old School|first=Melinda|last=Newman|work=Billboard|page=26|volume=118|issue=30|date=July 29, 2016|access-date=January 22, 2018}}</ref> ''Back to Basics'' received generally positive reviews from critics, who commented that the retro-oriented production complements Aguilera's vocals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/back-to-basics/christina-aguilera/critic-reviews|title=Critic Reviews for Back to Basics|website=Metacritic|access-date=January 22, 2018}}</ref> It debuted atop the ''Billboard'' 200 and has sold 1.7 million copies in the US.<ref name=\"AskBillboardCareer\"/> At the [[49th Annual Grammy Awards]] in February 2007, Aguilera won Best Female Pop Vocal Performance for \"Ain't No Other Man\", and performed \"[[It's a Man's Man's Man's World]]\" in tribute of the late [[James Brown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2007/SHOWBIZ/Music/02/11/grammy.awards/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021075431/http://edition.cnn.com/2007/SHOWBIZ/Music/02/11/grammy.awards/|title=A 'Nice' night for the Dixie Chicks|first=Todd|last=Leopold|publisher=CNN|date=February 12, 2007|archive-date=October 21, 2012}}</ref> ''Back to Basics'' was succeeded by two international top-ten singles: \"[[Hurt (Christina Aguilera song)|Hurt]]\" and \"[[Candyman (Christina Aguilera song)|Candyman]]\". Two other singles, \"[[Slow Down Baby]]\" and \"[[Oh Mother]]\", were released exclusively in Australia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sonybmg.com.au/news/details.do?newsId=20030829004728|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070904081540/http://sonybmg.com.au/news/details.do?newsId=20030829004728|title=Christina Aguilera Arrives In Town This Week!|publisher=Sony Music Australia|date=July 12, 2007|archive-date=September 4, 2007}}</ref> and Europe,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radioandrecords.com/formats/charts/euro/Switzerland.asp|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013015718/http://www.radioandrecords.com/formats/charts/euro/Switzerland.asp|title=Radio & Records: Swiss Top 20 Chart|work=Radio & Records|date=September 21, 2007|archive-date=October 13, 2007}}</ref> respectively. In support of ''Back to Basics'', Aguilera embarked on the [[Back to Basics Tour]], which ran from November 2006 to October 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1540564/christina-aguilera-reveals-european-tour-next-up-us-clubs/|title=Christina Aguilera Reveals European Tour \u2014 Next Up, U.S. Clubs|first=Jennifer|last=Vineyard|publisher=MTV News|date=September 11, 2006|access-date=October 23, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2008/11/145_5365.html|title=Christina Aguilera Shows Off Impressive Vocals|first=Cathy|last=Garcia|work=[[The Korea Times]]|date=June 25, 2007|access-date=June 11, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/aguilera-set-for-middle-east-debut|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110810070829/http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/aguilera-set-for-middle-east-debut|title=Aguilera set for Middle East debut|work=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]|first=Melanie|last=Swan|location=Abu Dhabi|date=October 23, 2008|archive-date=August 10, 2011}}</ref> With US$48.1 million grossed, the tour was the highest-grossing solo female tour of 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1047044/the-police-score-top-grossing-tour-of-07|title=The Police Score Top-Grossing Tour Of '07|date=December 13, 2007|work=Billboard|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007050948/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1047044/the-police-score-top-grossing-tour-of-07|archive-date=October 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2008, Aguilera gave birth to her child with Bratman, a son.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1579535/christina-aguilera-gives-birth-to-baby-boy/|title=Christina Aguilera Gives Birth to Baby Boy|publisher=MTV News|date=January 13, 2008|access-date=January 13, 2018}}</ref> Later that year, she appeared in the [[Martin Scorsese]] documentary ''[[Shine a Light (film)|Shine a Light]]'' chronicling a two-day [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]] concert in New York City's [[Beacon Theatre (New York City)|Beacon Theatre]], in which Aguilera performs \"[[Live with Me]]\" alongside the band's lead vocalist [[Mick Jagger]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/film/filmreviews/3672481/Film-reviews-Shine-a-Light-and-21.html|title=Film reviews: Shine a Light and 21|first=David|last=Gritten|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=April 11, 2008|access-date=August 28, 2013}}</ref> In commemoration of a decade-long career in the music industry, Aguilera released a [[greatest hits album]] titled ''[[Keeps Gettin' Better: A Decade of Hits]]'' exclusively through [[Target Corporation|Target]] in November 2008, in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1044276/target-scores-aguilera-hits-album-exclusive|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140831165331/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1044276/target-scores-aguilera-hits-album-exclusive|title=Target Scores Aguilera Hits Album Exclusive|first=Katie|last=Hasty|work=Billboard|date=September 3, 2008|archive-date=August 31, 2014|url-status=dead|access-date=July 8, 2014}}</ref> In addition to previous singles, it includes four original [[electropop]]-oriented songs, two of which are remade versions of two previous singles.<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707142741/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/christina-aguilera/albumguide|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/artists/christina-aguilera/albumguide|title=Christina Aguilera: Album Guide|work=Rolling Stone|archive-date=July 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1043616/hits-set-tees-up-next-christina-aguilera-album|title=Hits Set Tees Up Next Christina Aguilera Album|work=Billboard|date=October 31, 2008|first=Mariel|last=Conception|access-date=May 24, 2011}}</ref> Aguilera commented that the newly-recorded tracks' \"futurisic, robotic sound\" served as a preview for her follow-up studio album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1043491/christina-aguilera-better-and-better|title=Christina Aguilera: Better And 'Better'|first=Michael|last=Concepcion|date=November 14, 2008|access-date=January 24, 2018|work=Billboard}}</ref> ''Keeps Gettin' Better'' peaked at number nine on the ''Billboard'' 200, and its titular single \"[[Keeps Gettin' Better]]\" charted at number seven on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=\"AguileraBBCharts\"/> ''Billboard'' in 2009 recognized Aguilera as the 20th most successful artist of the 2000s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/266420/artists-of-the-decade|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140608034041/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/266419/artists-of-the-decade-page-two|title=Artists of the Decade|work=Billboard|archive-date=June 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2010\u20132011: ''Bionic'', ''Burlesque'', and ''The Voice''===\n[[File:Christina Aguilera (at premiere of \"To John With Love\", September 2010).jpg|thumb|upright|left|Aguilera at a [[Montblanc (company)|Montblanc]] event in 2010]]\nAguilera began work on her sixth studio album during pregnancy, when she frequently listened to [[electronic music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1641039/christina-aguilera-brings-new-songs-classic-hits-today-show.jhtml|title=Christina Aguilera Brings New Songs, Classic Hits To 'Today' Show|publisher=MTV News|first=James|last=Dinh|date=June 8, 2010|access-date=July 18, 2013}}</ref> The lead single from the album, \"[[Not Myself Tonight]]\", was released in March 2010.<ref name=\"releases\">{{cite web|url=http://www.clevelandleader.com/node/13444|title=New Christina Aguilera Album \"Bionic\" Out June 8th|first=Eugene|last=McCormick|newspaper=[[The Cleveland Leader]]|date=March 25, 2010|access-date=March 17, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203005849/http://www.clevelandleader.com/node/13444|archive-date=December 3, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Heavily influenced by electronic genres, the song signaled Aguilera's musical experiments on her forthcoming album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/christina-aguilera-hits-the-dance-floor-with-not-myself-tonight-20100331|title=Christina Aguilera Hits the Dance Floor With Not Myself Tonight|first=Daniel|last=Kreps|work=Rolling Stone|date=March 31, 2010|access-date=March 17, 2014}}</ref> It peaked at number 23 on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=\"AguileraBBCharts\"/> The album, titled ''[[Bionic (Christina Aguilera album)|Bionic]]'', was released in June 2010. Categorized as a R&B-flavored [[futurepop]] album by critics,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2010/06/album-review-christina-aguileras-bionic.html|title=Album review: Christina Aguilera's 'Bionic'|date=June 7, 2010|first=Margaret|last=Wappler|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=August 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-christina-aguilera-bionic-rca-1991440.html|title=Album: Christina Aguilera, Bionic (RCA)|first=Andy|last=Gill|work=The Independent|date=June 4, 2010|access-date=August 8, 2014}}</ref> ''Bionic'' lyrically revolves around sexual themes while also discussing [[feminism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jun/06/christina-aguilera-bionic-cd-review|title=Bionic {{!}} CD Review {{!}} Music|work=[[The Observer]]|first=Kitty|last=Empire|date=June 6, 2010|access-date=August 10, 2014}}</ref> Critical reaction to the album was mixed; reviewers commended Aguilera's experimentation with new styles, but found it forced and unnatural.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/bionic/christina-aguilera/critic-reviews|title=Critic Reviews for Bionic|website=Metacritic|access-date=January 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/07/arts/music/07choice.html?pagewanted=1&sq=bionic&st=cse&scp=1|title=New CD's|first=Jon|last=Pareles|author-link=Jon Pareles|work=The New York Times|date=June 7, 2010|access-date=August 8, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jun/03/christina-aguilera-bionic-cd-review|title=Christina Aguilera \u2013 Bi-On-Ic {{!}} CD Review|work=The Guardian|date=June 3, 2010|first=Alexis|last=Petridis|access-date=August 8, 2014}}</ref> The album peaked at number three on the ''Billboard'' 200 and has sold 332,000 copies in the US as of 2019. <ref name=salesupdate2019>{{cite web|title=Ask Billboard: A Supersized Mailbag in Honor of Lil Nas X & Billy Ray Cyrus' Record Run Atop the Hot 100|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/business/chart-beat/8528273/lil-nas-x-billy-ray-cyrus-christina-aguilera-ask-billboard-mailbag |work=Billboard |first=Gary |last=Trust |date=August 24, 2019 |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |accessdate=August 24, 2019}}</ref> The album spawned one other international single, \"[[You Lost Me]]\". Two other singles from the album, \"[[Woohoo (Christina Aguilera song)|Woohoo]]\" featuring rapper [[Nicki Minaj]] and \"[[I Hate Boys]]\", were released in the US and Europe,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=69239|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6QujmdbEt?url=http://www.fmqb.com/Article.asp?id=69239|title=Airplay Archive|work=FMQB|archive-date=July 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/be/album/woohoo-feat-nicki-minaj-single/id374246489|title=Woohoo \u2013 Single\n|publisher=iTunes Store Belgium|access-date=July 8, 2014}}</ref> and Australia, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themusicnetwork.com/music-releases/singles/2010/06/28/issue-793/Christina-Aguilera--i-Hate-Boys/|title=Christina Aguilera \u2013 I Hate Boys \u2013 Issue 793|work=[[The Music Network]]|date=June 28, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120406144504/http://www.themusicnetwork.com/music-releases/singles/2010/06/28/issue-793/Christina-Aguilera--i-Hate-Boys/|archive-date=April 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAguilera starred alongside [[Cher]] in the musical film ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2010/dec/11/cher-christina-aguilera-burlesque|title=Cher could teach Christina Aguilera a thing or two in Burlesque|work=The Guardian|first=John|last=Patterson|date=December 11, 2010|access-date=August 29, 2013}}</ref> Written and directed by [[Steve Antin]], the film was released in theaters in November 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2010-11-22-burlesque24_VA_N.htm|title=Director Antin had stars in his eyes when he cast 'Burlesque'|work=USA Today|first=Susan|last=Wloszczyna|date=November 23, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715104549/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2010-11-22-burlesque24_VA_N.htm|archive-date=July 15, 2014|url-status=dead|access-date=July 8, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera played Ali Rose, who quits her bar service job and moves to Los Angeles, where she aspires to be a performer in a [[American burlesque|burlesque]] club owned by Tess Scali (Cher). ''Burlesque'' grossed US$90 million in the box office<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=burlesque.htm|title=Burlesque (2010)|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|access-date=August 25, 2013}}</ref> and received mixed reviews from critics, who found it [[clich\u00e9]]d but praised Aguilera's acting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/burlesque|title='Burlesque' Reviews|website=Metacritic|access-date=May 2, 2014}}</ref> The film received a nomination for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]] at the [[68th Golden Globe Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/env-2011-globes-nom-list-scorecard-html-htmlstory.html|title=2011 Golden Globes nominees & winners|work=Los Angeles Times|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715024803/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/env-2011-globes-nom-list-scorecard-html-htmlstory.html|archive-date=July 15, 2014|url-status=dead|access-date=July 8, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera recorded eight tracks for the film's ten-track [[Burlesque: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|accompanying soundtrack]], and Cher performed the other two.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|others=Christina Aguilera, Cher|title=Burlesque: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|year=2010|type=inlay cover|publisher=Screen Gems, Inc|page=iTunes Digital Booklet}}</ref> The soundtrack reached number 18 on the ''Billboard'' 200 and was certified gold by the RIAA.<ref name=\"RIAA\"/><ref name=\"AguileraBBCharts\"/>\n\nAt the [[Super Bowl XLV]] in February 2011, Aguilera omitted a few lines while performing the US national anthem.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1657367/christina-aguilera-super-bowl/|title=Christina Aguilera Apologizes For Super Bowl National Anthem Flub|first=Gil|last=Kaulfman|publisher=MTV News|date=July 2, 2011|access-date=February 23, 2015}}</ref> She apologized for the incident, saying: \"I got so caught up in the moment of the song that I lost my place.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/entertainment/music/2011/02/07/17179721-wenn-story.html|title=Aguilera sorry for Super Bowl fumble|work=[[Toronto Sun]]|date=December 12, 2010|access-date=February 7, 2011}}</ref> At the [[53rd Annual Grammy Awards]], she performed alongside [[Jennifer Hudson]], [[Martina McBride]], [[Yolanda Adams]], and [[Florence Welch]], in a segment that paid tribute to soul singer [[Aretha Franklin]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Semigran|first=Aly|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1657852/christina-aguilera-jennifer-hudson-aretha-franklin-grammy-tribute/|title=Christina Aguilera, Jennifer Hudson Belt Out Aretha Franklin Grammy Tribute|publisher=MTV News|date=February 13, 2011|access-date=December 4, 2012}}</ref> Aguilera finalized her divorce from Jordan Bratman, from whom she had been separated since September 2010, on April 15, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/celebrity/2011-04-15/christina-aguileras-divorce-finalized-today/|title=Christina Aguilera's Divorce Finalized Today|publisher=VH1|first=Liz|last=Black|date=April 15, 2011|access-date=February 23, 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224150211/http://www.vh1.com/celebrity/2011-04-15/christina-aguileras-divorce-finalized-today/|archive-date=February 24, 2015}}</ref> She concurrently started dating Matthew Rutler, an assistant on the set of ''Burlesque''.<ref name=\"EngagedNY\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/christina-aguilera-engaged-boyfriend-matt-rutler-article-1.1615176|title=Christina Aguilera engaged to boyfriend Matt Rutler, reveals massive ring on Twitter|work=New York Daily News|location=New York|first=Nina|last=Golgowski|date=February 14, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140215032645/http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/christina-aguilera-engaged-boyfriend-matt-rutler-article-1.1615176|archive-date=February 15, 2014}}</ref> From April 2011 to December 2012, Aguilera served as a coach on the first three seasons of the television competition series ''[[The Voice (American TV series)|The Voice]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6281721/christina-aguilera-gwen-stefani-shakira-voice-poll|title=Christina Aguilera, Gwen Stefani or Shakira|work=Billboard|date=October 14, 2014|first=Katie|last=Atkinson|access-date=February 23, 2015}}</ref> During the first season, Aguilera was featured on [[Maroon 5]]'s single \"[[Moves like Jagger]]\" upon the invitation of the group's lead vocalist and Aguilera's fellow ''The Voice'' coach [[Adam Levine]]. The single peaked atop the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and has sold seven million digital copies worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1172581/maroon-5-and-christina-aguileras-moves-like-jagger-struts-to-no-1-on|title=Maroon 5 and Christina Aguilera's 'Moves Like Jagger' Struts To No. 1 on Billboard Hot 100|work=Billboard|date=August 31, 2011|first=Gary|last=Trust|access-date=August 31, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/news/read/bruno-mars-claims-2-best-selling-digital-songs-of-2011/047866|title=Bruno Mars claims 2 best-selling digital songs of 2011|work=[[Music Week]]|date=January 23, 2012|access-date=March 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2012\u20132017: ''Lotus'', second child, and television projects===\n[[File:Christina Aguilera - Breakthrough Prize Scientists, 2014.jpg|thumb|Christina during a performance in 2014]]\nUpon the third season of ''The Voice'' in September 2012, Aguilera released \"[[Your Body (Christina Aguilera song)|Your Body]]\" as the lead single from her seventh studio album.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474983/christina-aguilera-billboard-cover-story?page=0%2C1|title=Christina Aguilera: Billboard Cover Story|work=Billboard|first=Andrew|last=Hampp|date=September 21, 2012|access-date=September 1, 2013}}</ref> The single charted on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 at number 34.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474916/maroon-5-still-tops-hot-100-psy-one-step-from-no-1|title=Maroon 5 Still Tops Hot 100, PSY One Step From No. 1|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=September 26, 2012|access-date=September 7, 2013}}</ref> The album, titled ''[[Lotus (Christina Aguilera album)|Lotus]]'', followed in November 2012. Aguilera described the record as a \"rebirth\" of herself after the personal struggles she had overcome.<ref name=\"CareerBiggest\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/list/474045/christina-aguileras-top-10-biggest-career-moments?page=0%2C2|title=Christina Aguilera's Top 10 Biggest Career Moments|work=Billboard|date=November 21, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140613130053/http://www.billboard.com/articles/list/474045/christina-aguileras-top-10-biggest-career-moments?page=0%2C2|archive-date=June 13, 2014|first=Jason|last=Lipshutz|url-status=dead|access-date=June 20, 2014}}</ref> Contemporary reviewers found the album generic and conventional, as opposed to Aguilera's previous experimental ventures.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Review: Lotus|journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|location=London|date=January 2013|issue=318|page=101}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Caramanica|first1=Jon|last2=Pareles|first2=Jon|author-link2=Jon Pareles|last3=Ratliff|first3=Ben|date=November 13, 2012|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/13/arts/music/albums-by-christina-aguilera-soundgarden-and-brian-eno.html?_r=0|title=Albums by Christina Aguilera, Soundgarden and Brian Eno|page=34|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=November 17, 2012}}</ref> ''Lotus'' peaked at number seven on the ''Billboard'' 200 and has sold 303,000 copies in the US as of 2019. <ref name=salesupdate2019>{{cite web|title=Ask Billboard: A Supersized Mailbag in Honor of Lil Nas X & Billy Ray Cyrus' Record Run Atop the Hot 100|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/business/chart-beat/8528273/lil-nas-x-billy-ray-cyrus-christina-aguilera-ask-billboard-mailbag |work=Billboard |first=Gary |last=Trust |date=August 24, 2019 |publisher=Prometheus Global Media |accessdate=August 24, 2019}}</ref> The album was supported by one other single, \"[[Just a Fool]]\" featuring Aguilera's fellow ''The Voice'' coach [[Blake Shelton]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/reality-check/474076/christina-aguilera-blake-shelton-unveil-just-a-fool-on-the|title=Christina Aguilera, Blake Shelton Unveil 'Just a Fool' on 'The Voice'|work=Billboard|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|first=Jeff|last=Benjamin|date=November 20, 2012|access-date=June 18, 2013}}</ref> In December 2012, Aguilera was replaced by [[Shakira]] for the [[The Voice (U.S. season 4)|fourth season]] of ''The Voice''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474926/the-voice-locks-in-fourth-fifth-seasons-on-nbc|first=David|last=Greenwald|title='The Voice' Locks In Fourth, Fifth Seasons on NBC|work=Billboard|date=September 25, 2012|access-date=June 20, 2014}}</ref> She returned for the [[The Voice (U.S. season 5)|fifth season]] in September 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/462458/the-voice-season-5-premiere-coaches-christina-aguilera-and-cee-lo-green-make-a-triumphant-return|title=The Voice Season 5 Premiere: Coaches Christina Aguilera and Cee Lo Green Make a Triumphant Return|first=Leanne|last=Aguilera|publisher=E!|date=September 23, 2013|access-date=June 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Aguilera scored three international top-ten singles. She was featured on rapper [[Pitbull (rapper)|Pitbull]]'s \"[[Feel This Moment]]\", which peaked at number eight on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and was certified platinum by the RIAA.<ref name=\"RIAA\"/><ref name=\"AguileraBBCharts\"/> She subsequently appeared on Mexican singer [[Alejandro Fern\u00e1ndez]]'s cover of [[Miguel Gallardo]]'s \"[[Hoy Tengo Ganas de Ti#Alejandro Fern\u00e1ndez version|Hoy Tengo Ganas de Ti]]\" (1976), which earned a diamond certification in Mexico.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.amprofon.com.mx/certificaciones-amprofon.php?key=Alejandro+Fern%C3%A1ndez&action=Buscar&anio=&disquera=&tipoAlbum=&tipoCertificacion=|title=Certificaciones Amprofon|language=es|publisher=[[Asociaci\u00f3n Mexicana de Productores de Fonogramas y Videogramas]]|access-date=February 6, 2018|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20141022235531/http://www.amprofon.com.mx/certificaciones-amprofon.php?key=Alejandro+Fern%C3%A1ndez&action=Buscar&anio=&disquera=&tipoAlbum=&tipoCertificacion=|archive-date=October 22, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera collaborated with [[A Great Big World]] on the ballad \"[[Say Something (A Great Big World song)|Say Something]]\", which earned a six-time platinum certification from the RIAA<ref name=\"RIAA\"/> and won [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Duo/Group Performance|Best Pop Duo/Group Performance]] at the [[57th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/57th-annual-grammy-awards|title=57th Annual Grammy Awards|publisher=[[National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences]]|access-date=February 6, 2018}}</ref> Aguilera temporarily withdrew from ''The Voice'' for the [[The Voice (U.S. season 6)|sixth]] and [[The Voice (U.S. season 7)|seventh]] seasons, citing her desire to devote her time to her family. She was respectively replaced by Shakira and [[Gwen Stefani]] during the two seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/shakira-usher-return-voice-season-6-article-1.1551737|title=Shakira, Usher returning to 'The Voice' for Season 6|first=Zayda|last=Rivera|work=New York Daily News|date=December 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140906051505/http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/shakira-usher-return-voice-season-6-article-1.1551737|archive-date=September 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/christina-aguilera-gwen-stefani-the-voice-confirms-coach-2014294|title=Christina Aguilera Welcomes Gwen Stefani to The Voice, Confirms Singer's Role as Season 7 Coach|work=Us Weekly|date=April 29, 2014|access-date=February 23, 2015}}</ref> After her engagement to Matthew Rutler in February 2014 and the birth of their daughter in August,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-christina-aguilera-baby-girl-name-matthew-rutler-20140818-story.html|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=August 18, 2014|access-date=August 18, 2014|title=Christina Aguilera welcomes, names new baby girl with Matthew Rutler|first=Christie|last=D'Zurilla}}</ref> she returned for the [[The Voice (U.S. season 8)|eighth season]] in October.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/6281700/christina-aguilera-returning-the-voice-season-8|title=Goodbye, Gwen: Christina Aguilera Returning to 'The Voice'|date=October 14, 2014|work=Billboard|first=Joe|last=Lynch|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> Aguilera's one more season with ''The Voice'' was the [[The Voice (U.S. season 10)|tenth]], in which she won with her contestant [[Alisan Porter]] in May 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/alisan-porter-makes-christina-aguilera-first-winning-female-voice-coach/|title=Alisan Porter makes Christina Aguilera first winning female 'Voice' coach|publisher=CBS News|last=Park|first=Andrea|date=May 25, 2016|access-date=May 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAguilera played a recurring role as singer Jade St. John, a pop singer who tries to venture out to [[country music]], on the [[Nashville (season 3)|third season]] of [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s musical drama series ''[[Nashville (2012 TV series)|Nashville]]'' in April 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Berman|first1=Eliza|title=Watch Christina Aguilera Vamp It Up on a Sneak Peak From Nashville|work=Time|date=April 9, 2015|url=http://time.com/3816030/christina-aguilera-nashville/|access-date=May 1, 2015}}</ref> She and her partner Rutler served as executive producers for a music-based game show, ''Tracks'', which aired on [[Spike TV]] in March 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wagmeister|first1=Elizabeth|title=Christina Aguilera Producing Music Game Show for Spike TV|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/tracks-game-show-christina-aguilera-spike-tv-1201730419/|access-date=March 16, 2016|work=Variety|date=March 15, 2016}}</ref> Aguilera recorded a song titled \"[[Change (Christina Aguilera song)|Change]]\", which she dedicated to the victims of the [[2016 Orlando nightclub shooting]] as well as [[Christina Grimmie]], who was fatally shot in Orlando the day before the nightclub shooting. The proceedings were donated to the National Compassion Fund to benefit the victims' families.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/watch-christina-aguilera-belt-orlando-tribute-change-on-kimmel-20160624|title=Watch Christina Aguilera Belt Orlando Tribute 'Change' on 'Kimmel'|work=Rolling Stone|first=Ryan|last=Reed|date=June 24, 2016|access-date=February 6, 2018}}</ref> Her other works included recording a [[disco]] song titled \"[[Telepathy (Christina Aguilera song)|Telepathy]]\" featuring [[Nile Rodgers]] for the soundtrack of [[Netflix]] original series ''[[The Get Down]]'' (2016),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/08/11/christina-aguilera-telepathy/|title=Christina Aguilera's Telepathy: Xtina returns to the dance floor|first=Joey|last=Nolfl|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=August 11, 2016|access-date=February 6, 2018}}</ref> being a voice actress for ''[[The Emoji Movie]]'' (2017),<ref>{{cite news|last1=French|first1=Megan|last2=Blynn|first2=Jamie|title=Meet Christina Aguilera's 'Emoji Movie' Character Akiko Glitter: First Pic!|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/meet-christina-aguileras-emoji-movie-character-first-pic-w482253|access-date=May 15, 2017|work=Us Weekly|date=May 15, 2017}}</ref> and starring in the romantic science fiction film ''[[Zoe (film)|Zoe]]'' (2018).<ref>{{cite news|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Christina Aguilera, Theo James, Rashida Jones Join Sci-Fi Romance 'Zoe'|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/christina-aguilera-theo-james-rashida-jones-romance-zoe-1202404532/|access-date=May 2, 2017|work=Variety|date=May 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2018\u2013present: ''Liberation'' and The Xperience===\n[[File:Liberation Tour (31108487277).jpg|thumb|Christina Aguilera performing at the Pepsi Center on October 19, 2018 on her Liberation Tour]]\nAguilera started work on her new album in the summer of 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6457974/christina-aguilera-next-album-pharrell-williams|title=Christina Aguilera Talks Next Album, Working with Pharrell Williams on New Music|last=Lipshut|first=Jason|date=January 30, 2015|work=Billboard|access-date=May 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.papermag.com/christina-aguilera-transformation-2553214651.html|title=Christina Aguilera Is Back With a New Transformation|last1=Lodi|first1=Marie|date=March 26, 2018|work=[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]|access-date=May 6, 2018}}</ref> Its release was preceded by two singles: \"[[Accelerate (Christina Aguilera song)|Accelerate]]\" featuring [[Ty Dolla Sign]] and [[2 Chainz]] and \"[[Fall in Line]]\" featuring [[Demi Lovato]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/5264447/christina-aguileras-accelerate/|title=Christina Aguilera Is Back With a New Rap-Forward Single|date=May 3, 2018|work=Time|access-date=May 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/hear-christina-aguileras-fall-in-line-with-demi-lovato-w520357|title=Hear Christina Aguilera's Empowering New Song 'Fall in Line' With Demi Lovato|last=Kreps|first=Daniel|date=May 16, 2018|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=May 19, 2018}}</ref> The album, titled ''[[Liberation (Christina Aguilera album)|Liberation]]'', was released in June 15, 2018 to favorable reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/liberation/christina-aguilera|title=Reviews for Liberation by Christina Aguilera|website=Metacritic|access-date=October 31, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/christina-aguileras-liberation-w521561|title=Review: Christina Aguilera Flexes Her Diva Power on the Excellent 'Liberation'|last=Spanos|first=Brittany|date=June 14, 2018|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=June 19, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/13/arts/music/christina-aguilera-liberation-review.html|title=Christina Aguilera Exults in Her Voice on \u2018Liberation\u2019|last=Pareles|first=Jon|date=June 13, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 21, 2018}}</ref> Aguilera heavily incorporated R&B and hip hop on the album to represent her desire for freedom from what she described as the \"churning hamster wheel\" that was ''The Voice''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/magazine-feature/8446904/christina-aguilera-new-album-liberation-interview-cover-story-2018|title=Christina Aguilera on 'Longing for Freedom' & Her Hip-Hop-Inspired Return to Music|last=Jones|first=Allie|date=May 3, 2018|work=Billboard|access-date=July 1, 2019}}</ref> ''Liberation'' debuted at number six on the ''Billboard'' 200 chart, becoming Aguilera's seventh US top-ten album.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8462423/5-seconds-of-summer-third-no-1-album-billboard-200-chart|title=5 Seconds of Summer Earn Third No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart With 'Youngblood'|last1=Caulfield|first1=Keith|date=June 24, 2018|work=Billboard|access-date=July 13, 2018}}</ref> At the [[61st Annual Grammy Awards]], \"Fall in Line\" was nominated for Best Pop Duo/Group Performance, and the album track \"[[Like I Do (Christina Aguilera song)|Like I Do]]\", which featured [[GoldLink]] was nominated for [[Best Rap/Sung Performance]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/61st-annual-grammy-awards|title=61st Annual GRAMMY Awards|date=December 6, 2018|publisher=National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences|access-date=December 14, 2018}}</ref> \n\nTo promote ''Liberation'', Aguilera embarked on a US tour, the [[Liberation Tour]], which ran from September to November 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8455203/christina-aguilera-liberation-tour-dates|title=Christina Aguilera Announces Liberation Tour, First Outing Since 2008|date=May 9, 2018|access-date=May 9, 2018|first=Kaufman|last=Gil|work=Billboard}}</ref> and a European tour, [[The X Tour (Christina Aguilera)|The X Tour]], which ran from July to December 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7714327/christina-aguilera-announces-the-x-tour?chrome=1|title=She's Coming, Europe! Christina Aguilera Announces 'The X Tour'|first=Mike|last=Nied|website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|date=March 4, 2019|access-date=June 29, 2019}}</ref> She also headlined [[The Xperience]], a 25-date concert residency at the [[Zappos Theater]] in [[Las Vegas]] beginning in May and concluding in March 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8495496/christina-aguilera-brings-the-xperience-to-las-vegas|title=Christina Aguilera Brings 'The Xperience' to Las Vegas|date=January 29, 2019|work=Billboard|first=Melinda|last=Sheckells}}</ref> In 2019, Aguilera received [[Disney Legend|The Disney Legends Awards]] for \"her remarkable contributions to the Disney legacy\".<ref>https://d23.com/2019-disney-legends/?disney2</ref> In October 2019, Aguilera released the song \"Haunted Heart\" from the soundtrack of the computer-animated ''[[The Addams Family (2019 film)|Addams Family]]'' film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/snoop-dogg-and-migos-share-new-song-for-the-addams-family-listen/|title=Snoop Dogg and Migos Share New Song for The Addams Family: Listen|website=Pitchfork|last=Moreland|first=Quinn|date=September 13, 2019|accessdate=September 14, 2019}}</ref>. On March 6, 2020, Aguilera released \"Loyal Brave True\" as a promotional single from the upcoming live action remake of ''[[Mulan (2020 film)|Mulan]]''<ref>cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/christina-aguilera-mulan-new-song-loyal-brave-true-964115/amp/|title=Christina Aguilera Returns to Her Disney Roots with New Song}}</ref>. She has also announced that she will release a re-recording of \"Reflection\" during her Xperience show.\n\n==Artistry==\n===Voice===\nAguilera is a [[soprano]],<ref name=\"GuardianSexual\">{{cite news|first=Hermione|last=Hoby|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/jun/13/christina-aguilera-interview-bionic|title=Christina Aguilera: 'I'm a very sexual person by nature'|work=The Guardian|date=June 13, 2010|access-date=November 5, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"EverythingSinging\">{{Cite book|title=The Everything Singing Book with CD: From Mastering Breathing Techniques to Performing Live\u2014all You Need to Hit the Right Notes|last=Sheppard|first=Bettina|author-link=|year=2008|publisher=Everything Books|location=|isbn=|page=100|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=FQ4ItFJXHEwC&pg=PA100&lpg=PA100&dq=Christina+Aguilera+AND+soprano#v=onepage&q=Christina%20Aguilera%20AND%20soprano|access-date=November 18, 2017|df=mdy-all}}{{dead link|date=October 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2011/aug/26/home/la-hm-hotprop-christina-aguilera-20110826|title=Christina Aguilera sells Sunset Strip-area home|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=August 26, 2011|access-date=February 21, 2018|first=Lauren|last=Beale}}</ref> possessing a four-octave [[vocal range]] spanning from [[C (musical note)|C<sub>3</sub>]] to [[C\u266f (musical note)|C\u266f<sub>7</sub>]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Gayles|first=Contessa|title=10 Things You Didn't Know About 'The Voice' Coach and 'Dirrty' Pop Star Christina Aguilera|url=http://blog.music.aol.com/2011/05/24/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-voice-christina-aguilera/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110601042700/http://blog.music.aol.com/2011/05/24/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-the-voice-christina-aguilera|archive-date=June 1, 2011|date=May 24, 2011|publisher=[[AOL]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/105319/compare-vocal-ranges-of-worlds-greatest-singers/|title=This Interactive Chart Compares the Vocal Ranges of the World's Greatest Singers|first=Samantha|last=Grossman|date=May 20, 2014|access-date=July 21, 2014|work=Time}}</ref> Since the start of her career Aguilera's voice has been compared to that of [[Mariah Carey]] and [[Whitney Houston]].<ref name=\"NYTimesVoice\"/> [[David Browne (journalist)|David Browne]] writing for ''The New York Times'' noted that Aguilera's vocal performance was highly influenced by Carey and Houston, sharing that \"Aguilera has been one of the foremost practitioners of the overpowering, Category 5 vocal style known as [[melisma]]\", and \"Ms. Carey, Ms. Houston and Ms. Aguilera, to name its three main champions, are most associated with the period from the late '80s through the late '90s\".<ref name=\"NYTimesVoice\">{{cite news|last=Browne|first=David|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 24, 2010|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/26/arts/music/26browne.html|title=Trilling Songbirds Clip Their Wings|access-date=January 4, 2010}}</ref> A journal by Ann Powers for the ''Los Angeles Times'' said there are influences of [[Barbra Streisand]], [[Gladys Knight]] and [[Aretha Franklin]] on Aguilera's vocal style, opining that the \"Aguilera's Streisand-esque tendencies\" \"[help Aguilera] figure out how to become the 'great singer' she's been dubbed since she released her first single, the wise-beyond-its-years 'Genie in a Bottle', at 18\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Powers|first=Ann|work=Los Angeles Times|date=August 15, 2006|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2006/aug/15/entertainment/et-christina15|title=Old-school? Her?|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130301065054/http://articles.latimes.com/2006/aug/15/entertainment/et-christina15|archive-date=March 1, 2013}}</ref> [[Sasha Frere-Jones]] wrote in ''[[The New Yorker]]'', \"Aguilera doesn't need to reincarnate [[Sarah Vaughan]] to be a serious singer. She already is one, in the tradition of nineteen-nineties pop and R&B, skillfully deploying [[melisma]] for razzle-dazzle\".<ref name=\"NewYorker\">{{cite news|last=Frere-Jones|first=Sasha|title=Sex Symbols|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2006/09/04/sex-symbols|access-date=August 12, 2013|work=[[The New Yorker]]|date=September 4, 2006}}</ref> In 2003, Aguilera was placed fifth on MTV's \"Best Voices in Music Ever\" list,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ranker.com/list/mtv_s-best-voices-in-music-ever-v1/music-lover|title=MTV's Best Voices in Music Ever|work=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|date=March 1, 2003|access-date=July 31, 2015}}</ref> while ranking atop both COVE and Latina magazine's best Pop and Latina vocalist of all time in 2004 and 2013, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://popdirt.com/christina-aguilera-named-best-vocalist-by-cove/33315/|title=Christina Aguilera Named Best Vocalist By Cove|publisher=Popdirt|date=October 5, 2004|access-date=July 31, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latina.com/entertainment/music/best-latin-singers-pop-stars-all-time|title=THE 50 BEST LATINO SINGERS OF ALL TIME!|work=Latina Magazine|date=February 8, 2013|access-date=July 31, 2015}}</ref> In a review for ''Liberation'', [[Jon Pareles]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' commented on Aguilera's vocal versatility: \"Nothing less than high drama suits Christina Aguilera's voice. She can be brassy, tearful, sultry, gritty, breathy, sweet or furious. She can belt and she can tease; she can aim a note as directly as a missile or turn its trajectory into an aerobatic spiral of leaping, quivering, scalloping melismas. Her voice is not an instrument for making modest statements; it's about peaks of self-affirmation, indescribable sensual pleasures, steely counterattacks and abysses of sorrow\".<ref name=\"liberationreview\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/13/arts/music/christina-aguilera-liberation-review.html|title=Christina Aguilera Exults in Her Voice on 'Liberation'|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 13, 2018|access-date=June 14, 2018|first=Jon|last=Parales}}</ref>\n\nAguilera has, however, been criticized for her excessive use of melisma and [[oversinging]] on songs and in concerts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-17039208|title=Whitney Houston and the art of melisma|first=Lauren|last=Everitt|work=BBC News|date=February 15, 2012|access-date=July 11, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"EWOver\">{{cite web|last=William|first=Chris|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=December 11, 2001|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,91277,00.html|title=Genie at Full Throttle|access-date=July 11, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"MTVOver\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1523040/the-scourge-of-american-idol-oversingers/|title=The Scourge Of 'American Idol': Oversingers|first=Corey|last=Moss|publisher=MTV News|date=February 2, 2006|access-date=July 11, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"SeattleOver\">{{cite web|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/entertainment/2003633250_oversinging26.html|title=Wo-o-o, whoa: Stop oversinging!|first=Preston|last=Jones|work=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]|date=March 26, 2007|access-date=July 11, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fseattletimes.com%2Fhtml%2Fentertainment%2F2003633250_oversinging26.html&date=2013-02-02|archive-date=February 2, 2013}}</ref> John Eskow of ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' named Aguilera a main proponent for \"oversouling\", described as the \"gratuitous and confected melisma\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Eskow|first=John|title=Christina Aguilera and the Hideous Cult of Oversouling|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/john-eskow/christina-aguilera-and-th_b_819979.html|access-date=December 5, 2012|work=HuffPost|date=February 8, 2011}}</ref> Lucy Davies, a writer for [[BBC Music]], opined that although Aguilera had \"a stunning voice\", she \"could be more varied, simply by cutting out some of the 'y-e-e-eeeh, woah yeh's'\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Davies|first1=Lucy|title=Christina Aguilera Back to Basics Review|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/4g25|publisher=[[BBC Music]]|access-date=June 15, 2014|date=August 14, 2006}}</ref> Longtime producer [[Linda Perry]], who wrote the song \"Beautiful\", revealed about the recording sessions with Aguilera, \"I tried to keep it straight. I told her to get rid of the finger waves. Every time she'd start going into 'hoo-ha', I'd stop the tape. I'm like, 'You're doing it again'\". Perry ended up using the song's first take adding, \"She had a hard time accepting that as the final track. She's a perfectionist. She knows her voice really well, and she knows what's going on. She can hear things that nobody else would catch.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Hiatt|first=Brian|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=October 29, 2002|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,385297_2,00.html|title='Dirrty' Work (page 2)|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070619120647/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0%2C%2C385297_2%2C00.html|archive-date=June 19, 2007|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> An editor from ''Entertainment Weekly'', Chris Willman, stated that the oversinging on Aguilera's albums was inspired by Carey, writing that \"the Mariah venerators don't get away with it so easily. Aguilera, for one thing, has a slightly nasal tone that really only becomes obvious when she's overselling a song\".<ref name=\"EWOver\"/>\n\n===Influences===\n[[File:Etta James 2006.jpg|thumb|upright|Aguilera cites [[Etta James]] ''(pictured)'' as her main influence]]\nAguilera has credited blues singer [[Etta James]] as her main influence and inspiration, elaborating, \"Etta is my all-time favorite singer. I've said it for the last seven years \u2013 since I had my first debut record out \u2013 in every interview\".<ref name=\"EttaJames\">{{cite news|last=Vineyard|first=Jennifer|date=June 28, 2006|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1535359/christina-aguilera-can-die-happy-shes-bonded-with-bad-girl-idol-etta-james/|title=Christina Aguilera Can Die Happy \u2013 She's Bonded With 'Bad Girl' Idol Etta James|publisher=MTV News|access-date=June 12, 2014}}</ref> Following James' death in 2012, Aguilera was asked to perform \"[[At Last]]\" at James' funeral.<ref>{{cite news|last=Martinez|first=Michael|title=Etta James remembered as an authentic voice at funeral|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/01/28/showbiz/etta-james-funeral/index.html|publisher=CNN|access-date=January 29, 2012|date=January 28, 2012}}</ref> Prior to the performance, Aguilera revealed, \"There's a line in this song that says 'I found a dream that I could speak to.' And for me that dream, all my life, has been Etta James\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Farley|first=Christopher|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=January 29, 2012|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2012/01/29/christina-aguilera-sings-at-last-at-etta-james-funeral/|title=Christina Aguilera Sings 'At Last' at Etta James Funeral|access-date=June 12, 2014}}</ref> Other classic artists, including [[Billie Holiday]], [[Otis Redding]], [[Aretha Franklin]], [[Nina Simone]], and [[Ella Fitzgerald]], are also Aguilera's major influences; her fifth studio album ''Back to Basics'' is inspired by vintage jazz, blues and soul music records by them.<ref>{{cite news|last=Moss|first=Corey|title=Christina's New Split-Personality Album Is Mature And 'Dirrty'|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1529698/christinas-new-split-personality-album-is-mature-and-dirrty/|access-date=June 15, 2014|publisher=MTV News|date=April 27, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Vineyard|first1=Jennifer|last2=Norris|first2=John|last3=Edwards|first3=Luc|title=Christina Aguilera's Old Soul|url=http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/aguilera_christina/news_feature_080906/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140805022136/http://www.mtv.com/bands/a/aguilera_christina/news_feature_080906/|archive-date=August 5, 2014|access-date=June 15, 2014|publisher=MTV News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1531567/for-the-record-quick-news-on-christina-aguilera-jennifer-lopez-snoop-dogg-jessica-simpson-bjork-more/|title=For The Record: Quick News On Christina Aguilera, Jennifer Lopez, Snoop Dogg, Jessica Simpson, Bjork & More|publisher=MTV News|date=May 11, 2006|access-date=February 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAguilera mentions [[Whitney Houston]] as another influence,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stylist.co.uk/home/whitney-houston-singers-she-inspired|work=[[Stylist (magazine)|Stylist]]|title=Whitney Houston's prot\u00e9g\u00e9es: Christina Aguilera|access-date=June 18, 2014|first=Anna|last=Pollitt|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714185522/http://www.stylist.co.uk/home/whitney-houston-singers-she-inspired|archive-date=July 14, 2014}}</ref> having performed many of her songs in her early years during talent shows.<ref name=\"WashingtonPost\"/> She also cites [[Mariah Carey]] and [[Celine Dion]] as an inspiration, and covered the latter's songs: \"These Are the Special Times\" on ''[[My Kind of Christmas]]'', and \"[[The Prayer (Celine Dion and Andrea Bocelli song)|The Prayer]]\" on the NBC reality singing competition ''[[The Voice (U.S. season 2)|The Voice]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Matter of Time Christina Aguilera Says She'll Leave The Pack, Including Britney Spears in the Dust|work=[[Hartford Courant]]|last=Catlin|first=Roger|page=10|date=August 31, 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UoINJdqVsdw|title=Christina Aguilera talks about Celine Dion|via=YouTube|date=April 26, 2013|access-date=April 18, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera's debut album producer Ron Harris revealed that Aguilera during her recording sessions for ''[[Christina Aguilera (album)|Christina Aguilera]]'' would constantly listen to [[Brandy Norwood|Brandy]]'s music, studying and trying to replicate her adlibs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bS2ncjBBC2k|title=Film & Music Industry Forum - Ron Harris 3-7-16|last=Loyola University Film and Music Industry Studies|date=May 3, 2016|access-date=June 21, 2018|via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> According to author Pier Dominguez of the book ''Christina Aguilera: A Star Is Made'', Aguilera stated that Carey and her debut single, \"[[Vision of Love]]\" (1990), had the biggest influence on her vocal style.<ref>{{harvnb|Dominguez|2003|page=134}}</ref> Aguilera points out the musical film ''[[The Sound of Music (film)|The Sound of Music]]'' and its lead actress, [[Julie Andrews]], as her first inspiration for singing and performing.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rosen|first=Craig|url=http://music.yahoo.com/read/story/12058962|title=Christina Aguilera Climbs Every Mountain For 'My Kind Of Christmas'|publisher=Yahoo! Music|date=September 29, 2000|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524205307/http://music.yahoo.com/read/story/12058962|archive-date=May 24, 2011}}</ref> At the age of six, the film helped Aguilera cope with her violent childhood, \"Bad things happened in my home; there was violence. ''The Sound of Music'' looked like a form of release.\"<ref name=\"WMagazine\"/> Aguilera credits [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] and [[Janet Jackson]] as two biggest inspirations for her image, \"for being re-inventive and being brave as strong females, to explore whatever, even if they do get bad press. It's just like they were fearless.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sculley|first=Alan|title=What Christina wants|newspaper=[[The Patriot Ledger]]|page=17|date=September 8, 2000}}</ref> During the promotion of ''Back to Basics'', her image was also inspired by the \"Golden age of Hollywood\" actresses including [[Marlene Dietrich]], [[Marilyn Monroe]], [[Carole Lombard]], [[Greta Garbo]] and [[Veronica Lake]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Moss|first=Corey|title=Christina Channels Marilyn Monroe For Intimate Album Cover|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1535431/christina-channels-marilyn-monroe-for-intimate-album-cover/|access-date=June 15, 2014|publisher=MTV News|date=June 29, 2006}}</ref> Aguilera is also inspired by her ''Burlesque'' co-star, [[Cher]]: \"I have always had tremendous respect for her. She is a woman who did everything before anyone else did it. She is an icon and she inspired me through some of my career. We've had similar costumes too!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/offbeat/articles/2010/02/08/20100208christina-aguilera.html|title=Christina Aguilera inspired by Cher|work=[[The Arizona Republic]]|date=February 8, 2010|access-date=July 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Musical style and themes===\n[[File:Understand - Christina Aguilera.jpg|thumb|upright|Aguilera performing during her [[Back to Basics Tour]] in 2006]]\nAguilera frequently blends elements of pop, [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[dance-pop]] and [[soul music|soul]] music into her projects,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/07/arts/music/07choice.html|title=New CDs|first=Jon|last=Pareles|author-link=Jon Pareles|newspaper=The New York Times|date=June 6, 2010|access-date=June 7, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dallasobserver.com/2004-03-04/music/ladies-night-out-tour/|title=Ladies Night Out Tour|work=[[Dallas Observer]]|quote=With all the attention lavished on female R&B stars like [...] Christina Aguilera|date=March 4, 2004|first=Mikael|last=Wood|access-date=February 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Genie out of a bottle|first=Peter|last=Holder|first2=Jo|last2=Casamento|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)|The Daily Telegraph]]|location=Australia|page=16|date=March 10, 2000}}</ref> and her records typically include a combination of ballads and uptempo tracks.<ref name=\"NYTimesShrunk\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/17/arts/music/17sann.html|title=Honey They've Shrunk the Pop Stars (but Christina Aguilera Fights On)|first=Kelefa|last=Sanneh|work=The New York Times|date=August 17, 2006|access-date=July 9, 2014}}</ref> ''Christina Aguilera'' (1999) prominently displayed [[teen pop]] and dance-pop music,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/christina-aguilera-mw0000244313|title=Christina Aguilera \u2013 Christina Aguilera|first=Stephen Thomas|last=Erlewine|website=AllMusic|access-date=July 9, 2014}}</ref> while ''Mi Reflejo'' (2000) takes inspiration from [[Latin music (genre)|Latin music]].<ref name=\"MiReflejoNYPost\">{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2000/09/12/christinas-a-winner-in-spanish-too/|title=Christina's a winner in Spanish, too|last=Aquilante|first=Dan|newspaper=New York Post|date=September 12, 2000|access-date=May 31, 2013}}</ref> Her first Christmas album, ''My Kind of Christmas'', combines covers of Christmas standards and several original dance-pop tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/my-kind-of-christmas-mw0000100386|title=My Kind of Christmas by Christina Aguilera on AllMusic|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012025651/http://www.allmusic.com/album/my-kind-of-christmas-mw0000100386|archive-date=October 12, 2012|access-date=September 13, 2012|website=AllMusic|first=Stephen|last=Erlewine|url-status=dead}}</ref> Aiming for musical diversity and artistic growth, Aguilera worked with R&B, rock, [[hip hop music|hip hop]], and Latin music for ''Stripped'' (2002).<ref name=\"NotYourPuppet\"/><ref name=\"Stripped\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,384149~4~0~stripped,00.html|title=Stripped Review|last=Browne|first=David|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=November 1, 2002|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012121321/http://ew.com/ew/article/0%2C%2C384149~4~0~stripped%2C00.html|archive-date=October 12, 2007|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> David Browne from ''Entertainment Weekly'' credited the release with distancing Aguilera from her pop contemporaries.<ref name=\"Stripped\"/> Aguilera leaned towards R&B, [[blues]], jazz, and [[Soul music|soul]] on ''Back to Basics'' (2006).<ref name=\"B2BMusic\"/><ref name=\"LATimes\">{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2007/mar/07/entertainment/et-aguilera7|title=Props mistress|last=Powers|first=Ann|work=Los Angeles Times|date=March 7, 2007|access-date=May 28, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"TheObserver\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2006/aug/13/shopping.christinaaguilera|title=Christina Aguilera, Back to Basics|first=Paul|last=Flynn|newspaper=[[The Observer]]|date=August 12, 2006|access-date=May 3, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn contrast, ''Bionic'' (2010) sees significant use from futuristic [[electronic music]], described as an [[electropop]] album.<ref name=\"ElectronicBionic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1641039/christina-aguilera-brings-new-songs-classic-hits-to-today-show/|title=Christina Aguilera Brings New Songs, Classic Hits To 'Today' Show|first=James|last=Dinh|publisher=MTV News|date=June 8, 2010|access-date=July 8, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/bionic-mw0001989957|title=Bionic \u2013 Christina Aguilera {{!}} Overview|website=[[AllMusic]]|first=Thomas|last=Stephen Erlewine|author-link=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|access-date=August 8, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120711102448/http://www.allmusic.com/album/bionic-mw0001989957|archive-date=July 11, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D05E6D71230F934A35752C1A9669D8B63|title=For Gays, New Songs of Survival (page 2)|work=[[The New York Times]]|first=Alex|last=Hagwood|date=November 7, 2010|access-date=August 16, 2014}}</ref> The soundtrack for her 2010 feature film ''[[Burlesque (2010 American film)|Burlesque]]'' (2010) was influenced by ''Cabaret'', and featured several established songs that were redone as dance numbers in a fashion similar to ''Moulin Rouge!'' (2001).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2007/film/news/screen-gems-enlists-antin-for-burlesque-1117974104/|title=Screen Gems enlists Antin for 'Burlesque'|work=Variety|date=October 15, 2007|first=Michael|last=Fleming|access-date=February 23, 2015}}</ref> Aguilera partnered with mainstream producers including [[Shellback (producer)|Shellback]] and [[Max Martin]] during production of ''Lotus'' (2012); when discussing her interactions with the latter, she commented that \"He's known about me but we haven't crossed paths,\" adding \"Those records were the kind I wanted to stray apart from. If you look at what I did in the past (after my debut), I always try to do things that will challenge me and challenge the listener, too.\"<ref name=\"Billboard Cover\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/474983/christina-aguilera-billboard-cover-story|title=Christina Aguilera: Billboard Cover Story|last=Hampp|first=Andrew|work=Billboard|date=September 21, 2012|access-date=July 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAguilera stated that she feels a sense of responsibility to reference portions of her personal life so that \"people that can relate might not feel as alone in the circumstance.\" Many of her works consequently discuss love; she has also co-written two tracks which dealt with the domestic abuse throughout her childhood.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/57547/basic-instinct|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114034718/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/57547/basic-instinct|title='Basic' Instinct|work=Billboard|date=August 13, 2006|archive-date=January 14, 2009}}</ref> Aguilera has frequently mentioned [[feminism]] in her music; she has expressed her belief that sexuality is \"very empowering\", and has commented that \"If I want to be sexual, it's for my own appreciation and enjoyment! That's why I like to talk about the fact that sometimes I am attracted to women. I appreciate their femininity and beauty.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20393540,00.html|title=Christina Aguilera: Why I'm Sometimes Attracted to Women|last=Oh|first=Eunice|work=People|date=June 11, 2010|access-date=May 11, 2013}}</ref> She has alluded to her physical attractions to women in other interviews as well.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stein|first1=Joshua David|title=Christina Aguilera Reclaims The Fame|url=https://www.out.com/entertainment/music/2010/05/16/christina-aguilera-reclaims-fame|work=Out Magazine|publisher=Here Publishing Inc.|date=May 16, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bendix|first1=Trish|title=Christina Aguilera: What she's said about her sexuality|url=http://www.afterellen.com/people/80238-christina-aguilera-what-shes-said-about-her-sexuality|work=After Ellen|publisher=Evolve Media LLC|date=October 15, 2010|quote=Two women are way sexier than two men in bed. We have a better feel for our bodies. I love experimenting with my sexuality. [...] If that means girls then so be it. It would be wrong to hide this side of my personality. [...] I don't get to kiss all the girls and the boys, but my husband knows that I get into girls. I think it's fun to be open and play. ... I definitely love women. I think they're more attractive to the naked eye.}}</ref> Her \"Can't Hold Us Down\" from ''Stripped'' denounces gender-related [[double standard]]s, in which men are applauded for their sexual behaviors, while women who behave in a similar fashion are disdained.<ref>{{harvnb|Railton|Watson|2011|page=88}}</ref> The main theme of ''Bionic'' was also about woman empowerment; Hermione Hoby from ''[[The Guardian]]'' opined that \"she incites more of a sisterly spirit of collaboration, including riot grrrl feminists [[Le Tigre]]. Aguilera's not shy of the odd feministic declaration herself.\"<ref name=\"GuardianSexual\"/> In regards to production, Aguilera has often verbalized her preference of working with more \"obscure\" collaborators, and noted that she is not necessarily inclined to contact \"the No.1 chart-toppers in music\" because of their popular demand.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/58465/new-aguilera-album-set-for-august|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114030752/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/58465/new-aguilera-album-set-for-august|title=New Aguilera Album Set For August|last=Cohen|first=Jonathan|work=Billboard|date=June 11, 2006|archive-date=January 14, 2009}}</ref> ''The New York Times''{{'}} Kelefa Sanneh described her decision to work with [[DJ Premier]] on ''Back to Basics'' as \"a decision to snub some of the big-name producers on whom pop stars often rely.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/17/arts/music/17sann.html|title=Honey They've Shrunk the Pop Stars|last=Sanneh|first=Kelefa|newspaper=The New York Times|date=August 17, 2006|access-date=July 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Image==\nAguilera has reinvented her public image on numerous occasions throughout her career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.chron.com//handstamp/2007/02/christina-aguilera-claims-her-pop-throne/|title=Christina Aguilera claims her pop throne|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|first=Joey|last=Guerra|date=February 20, 2007|access-date=July 17, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6WEW0UaKu?url=http://blog.chron.com//newswatch/2011/04/ktru-station-off-air-but-still-broadcasting-online/|archive-date=February 10, 2015}}</ref> In the later 1990s, her then-manager Steve Kurtz marketed her as a bubblegum pop entertainer to capitalize on the genre's financial lure,<ref name=\"USAToday\"/> which earned her recognition as a [[teen idol]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/the_greatest/episode.jhtml?episodeID=67297|title=50 Greatest Teen Idols|publisher=VH1|access-date=July 19, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120209143618/http://www.vh1.com/shows/the_greatest/episode.jhtml?episodeID=67297|archive-date=February 9, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Aguilera introduced her [[alter ego]] \"Xtina\" during 2002 and 2003, which presented an increasingly provocative persona.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/10/29/1035683410806.html|title=Aguilera sheds teen pop image, alongside clothes|date=October 30, 2002|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=July 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.virginmedia.com/music/features/alter-egos.php?page=6|title=Christina Aguilera=Xtina|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223111841/http://www.virginmedia.com/music/features/alter-egos.php?page=6|archive-date=February 23, 2015|url-status=dead|access-date=February 23, 2015}}</ref> During this time, she dyed her hair black, debuted several piercings, and participated in several nude pictorials for publications.<ref name=\"CareerBiggest\"/> In 2004, Aguilera embraced a more \"mature\" image with retro-styled hair and makeup, which was inspired by classic movie stars including Marilyn Monroe, [[Marlene Dietrich]] and [[Mary Pickford]].<ref name=\"HelloMag\"/> This reinvention was named \"Baby Jane\" in 2006, an alter ego which was taken from the 1962 film ''[[What Ever Happened to Baby Jane? (1962 film)|What Ever Happened to Baby Jane?]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1539161/christina-clip-got-a-boost-from-outkast-role-playing-dancers-vmas-behind-the-camera/|title=Christina Clip Got A Boost From Outkast, Role-Playing Dancers|publisher=MTV News|first=Jennifer|last=Vineyard|date=August 23, 2006|access-date=June 23, 2013}}</ref> Aguilera received widespread criticism over her curvy figure from gaining weight in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/christina-aguilera-fat-girl-article-1.1171905|title=Christina Aguilera on her curvy, controversial figure: 'I got tired of being a skinny, white girl'|first=Joyce|last=Chen|work=Daily News|location=New York|date=October 1, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014134839/http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/christina-aguilera-fat-girl-article-1.1171905|archive-date=October 14, 2014}}</ref> She later received favorable media attention after a significant weight loss in 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/christina-aguilera-weight-loss-how-did-she-do-it-1411294|title=Christina Aguilera Weight Loss: How Did She Do It?|work=[[International Business Times]]|first=Amethyst|last=Tate|date=September 26, 2013|access-date=July 19, 2014}}</ref> In 2018, Aguilera appeared bare-faced without makeup and [[photo manipulation|retouching]] on the cover of ''[[Paper (magazine)|Paper]]'' magazine and received widespread praise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisinsider.com/christina-aguilera-no-makeup-paper-magazine-cover-shaming-2018-3|title=People are praising Christina Aguilera for her makeup-free photoshoots|date=March 27, 2018|work=INSIDER}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/03/26/entertainment/christina-aguilera-no-makeup-paper-magazine/index.html|title=Christina Aguilera goes makeup free for Paper|date=March 27, 2018|publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Aguilera Madame Tussauds.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Wax figure of Aguilera at [[Madame Tussauds]] in London]]\nAguilera is considered a pop icon,<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/04/02/idUS169214+02-Apr-2012+PRN20120402|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6NCNMPoOJ?url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/04/02/idUS169214+02-Apr-2012+PRN20120402|title=Superstar Songstress Britney Spears Will Battle Fellow Pop Princess Christina Aguilera This Week in the Championship Round of the Celebrity Bowling Hall of Fame Tournament|agency=Reuters|date=April 2, 2012|archive-date=February 7, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> and has frequently garnered comparisons to Britney Spears.<ref name=\"VirginMedia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.virginmedia.com/music/features/christina-aguilera-v-britney-spears.php|title=Christina Aguilera v Britney Spears: Who's the best popstar?|first=Matthew|last=Horton|date=August 11, 2012|access-date=July 19, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"EWCompare\">{{cite web|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2011/08/16/britney-spears-christina-aguilera-showdown/|title=Britney Spears vs. Christina Aguilera: Who's the greater turn-of-the-millennium pop diva?|first=Melissa|last=Maerz|date=August 16, 2013|work=Entertainment Weekly|access-date=July 19, 2014}}</ref> David Browne of ''Entertainment Weekly'' said that Aguilera is \"too eager not to offend\" in her mild-mannered music, making her a \"good girl pretending to be bad\", and also said that Spears' \"artificial-sweetener voice\" was a welcome change of pace from Aguilera's \"numbing vocal gymnastics\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,64697,00.html|title=Oops!... I Did It Again Review|first=David|last=Browne|work=Entertainment Weekly|access-date=July 17, 2009|date=May 19, 2000}}</ref> Matthew Horton from [[Virgin Media]] suggested that Aguilera was a more impressive performer than Spears despite her lower sales figures.<ref name=\"VirginMedia\"/> Aguilera has also been regarded as a [[sex symbol]].<ref name=\"NewYorker\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Sanneh|first=Kelefa|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/08/arts/the-new-season-music-idol-returns-her-image-remade.html|title=The New Season/Music Idol Returns|work=The New York Times|date=February 13, 2012|access-date=May 13, 2013}}</ref> A 2003 issue of ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]'' magazine that she covered became its best-selling issue;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maxim.com/girls-of-maxim/christina-aguilera|title=Christina Aguilera|work=Maxim|date=April 24, 2007|access-date=July 19, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301161931/http://www.maxim.com/girls-of-maxim/christina-aguilera|archive-date=March 1, 2012}}</ref> Aguilera was named \"Sexiest Woman of the Year\" by its subscribers later that year,<ref name=\"Maxim\">{{cite web|url=http://www.maxim.com/hot-100/2003-hot-100|title=2003 Hot 100 \u2013 Christina Aguilera {{!}} Maxim|work=[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]|date=May 1, 2003|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120301161931/http://www.maxim.com/girls-of-maxim/christina-aguilera|archive-date=March 1, 2012}}</ref> and also earned the magazine its best-selling issue after posing on the cover that year.<ref>{{cite news|title=MAXIM Magazine Unveils the 'Hot 100' for 2003|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/maxim-magazine-unveils-the-hot-100-for-2003-55695342.html|access-date=February 3, 2017|agency=PR Newswire|date=May 16, 2003}}</ref> Additionally recognized as a gay icon,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1458472/christina-gwen-stefani-dita-von-teese-help-bring-back-burlesque/|title=Christina, Gwen Stefani, Dita Von Teese Help Bring Back Burlesque|last=Edwards|first=Tanya|publisher=MTV News|date=November 4, 2004|access-date=October 20, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/arts-entertainment/music/2012/11/28/christina-aguilera-says-lgbt-fans-held-her-when-she-could-not|title=Christina Aguilera Says LGBT Fans Held Her Up When She Couldn't Stand|first=Diane|last=Anderson-Minshall|work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]|date=November 28, 2012|access-date=July 19, 2014}}</ref> she was the first honoree on [[The Abbey (club)|The Abbey]]'s Gay Walk of Fame for her contributions to the [[LGBT]] community.<ref name=\"Abbey\">{{cite web|last=Bain|first=Becky|url=http://idolator.com/5832331/christina-aguilera-the-abbey-gay-walk-of-fame|title=Christina Aguilera Immortalized On Gay Walk Of Fame|publisher=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|access-date=May 13, 2013}}</ref> The music video for \"Beautiful\" earned Aguilera a [[14th GLAAD Media Awards|GLAAD Media Award]] for its positive portrayal of the LGBT community.<ref name=\"GLAAD\">{{cite web|url=http://www.glaad.org/media/release_detail.php?id=3359|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050418084316/http://www.glaad.org/media/release_detail.php?id=3359|title=Eric McCormack, Todd Haynes, Christina Aguilera, The Hours, Six Feet Under Honored at 14th Annual GLAAD Media Awards Presented by Absolut Vodka in Los Angeles|publisher=GLAAD|date=April 26, 2003|archive-date=April 18, 2005}}</ref>\n\nFashion has also been a part of Aguilera's music career and image.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/photos/426310/christina-aguileras-fashion-evolution?i=43845|title=Christina Aguilera's Fashion Evolution|work=Billboard|access-date=July 25, 2014}}</ref> She has frequently worn clothes designed by [[Roberto Cavalli]], [[John Galliano]], [[Marc Jacobs]], and [[Alexander McQueen]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Alexander|first=Hilary|date=July 7, 2005|work=The Daily Telegraph|url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/article/TMG3342005/Galliano-celebrates-100-years-of-Dior-with-his-own-new-look.html|title=Galliano celebrates 100 years of Dior with his own 'new look'|access-date=November 20, 2009|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140108212736/http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/article/TMG3342005/Galliano-celebrates-100-years-of-Dior-with-his-own-new-look.html|archive-date=January 8, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Morley-Cartner|first=Jess|date=June 4, 2004|newspaper=The Guardian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2004/jun/04/jesscartnermorleyonfashion.arts|title=The old black McQueen in London for charity|access-date=November 20, 2009}}</ref> During the Back to Basics Tour in 2006, Aguilera performed in a stole made of fur designed by Roberto Cavalli, unaware that it was made from real fur of a white fox. After receiving a video about the treatment of foxes from [[PETA]] vice president [[Dan Mathews]], Aguilera replaced it with a faux-fur stole, further stating that she was \"very upset\" because she \"only ever wears fake fur\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peta.org/blog/christina-aguileras-costume-change/|title=Christina Aguilera Costume Change|publisher=[[PETA]]|date=December 12, 2006|access-date=July 25, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera's costumes from ''Burlesque'' were featured in the [[Fashion Institute of Design & Merchandising]]'s Art of Motion Picture Costume Design exhibition.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://travel.usatoday.com/destinations/story/2011/02/Oscar-nominated-fashions-on-display-at-LA-museum/43906488/1|title=Oscar-nominated fashions on display at L.A. museum|last=Cohen|first=Sandy|newspaper=USA Today|date=February 20, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140906051939/http://travel.usatoday.com/destinations/story/2011/02/Oscar-nominated-fashions-on-display-at-LA-museum/43906488/1|archive-date=September 6, 2014}}</ref> Wax figures of Aguilera are located at [[Madame Tussauds]] wax museums in London and New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.madametussaudswaxmuseum.com/branches/madame-tussauds-london.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121205062908/http://www.madametussaudswaxmuseum.com/branches/madame-tussauds-london.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 5, 2012|title=Madame Tussauds London|publisher=Madame Tussauds|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://starpittsburgh.cbslocal.com/photo-galleries/2011/10/14/watching-christina-aguilera-grow-xtina-through-the-years/justin-christina-wax-figures-arrive-at-madame-tussauds-to-open-club-mtny/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402103020/http://starpittsburgh.cbslocal.com/photo-galleries/2011/10/14/watching-christina-aguilera-grow-xtina-through-the-years/justin-christina-wax-figures-arrive-at-madame-tussauds-to-open-club-mtny/|url-status=dead|archive-date=April 2, 2015|title=Justin & Christina Wax Figures Arrive At Madame Tussauds To Open Club MTNY|publisher=[[WBZZ-HD2]]|date=October 14, 2011|access-date=August 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n{{see also|List of awards and nominations received by Christina Aguilera}}\n[[File:Xtina star walk of fame.jpg|right|160px|thumb|Aguilera's star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]], which she received in 2010]]\nAs of 2018, Aguilera had sold over 75 million albums and singles worldwide.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://vaaju.com/romaniaeng/christina-aguilera-topless-for-the-cover-of-her-new-album-photo/|title=Christina Aguilera, topless for the cover of her new album|work=[[Mediafax]]|date=June 21, 2018|access-date=August 3, 2018}}</ref> Aguilera's works have earned her numerous [[List of awards and nominations received by Christina Aguilera|awards and accolades]], including five [[Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/artist/christina-aguilera|title=Christina Aguilera Artist|publisher=[[Grammy Awards]]|access-date=August 3, 2014}}</ref> Various artists have noted that they were inspired by Aguilera, including [[Ariana Grande]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ArianaGrande/status/16191065723764736|title=Ariana Grande wishes Christina Aguilera a \"Happy Birthday|date=December 18, 2010|work=Twitter}}{{Primary source inline|date=January 2019}}</ref> [[Tinashe]],<ref name=\"TinasheQ&A\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6386058/tinashe-video-interview-aquarius|title=Tinashe On Bringing Females Into the Mainstream: 'There's Definitely Room For More|last=Lipshutz|first=Jason|date=December 8, 2014|work=Billboard|access-date=July 8, 2015}}</ref> [[Lady Gaga]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/491950/christina-aguilera-and-lady-gaga-perform-on-the-voice-effectively-putting-feud-rumors-to-rest|title=Christina Aguilera and Lady Gaga Perform on The Voice, Effectively Putting Feud Rumors to Rest|last=Johnson|first=Zach|date=December 18, 2013|publisher=E!|access-date=January 25, 2014}}</ref> [[Sam Smith (singer)|Sam Smith]],<ref name=\"SamInterview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/music/sam-smith-on-lady-gaga-tom-petty-boy-george-and-his-next-album/story-e6frfn29-1227304979980|title=Sam Smith on Lady Gaga, Tom Petty, Boy George ... and his next album|last=Beth|first=Dorris|date=April 15, 2015|publisher=News Corporation Australia|access-date=July 8, 2015}}</ref> and [[Lauren Jauregui]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/lauren-jauregui-shares-playlist-of-her-life|title=Lauren Jauregui Shares the Playlist of Her Life|work=[[Teen Vogue]]|date=October 26, 2018|accessdate=December 14, 2018}}</ref> among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capecodtimes.com/article/20100523/NEWS/5230322|title=Cape songwriter pens song for the troops|last=Wysocki|first=Heather|date=May 23, 2010|access-date=April 30, 2016|newspaper=[[Cape Cod Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2267844/selena-gomez-really-naked-revival-album-cover/|title=Was Selena Gomez Really Naked On Her Revival Album Cover?|last=Garibaldi|first=Christina|date=November 9, 2015|publisher=MTV News|access-date=December 2, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"GagaEOnline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/458017/lady-gaga-defends-miley-cyrus-lighten-up-and-leave-her-alone-|title=Lady Gaga Defends Miley Cyrus: 'Lighten Up and Leave Her Alone!'|last=Johnson|first=Zach|date=September 12, 2013|publisher=E!|access-date=June 21, 2014}}</ref> Her work has also inspired some athletes, including American figure skater [[Johnny Weir]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.windycitymediagroup.com/gay/lesbian/news/ARTICLE.php?AID=30675|title=Johnny Weir lets us in his 'World'|publisher=Windy City Media Group|access-date=May 13, 2013}}</ref> and American swimmer [[Dana Vollmer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seventeen.com/health/fitness/dana-vollmer-motivation-tips|title=Dana Vollmer Success Tips (Interview)|last=Abel|first=Alex|date=February 18, 2013|work=[[Seventeen (American magazine)|Seventeen]]|access-date=May 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAguilera's use of sexual imagery has helped catalyze public discourse on sexuality and feminism. Rhiannon Lucy Cosslett, co-founder of ''[[The Vagenda]]'', opined that the provocative dance routines in Aguilera's music videos are \"empowering\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/07/miley-cyrus-music-business-women-sinead-oconnor|title=Miley Cyrus: does the music business exploit women?|date=October 7, 2013|work=The Guardian|access-date=August 2, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera is also known for her television and music video impact; in 2012, Jon Caramanica of ''The New York Times'' commented that Aguilera \"will be remembered for her glamour, her scandalous take on femme-pop and her [[Brobdingnag]]ian voice, and&nbsp;... as the person who almost single-handedly reshaped music-competition reality programming\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/18/arts/music/how-christina-aguilera-changed-judging-of-reality-tv-music.html|title=How Christina Aguilera Changed Judging of Reality TV Music|last=Caramanica|first=Jon|date=September 17, 2012|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 13, 2013}}</ref> She was considered as one of the greatest women of the music video era by VH1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/photos/gallery/?fid=1477005&page=2&thumbnails=true|title=50 Greatest Women Of the Video Era|publisher=VH1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523054154/http://www.vh1.com/photos/gallery/?fid=1477005&page=2&thumbnails=true|archive-date=May 23, 2013|url-status=dead|access-date=May 13, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nWriting for The Hampton Institute, critic Terry Young, Jr. commented that Aguilera \"redefined the 21st century female pop performer,\" adding that following the release of ''Stripped'', \"artists like Spears and [[Beyonc\u00e9]] became more comfortable expressing sexuality and no longer felt the need to sell the notion of innocence\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hamptoninstitution.org/revisiting-stripped.html|title=Revisiting ''Stripped'': How Christina Aguilera Challenged Notions of Feminism and Sexuality|last=Young, Jr.|first=Terry|date=May 22, 2014|publisher=The Hampton Institute|access-date=May 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2008, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' placed Aguilera at number 58 on its list of 100 Greatest Singers of All Time, writing that \"[Aguilera] has had the finesse and power of a blues queen ever since she was a child star\".<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-greatest-singers-of-all-time-19691231/christina-aguilera-20101202|title=100 Greatest Singers of All Time: Christina Aguilera|date=November 27, 2008|work=Rolling Stone|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140705143029/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/100-greatest-singers-of-all-time-19691231/christina-aguilera-20101202|archive-date=July 5, 2014}}</ref> In November 2010, Aguilera was honored with a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/950886/christina-aguilera-gets-star-on-hollywood-walk-of-fame|title=Christina Aguilera Gets Star on Hollywood Walk of Fame|date=November 15, 2010|work=Billboard|access-date=August 3, 2014}}</ref> In October 2012, Aguilera's costumes and video collection was included on the \"Women Who Rock\" exhibition by the [[National Museum of Women in the Arts]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/28/arts/artsspecial/women-who-rock-exhibit-traces-female-music-artists-in-america.html|title='Women Who Rock' Exhibit Traces Female Music Artists in America|last=Olson|first=Elizabeth|date=October 26, 2012|work=The New York Times|access-date=August 3, 2014}}</ref> That same year, [[VH1]] named Aguilera the eighth greatest woman in the music industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/music/tuner/2012-02-13/100-greatest-women-in-music/94/|title=The 100 Greatest Women In Music|last=Graham|first=Mark|date=February 13, 2012|publisher=VH1|access-date=May 13, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2013 People's Choice Awards]], Aguilera was awarded the People's Voice Award, which recognized her ability to reach people across various genres.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1699242/christina-aguilera-peoples-choice-awards/|title=Christina Aguilera Goes From 'The Voice' To People's Choice|first=Jocelyn|last=Vena|publisher=MTV News|date=December 20, 2012|access-date=August 1, 2014}}</ref> Also in 2013, Aguilera was one of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''{{'}}s 100 Most Influential People in the World. In the article for the magazine, [[Celine Dion]] wrote, \"Without a doubt, [Aguilera]'s one of the most talented artists the world has ever seen and heard, and I think she's going to continue to amaze us for many, many years to come.\"<ref name=\"Influential\">{{cite news|url=http://time100.time.com/2013/04/18/time-100/slide/christina-aguilera/|title=Christina Aguilera: The 2013 Time 100|work=Time|first=Celine|last=Dion|date=April 18, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130419081239/http://time100.time.com/2013/04/18/time-100/slide/christina-aguilera/|archive-date=April 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, the [[Human Rights Campaign]] honored Aguilera with its \"Ally for Equality\" award. She was recognized as an \"LGBTQ icon\" who used her platform to share a message of hope and inspiration.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/christina-aguilera-to-be-honored-by-human-rights-campaign-for-lgbtq-advocacy|title=Christina Aguilera to be honored by Human Rights Campaign for LGBTQ advocacy|publisher=Fox News|access-date=March 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>https://www.hrc.org/blog/hrc-announces-senator-kamala-harris-will-speak-at-the-2019-hrc-la-dinner</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\n\n===Philanthropy===\nIn 2000, Aguilera supported a program called Come on Over and Do Something, which aimed to \"encourage kids to get involved in their communities and make a difference.\"<ref>{{cite web|access-date=April 27, 2013|url=http://www.sptimes.com/News/100200/Xpress/What_a_girl_wants__is.shtml|title=What a girl wants ... is for kids to help their community|work=[[The St. Petersburg Times]]|first=Ally|last=Sikora|date=October 2, 2000|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819090145/http://www.sptimes.com/News/100200/Xpress/What_a_girl_wants__is.shtml|archive-date=August 19, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A year later, she signed a letter from the [[People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals]] (PETA) to the South Korean government requesting that the country stop its alleged killing of dogs for food.<ref>{{cite news|last=Travis|first=Neal|date=September 13, 2001|title=Terror Attack Blows D.A.'s Timing|newspaper=New York Post|page=67}}</ref> In 2010, Aguilera auctioned tickets for her planned tour for [[Christie's]] A Bid to Save the Earth, which benefited the non-profit environmental groups [[Conservation International]], [[Oceana (non-profit group)|Oceana]], [[Natural Resources Defense Council]], and The Central Park Conservancy.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Manhattan Neighborhood Network]]|last=Ju|first=Siel|date=February 3, 2010|url=http://www.mnn.com/lifestyle/arts-culture/blogs/christies-celeb-studded-earth-day-auction|title=Christie's celeb-studded Earth Day auction|access-date=February 4, 2010}}</ref> Aguilera contributed US$200,000 to the [[Women's Center & Shelter of Greater Pittsburgh]] in December 2003,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2002&dat=20031223&id=q2wyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ULUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1457,6172137|title=People Watch|page=19|work=[[The Beaver County Times]]|date=December 23, 2003|access-date=April 18, 2016}}</ref> and was part of the [[Lifetime Television]]'s \"End violence against women\" campaign.<ref>{{cite web|title=Christina Aguilera, Nicole Kidman and Martina McBride Join Lifetime Television for 7th Annual Emmy Award-Winning, Multi-Platform 'End Violence Against Women' Campaign|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/christina-aguilera-nicole-kidman-and-martina-mcbride-join-lifetime-television-for-7th-annual-emmy-award-winning-multi-platform-end-violence-against-women-campaign-57825437.html|agency=PR Newswire|access-date=June 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Aguilera contributed \"Beautiful\" to the compilation album ''[[Love Rocks]]'', which proceeds benefited the [[Human Rights Campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140920235026/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/64152/love-rocks|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/64152/love-rocks|title=Love Rocks|work=Billboard|date=February 19, 2005|archive-date=September 20, 2014}}</ref> Aguilera participated in the AIDS Project Los Angeles' Artists Against AIDS \"[[What's Going On (song)|What's Going On?]]\" cover project, and became the face for [[MAC Cosmetics]] and spokesperson for MAC AIDS Fund in 2004. Singer [[Elton John]] featured Aguilera in his charity book ''4 Inches'', which benefitted the [[Elton John AIDS Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/paris-and-nicky-hilton-kimora-lee-simmons-christina-aguilera-rebecca-romijn-elle-macpherson-heidi-klum-among-44-celebrities-to-bare-all-for-new-book-to-benefit-the-elton-john-aids-foundation-54528372.html|title=Paris and Nicky Hilton, Kimora Lee Simmons, Christina Aguilera, Rebecca Romijn, Elle Macpherson, Heidi Klum Among 44 Celebrities To Bare All For New Book To Benefit The Elton John AIDS Foundation|agency=PR Newswire|date=June 5, 2005}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Secretary Clinton With David Novak and Christina Aguilera (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Aguilera (left) and Novak (right) were honored with the George McGovern Leadership Award in October 2012 for their contributions to the United Nations World Hunger Relief effort, while Clinton (center) was given a special tribute]]\n\nIn the run-up to the [[2004 United States presidential election]], Aguilera was featured on billboards for the \"Only You Can Silence Yourself\" online voter registration drive run by the [[political party|nonpartisan]], non-profit campaign \"[[Declare Yourself]]\". In these political advertisements, shot by David LaChapelle, Aguilera was shown with her mouth sewn shut to symbolize the effects of not voting.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/67360/stars-declare-support-for-voting-initiative|title=Stars 'Declare' Support For Voting Initiative|date=July 13, 2004|work=Billboard|access-date=August 15, 2014}}</ref> In late 2007, Aguilera became the spokesperson for \"[[Rock the Vote]]\", through which she encouraged young people to vote in the [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 presidential election]].<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071115130951/http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/arts_entertainment/aguilera%2Bbacks%2Bvoting%2Bcampaign/1047562|url=http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/arts_entertainment/aguilera+backs+voting+campaign/1047562|title=Aguilera backs voting campaign|publisher=[[Channel 4]]|date=November 14, 2007|archive-date=November 15, 2007|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2005, Aguilera donated her wedding gifts to American charities in support of [[Hurricane Katrina]] victims,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.today.com/id/10142556/ns/today-today_entertainment/t/christina-aguilera-wed-over-weekend/|title=Christina Aguilera wed over weekend|work=[[Today (US program)|Today]]|date=December 14, 2005|access-date=August 17, 2014}}</ref> and performed at \"Unite of the Stars\" concert for Unite Against Hunger in [[Johannesburg]], South Africa and for the [[Nelson Mandela Children's Fund]] at the Coca-Cola Dome.<ref>{{cite news|title=For The Record: Quick News On Christina Aguilera, Jennifer Lopez And Marc Anthony, Madonna, Bloc Party & More|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1512314/for-the-record-quick-news-on-christina-aguilera-jennifer-lopez-and-marc-anthony-madonna-bloc-party-more/|access-date=June 15, 2014|publisher=MTV News|date=October 26, 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Aguilera headlined London's Africa Rising charity concert at the [[Royal Albert Hall]], which raised awareness for finding substantial issues facing the continent.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/hi/music/newsid_7671000/7671293.stm|title=Christina Aguilera returns to the UK|work=BBC News|date=October 15, 2008|access-date=August 17, 2014|first=Sinead|last=Garvan}}</ref> That year, Aguilera appeared on the Turkish version of ''Deal or No Deal'', ''[[Var m\u0131s\u0131n? Yok musun?]]'', and donated proceeds to a charity program for [[orphan]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Altinsas|first=E. Baris|title=A loving family for children in need of protection|url=http://www.todayszaman.com/tz-web/detaylar.do?load=detay&link=156957&bolum=101|work=[[Today's Zaman]]|date=October 26, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520083051/http://www.todayszaman.com/newsDetail_getNewsById.action?load=detay&link=156957&bolum=101|archive-date=May 20, 2011}}</ref> In 2009, Aguilera became the global spokesperson for [[World Hunger Relief]];<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[Business Wire]]|url=http://www.businesswire.com/portal/site/google/?ndmViewId=news_view&newsId=20090715006146&newsLang=en|title=Aguilera Raises Awareness of Hunger Issue by Appearing in PSA, Advertising, Posters|date=July 15, 2009|access-date=July 15, 2009}}</ref> she and Bratman traveled to [[Guatemala]] with the [[World Food Programme]] to bring awareness to issues including its high [[malnutrition]] rate, and met with local families and beneficiaries of WFP's nutrition programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wfp.org/christina-aguilera|title=Christina Aguilera \u2013 A Voice for the Hungry|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130104151429/http://www.wfp.org/christina-aguilera|archive-date=January 4, 2013|publisher=[[World Food Programme]]}}</ref> Aguilera has helped raise over $148&nbsp;million for WFP and other hunger relief agencies in 45 countries.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=World Food Programme|url=http://www.wfp.org/christina-aguilera|title=Christina and the World Food Programme|access-date=January 13, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207041759/http://www.wfp.org/christina-aguilera|archive-date=December 7, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the [[2010 Haiti earthquake]], Aguilera donated a signed [[Chrysler 300]] which was auctioned for relief efforts.<ref>{{cite web|agency=PR Newswire|date=January 17, 2010|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/the-chrysler-brand-joins-forces-with-the-67th-annual-golden-globe-awards-to-contribute-relief-efforts-to-haiti-81918812.html|title=The Chrysler Brand Joins Forces With 'The 67th Annual Golden Globe Awards' to Contribute Relief Efforts to Haiti|access-date=January 18, 2010}}</ref> She additionally appeared on the ''[[Hope for Haiti Now: A Global Benefit for Earthquake Relief|Hope for Haiti]]'' telethon that January, where donations directly benefited [[Oxfam|Oxfam America]], [[Partners In Health]], [[International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement|Red Cross]] and [[UNICEF]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Karger|first=Dave|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2010/01/22/hope-for-haiti-now-the-telethons-10-best-performances/|title='Hope For Haiti Now': The telethon's 10 best performances|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=January 22, 2010|access-date=March 25, 2010}}</ref> She was featured on a public service announcement alongside former boxer [[Muhammad Ali]] to raise funds for the World Food Programme's efforts to bring food to survivors of the earthquake.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wfp.org/content/sneak-peek-christina-aguilera-and-muhammad-alis-haiti-psa|title=WFO|publisher=World Food Programme|access-date=January 31, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130807032922/http://www.wfp.org/content/sneak-peek-christina-aguilera-and-muhammad-alis-haiti-psa|archive-date=August 7, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Aguilera was nominated for a [[VH1]] Do Something Award for her work with the organization and her efforts in [[Humanitarian response to the 2010 Haiti earthquake|response to the earthquake]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/events/do_something_awards/2010/music-artist/|title=Do Something Music Artist|publisher=VH1|access-date=December 4, 2012}}</ref> In 2010, Aguilera was appointed [[United States Ambassador to the United Nations|UN ambassador]] for the World Food Programme.<ref name=\"RedBook\">{{cite news|title=Christina Aguilera Goes Solo|url=http://www.redbookmag.com/life/interviews/a6759/christina-aguilera-news-interview/|work=[[Redbook]]|access-date=February 24, 2011}}</ref> Following [[Hurricane Sandy]] in 2012, Aguilera performed \"Beautiful\" to open the ''[[Hurricane Sandy: Coming Together]]'' benefit telethon; all proceeds went to the [[American Red Cross]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Stars perform to help victims of Sandy|url=http://entertainment.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/11/02/14888295-stars-perform-to-help-victims-of-sandy|access-date=June 15, 2014|publisher=NBC News|date=November 2, 2012}}</ref> That year, Aguilera and [[David C. Novak|David Novak]] received the George McGovern Leadership Award.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wfpusa.org/world-food-programme-ambassador-christina-aguilera-and-yum-brands-chairman-david-novak-honored-state|title=World Food Program USA recognizes champions in solving global hunger; Pays special tribute to Secretary of State Hillary Clinton)|publisher=World Food Program USA|access-date=October 31, 2015|date=October 3, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131027224807/http://wfpusa.org/world-food-programme-ambassador-christina-aguilera-and-yum-brands-chairman-david-novak-honored-state|archive-date=October 27, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The following year Aguilera was honored with the Muhammad Ali Humanitarian of the Year Award.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schrenier|first=Bruce|url=http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/224454921.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130922105134/http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/224454921.html|archive-date=September 22, 2013|work=[[Star Tribune]]|title=Former President Jimmy Carter headlines winners of Muhammad Ali Humanitarian Awards|date=September 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Products and endorsements===\nIn 2000, Aguilera was the face for make-up line Fetish, where she worked in choosing colors and packaging for the line.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1424798/christina-aguilera-shares-her-fetish/|title=Christina Aguilera Shares Her Fetish|publisher=MTV News|first=Curtis|last=Waller|date=July 14, 2000|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> That same year, an interactive CD-ROM was produced called ''Christina Aguilera: Follow Your Dreams'' released by [[Simon & Schuster|Simon & Schuster Interactive]] which features games and quizzes, plus Aguilera herself talking about accomplishing her goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1121534/pop-beat-carlos-santana-everlast-christina-aguilera/|title=Pop Beat: Carlos Santana, Everlast, Christina Aguilera ...|publisher=[[MTV]]|date=June 27, 2000|access-date=September 20, 2017}}</ref> Throughout her career, Aguilera has endorsed several brands, including [[Sears]], [[Levi Strauss & Co|Levi's]],<ref name=\"Sears & Levi's\">{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/sears-and-levisr-launch-new-marketing-campaign-for-sponsorship-of-christina-aguilera-summer-tour-72584442.html|work=PSNewswire|title=Sears and Levi's(R) Launch New Marketing Campaign for Sponsorship of Christina Aguilera Summer Tour|last=Galvin|first=Aubree|date=July 31, 2000|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> [[Skechers]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,478535,00.html|title=Toeing the Line|work=Entertainment Weekly|last=Susman|first=Gary|date=August 27, 2003|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> [[Mercedes-Benz]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baby-benz.com/portal/a-class-w169/137--christina-aguilera-says-an-exclusive-qhelloq-to-the-new-a-class-|title=Christina Aguilera says an exclusive 'Hello' to the new A-Class|publisher=[[Mercedes-Benz]]|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> [[Versace]],<ref name=\"Versace\">{{cite web|last=Susman|first=Gary|date=March 5, 2003|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,429223~10~0~versacesignschristinaaguilera,00.html|title=Beautiful: Designer signs new muse and model|work=Entertainment Weekly|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141019000911/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0%2C%2C429223~10~0~versacesignschristinaaguilera%2C00.html|archive-date=October 19, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Virgin Mobile]],<ref name=\"Virgin\">{{cite web|url=http://www.brandrepublic.com/article/211094/virgin-mobile-claims-aguilera-ad-its-sexiest-ever|work=Variety|title=Virgin Mobile claims Aguilera ad is its 'sexiest ever'|last=Lepper|first=Joe|date=May 18, 2004|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> [[Orange UK]], [[Oreo]],<ref>[http://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/new-oreo-campaign-reminds-you-how-delightful-dunking-cookies-can-be/ New Oreo campaign reminds you how delightful dunking cookies can be] ''Adweek''</ref> [[Sony Ericsson]] <ref name=\"Orange & Sony\">{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2006/03/03/orange-signs-sony-ericsson-christina-aguilera/|work=Engadget|title=Orange signs Sony Ericsson, Christina Aguilera|last=Blass|first=Evan|date=March 23, 2006|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> and soft drink giants [[Coca-Cola]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,109862,00.html|title=Pop Star|work=Entertainment Weekly|last=Bonin|first=Liane|date=May 17, 2001|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> and [[Pepsi]] in 2001 and 2006, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|title=For The Record: Quick News On Christina Aguilera, Game, 50 Cent, Jessica Simpson, Nelly, C. DeLores Tucker & More|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1511468/for-the-record-quick-news-on-christina-aguilera-game-50-cent-jessica-simpson-nelly-c-delores-tucker-more/|access-date=June 15, 2014|publisher=MTV News|date=October 13, 2005}}</ref> In 2004, Aguilera earned [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]200,000 (about $300,000) for opening the summer sale at London's [[Harrods]] store<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/music/2004/06/29/christinaaguilera/|title=Christina Aguilera turns on the style for Harrods opening|work=Hello!|date=June 29, 2004|access-date=January 3, 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141028043032/http://www.hellomagazine.com/music/2004/06/29/christinaaguilera/|archive-date=October 28, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and appeared in an advertisement for [[MAC Cosmetics]]' Viva Glam V campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/pamela-anderson-is-the-next-spokesperson-and-newest-face-for-the-mac-aids-funds-viva-glam-v-lipstick-advertising-campaign-54386867.html|title=Pamela Anderson is the Next Spokesperson and Newest Face for the M.A.C AIDS Fund's VIVA GLAM V Lipstick Advertising Campaign|format=press release|agency=PR Newswire|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> Following the birth of her son in 2008, she was reportedly paid $1.5 million by ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' for her baby pictures, which became the [[List of most expensive celebrity photographs|ninth most expensive celebrity baby photographs ever taken]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/07/01/michael-jackson-magazine-business-media-jackson_slide_10.html|title=In Pictures: Most Expensive Celebrity Photos|access-date=May 29, 2013|last=Rose|first=Lacey|date=July 1, 2009|journal=Forbes}}</ref> In 2008, jewelry designer [[Stephen Webster]] and friend of Aguilera released \"Shattered\", a collection of [[sterling silver]] pieces, through [[Neiman Marcus]] and [[Bergdorf Goodman]]. Aguilera, who inspired the collection, was featured as a [[Hitchcock]] heroine.<ref>{{cite web|last=Conti|first=Samantha|date=February 19, 2008|work=[[Women's Wear Daily]]|url=http://www.wwd.com/accessories-news/jewelry/christina-aguilera-inspires-stephen-webster-silver-line-465346|title=Christina Aguilera Inspires Stephen Webster Silver Line|access-date=February 19, 2008}}</ref> They reprised their work together for Webster's 2009 spring line.<ref>{{cite web|last=Brown|first=Rachel|date=December 18, 2008|work=Women's Wear Daily|url=http://www.wwd.com/media-news/fashion-memopad/aguilera-goes-retro-pamela-meets-vivienne-stella-goes-moblie-1897710?full=true|title=Aguilera Goes Retro&nbsp;... Pamela Meets Vivienne|access-date=January 16, 2009}}</ref> In 2011, Aguilera attended [[S\u00e3o Paulo Fashion Week]] to premiere her new line of clothing for Brazilian department store [[C&A]], which launched in April of that year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.caras.com.mx/moda/322362/christina-aguilera-presenta-coleccion-ca/|title=Christina Aguilera presenta colecci\u00f3n C&A|work=Caras|publisher=Televisa S.A. de C.V.|language=Spanish|location=Mexico|date=August 19, 2011|access-date=January 3, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150103062908/http://www.caras.com.mx/moda/322362/christina-aguilera-presenta-coleccion-ca/|archive-date=January 3, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAguilera was named the number one awarded celebrity brand, with 13 awards won globally, in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://perfumes.christinaaguilera.com/en/awards|title=Christina Aguilera No. 1 Awarded Celebrity Brand|date=October 1, 2017}}</ref> Her first fragrance, Xpose, was released in Europe in late 2004 and sold relatively well.<ref>{{cite news|title=Showbiz Gossip|work=[[The Evening Chronicle]]|page=35|publisher=Newcastle Chronicle & Journal Ltd|date=January 18, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Hazlett|first=Courtney|publisher=[[MSN]]|date=May 8, 2008|url=http://www.today.com/id/24525545|title=Aguilera's new scent|access-date=May 9, 2008}}</ref> Through [[Procter & Gamble]], Aguilera released her signature fragrance, Simply Christina, in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/christina-aguilera/28220|title=Christina Aguilera to launch fragrance|work=[[NME]]|date=May 9, 2007|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> During the Christmas period of 2007, the fragrance became the number one perfume in the United Kingdom,<ref>{{cite news|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080109000818/http://www.rcalabelgroup.co.uk/news/8020/|url=http://www.rcalabelgroup.co.uk/news/8020/|title=Christina Tops Fragrance Charts|publisher=RCA Label Group UK. [[Sony BMG]]|date=December 17, 2007|archive-date=January 9, 2008}}</ref> and later in 2009 it was the country's fourth best selling perfume.<ref name=\"vogue.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/beauty/2010/01/15/all-star-perfumes|title=All Star Perfumes (Vogue.com UK)|work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] (United Kingdom)|date=January 15, 2010|access-date=September 18, 2010}}</ref> It won as the people's choice for favorite celebrity fragrance at the annual UK [[The Fragrance Foundation|Fifi Awards]] 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://nymag.com/thecut/2008/04/marc_jacobs_tom_ford_christina_1.html|title=Marc Jacobs, Tom Ford, and Christina Aguilera Win Top Fragrance Awards|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=April 24, 2008|access-date=August 9, 2008}}</ref> Aguilera released her third fragrance, Inspire, accompanied with a body care collection, in September 2008.<ref>{{cite journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081203174822/http://www.fashionmagazine.com/beauty/regulararticle/544/|url=http://www.fashionmagazine.com/beauty/regulararticle/544/|title=Sweet refrain|journal=[[Fashion (magazine)|Fashion]]|issue=September 2008|archive-date=December 3, 2008|first=Michelle|last=Bilodeau}}</ref> It was her first fragrance released outside of Europe.<ref>{{cite news|last=Epiro|first=Stephanie|title=P&G Hopes Aguilera Will 'Inspire' Its Fragrance Fortunes|url=http://www.wwd.com/beauty-industry-news/beauty-features/p-g-hopes-aguilera-will-inspire-its-fragrance-fortunes-1556271|work=Women's Wear Daily|date=July 24, 2008|access-date=August 27, 2008}}</ref> Her worldwide ad campaign included a television ad shot by David LaChapelle and was released in the United States in [[Macy's]] department stores. The release coincided with Macy's 150th anniversary which featured Aguilera in commemorative photos.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Business Wire|date=July 31, 2008|type=press release|url=http://www.businesswire.com/portal/site/google/?ndmViewId=news_view&newsId=20080731005593&newsLang=en|title=Mark Seliger Captures Macy's 'Stars' for Commemorative 150th Birthday Images|access-date=July 31, 2008}}</ref> She released her fourth fragrance, By Night, in October 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Christina-Aguilera-Night-Eau-Parfum/dp/B002SKFKZU|title=Christina Aguilera By Night Eau de Parfum|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=January 3, 2015}}</ref> which became the third best selling fragrance in the United Kingdom in 2009.<ref name=\"vogue.co.uk\"/> The range has been further augmented yearly by new releases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/10/25/christina-aguilera-royal-desire-ad-photoshop_n_2019309.html|title=Christina Aguilera's Royal Desire Perfume Ad Reeks Of Photoshop|first=Ellie|last=Krupnich|date=October 25, 2012|work=HuffPost|access-date=December 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-hook/474805/christina-aguilera-shows-skin-in-sinful-fragrance-ad|title=Christina Aguilera Shows Skin in Sinful Fragrance Ad|first=Gregory|last=DelliCarpini Jr.|work=Billboard|date=October 4, 2012|access-date=February 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://style.mtv.com/2013/10/18/christina-aguilera-unforgettable/|title=Christina Aguilera Reveals Unforgettable Fragrance Ad|publisher=MTV Style|first=Parry|last=Ernsberger|date=October 18, 2013|access-date=December 14, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7988853/christina-aguilera-perfume-ad-definition|title=Watch the High-Gloss Ad for Christina Aguilera's New Perfume, Definition|date=October 10, 2017|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]}}</ref>\n\n