]] wireless charging<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\"/>\n| input        = \n| display      = {{convert|4.7|in|mm|abbr=on}} [[Retina display|Retina HD display]] with [[IPS panel|IPS]] technology, 1334 \u00d7 750 pixel resolution (326 [[pixels per inch|ppi]]), 1400:1 contrast ratio (typical), 625&nbsp;cd/m\u00b2 max. brightness (typical), with dual-ion exchange-strengthened glass and {{nowrap|[[Force Touch|Haptic Touch]]}}<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\"/>\n| ext_display  = \n| rear_camera  = 12 MP with six-element lens, quad-LED [[Flash (photography)|\"True Tone\" flash]] with Slow Sync, [[autofocus]], [[IR filter]], [[Burst mode (photography)]], f/1.8 [[F-number|aperture]], [[4K resolution|4K]] video recording at 24, 30, or 60 [[Frame rate|fps]]; [[1080p]] at 30 or 60 fps; [[720p]] at 30 fps, [[Slow-motion|slow-motion video]] (1080p at 120 or 240 fps), [[timelapse]] with stabilization, [[panorama]], [[face detection]], Smart [[High-dynamic-range imaging|HDR]], [[Image stabilization#Digital image stabilization|digital image stabilization]], [[Image stabilization#optical image stabilization|optical image stabilization]], cinematic video stabilization (4K, 1080p, and 720p), Portrait mode and Portrait lighting\n| front_camera = 7 MP, f/2.2 [[F-number|aperture]], [[Burst mode (photography)|burst mode]], [[Camera#Exposure control|exposure control]], [[face detection]], auto-HDR, auto image stabilization, Retina flash, 1080p HD video recording, cinematic video stabilization (1080p and 720p), Portrait mode and Portrait lighting\n| sound        = Stereo speakers\n| connectivity = [[Bluetooth#Bluetooth_5|Bluetooth 5.0]]<br />[[Lightning (connector)|Lightning connector]]<br />[[Wi-Fi|Wi-Fi 6]] ([[IEEE 802.11ax|802.11ax]]) \n| other        = [[FaceTime]] audio- or video-calling, [[IP Code|IP67]] IEC standard 60529 (splash, water, and dust resistant)\n| sar          = \n| hac          = M3, T4\n| website      = {{URL|www.apple.com/iphone-se/}}\n| references   = \n}}\n{{iPhone models}}\nThe '''second-generation iPhone SE''' (also known as the '''iPhone SE (2020)''' and the '''2020 iPhone SE''') is a [[smartphone]] designed, developed, and marketed by [[Apple Inc.]] It is part of the 13th generation of the [[iPhone]], alongside the [[iPhone 11]] and [[iPhone 11 Pro|11 Pro/Pro Max]] models. Announced on April 15, 2020, the iPhone SE directly replaced the [[iPhone 8]] series, while also being the successor to the [[iPhone SE (1st generation)|first-generation iPhone SE]]. Pre-orders began on April 17, 2020, and the phone was subsequently released on April 24, 2020.\n\nThe second-generation SE shares the dimensions and form factor of the iPhone 8 (including its bezel and physical home button with [[Touch ID]]), but shares hardware components from the iPhone 11 lineup, including the [[Apple A13|Apple A13 Bionic]] processor (instead of the [[Apple A11|A11]], which is found in the iPhone 8).<ref>{{Cite news|last=Peters|first=Jay|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/4/15/21221293/iphone-se-vs-11-pro-specs-comparison-price-camera-size|title=How the second-gen iPhone SE compares to the iPhone 11|date=15 April 2020|work=The Verge|access-date=18 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This follows the pattern set by the [[iPhone SE (1st generation)|first-generation iPhone SE]] (which shared the dimensions and form factor of the older [[iPhone 5]] and [[iPhone 5S|5S]] but shared most of its internal hardware with the higher-end, larger [[iPhone 6S|6S]]).\n\nAs with the previous SE, the new phone is positioned as an entry-level iPhone, lacking for instance the edge-to-edge display, gesture navigation, and [[Face ID]] of the higher-end iPhone 11 and 11 Pro/Pro Max.\n\n== History ==\nA successor to the first-generation iPhone SE had been a source of rumor since 2017, the year after the device was released.<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.macrumors.com/2017/11/22/iphone-se-2-release-date-first-half-2018/ |title = iPhone SE 2 Again Rumored to Launch in First Half of 2018 |website = MacRumors |language = en |access-date = April 15, 2020 }}</ref> The name was also subject to speculation. Guesses included (most prevalently) '''iPhone SE 2 / iPhone SE2''', '''iPhone''', '''iPhone SE (2020) / iPhone SE 2020''', and '''iPhone 9''', due to design similarities with the iPhone 8.\n\nIn March 2020, cases for the phone were reportedly being shipped to [[Best Buy]],<ref name=\"9to5mac\">{{Cite web |url = https://9to5mac.com/2020/03/30/iphone-9-case-inventory-best-buy/ |title = iPhone 9 case inventory arriving at Best Buy, other retailers with April 5 merchandising date |last = Miller |first = Chance |date = March 30, 2020 |accessdate = April 3, 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200403181051/https://9to5mac.com/2020/03/30/iphone-9-case-inventory-best-buy/ |archive-date = April 3, 2020 |url-status = live }}</ref> showing an iPhone with an [[iPhone 8]]-sized body and a single camera lens.<ref name=\"9to5mac\" /> [[Belkin]] screen protectors for the iPhone SE were also listed on the online [[Apple Store]], cross-compatible with the base models of the [[iPhone 6]], [[iPhone 6S]], [[iPhone 7]] and [[iPhone 8]]. However, references to the iPhone SE were quickly removed.<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.tomsguide.com/news/apple-iphone-9-will-be-the-new-iphone-se |title = iPhone 9 will be called iPhone SE and could launch soon (Update) |website = Tom's Guide |accessdate = April 3, 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"9to5mac\" />\n\n== Design ==\nThe iPhone SE has an aluminum frame and glass front and back. The phone's dimensions and external design are nearly identical to that of the [[iPhone 8]] except for a centered Apple logo and no iPhone branding. Like the its predecessor, the iPhone 8, the second-generation iPhone SE has the same top and bottom bezels on the front and a home button integrated with the same second-generation [[Touch ID]] found in the iPhone 8.<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/iphone-se/ |title = iPhone SE 2020: Everything We Know |website = MacRumors |language = en |access-date = April 15, 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180805112853/https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/iphone-se/ |archive-date = August 5, 2018 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nThe iPhone SE is available in three colors \u2014 white, black,<!-- colors are not proper nouns --> and a [[Product Red]] edition.<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\"/> Though the offered colors line up with those of the iPhone 8 (silver, Space Gray, and Product Red respectively with no equivalent to the gold model), the iPhone SE uses a noticeably brighter shade of white, deeper shade of black, and lighter shade of red. Unlike the silver iPhone 8 (and all prior silver or white iPhones since the [[iPhone 4]]), the white iPhone SE features black bezels around the display like the black model and red model, in line with the color schemes of the iPhone 11 and [[iPhone XR|XR]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Color !!Name      <!-- hex codes from product selection page -->\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#262529\"| ||Black \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"F3F3F3\" |  ||White \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"B41325\"  |  ||Product Red\n|}\n\n== Specifications ==\n=== Size ===\nWith a screen diagonal of {{cvt|4.7|in}}, the second generation of the iPhone SE was among the smallest major in-production smartphones at the time of its release.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Axon|first=Samuel|url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2020/04/why-apple-has-stopped-making-small-phones-and-why-it-should-start-again/|title=Why Apple has stopped making small phones\u2014and why it should start again|date=18 April 2020|work=Ars Technica|access-date=18 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> However, it was still thirty percent larger than the SE's first generation, whose screen diagonal measured in at {{cvt|4|in}}. This led to one journalist declaring that the second-generation iPhone SE was the \"nail in the coffin\" for small phones after rapid increases in size in smartphones of all models in recent years.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Seifert|first=Dan|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/4/15/21222642/iphone-se-2-size-comparison-small-phone-trend-galaxy-oneplus|title=Even \u2018small\u2019 phones are big now|date=15 April 2020|work=The Verge|access-date=18 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Hardware===\nThe iPhone SE incorporates the Apple A13 Bionic system-on-chip (SoC) with an [[Apple motion coprocessors|M13 motion coprocessor]] and a third-generation neural engine. It is available in three internal storage configurations; 64&nbsp;GB, 128&nbsp;GB and 256&nbsp;GB.<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\" /> The SE has the same [[IP Code|IP67]] (dust-tight/30 minutes at 1m depth) rating for dust and water resistance as the iPhone 8.<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\" /> The phone lacks the [[ultra-wideband]] hardware (Apple U1 chip) found in the iPhone 11 and 11 Pro.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://appleinsider.com/articles/20/04/15/apples-new-iphone-se-doesnt-have-a-u1-ultra-wideband-chip|title=Apple's new iPhone SE doesn't have a U1 Ultra Wideband chip|website=appleinsider|last=Peterson|first=Mike|date=April 15, 2020|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"iPhone Hacks\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.iphonehacks.com/2020/04/2020-iphone-se-misses-features.html|title=2020 iPhone SE Misses Out On These 5 Features|last=|first=|date=|website=iPhone Hacks|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 26, 2020}}</ref>\n==== Display ====\nThe iPhone SE features the same Retina HD display found on the iPhone 8, with True Tone and wide color gamut ([[DCI-P3#Display P3|Display P3]]). The [[Force Touch|3D Touch]] found on the iPhone 8 has been replaced with Haptic Touch on the iPhone SE, which does not work for notifications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macrumors.com/2020/04/27/iphone-se-haptic-touch-notifications/|title=PSA: iPhone SE's Haptic Touch Doesn't Work With Notifications and It's Not a Bug|website=MacRumors|date=27 April 2020|accessdate=28 April 2020}}</ref> It can play [[HDR10]] and [[Dolby Vision]] content despite not having an HDR-ready display, done by down-converting the HDR content to fit the display while still having some enhancements to dynamic range, contrast, and wide color gamut compared to [[standard-dynamic-range video|standard]] content.\n\n==== Camera ====\nThe iPhone SE features a single 12 MP rear camera, similar to the single camera system of the [[iPhone 8]], capable of recording 4K video at 24&nbsp;fps, 30&nbsp;fps, or 60&nbsp;fps, 1080p HD video at 30&nbsp;fps or 60&nbsp;fps, or 720p HD video at 30&nbsp;fps. The camera has an <!-- MOS:NOSYMBOLS -->aperture of f/1.8, autofocus, optical image stabilization, and a quad-LED True Tone flash. The phone can also take panoramas up to 63&nbsp;MP, and shoot photos in burst mode. The front camera is 7&nbsp;MP with an aperture of f/2.2 and autofocus, capable of shooting 1080p HD video at 30 fps.<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gsmarena.com/apple_iphone_se_(2020)-10170.php|title=Apple iPhone SE (2020)|last=|first=|date=|website=GSMArena|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 26, 2020}}</ref> The camera interface adopts \"QuickTake\" from the 11 and 11 Pro, which allows the user to long-press the shutter button to take a video.<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\" />\n\nBoth the front and rear cameras of the iPhone SE support Portrait mode and Portrait Lighting, and Smart HDR is featured on the rear camera.<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\" /> Compared to the iPhone 8, the new processor of the SE adds support for extended dynamic range video up to 30 fps, stereo recording and cinematic video stabilization. However, the usage of older hardware for the sensor results in some limitations; the iPhone SE does not support Night Mode or Deep Fusion unlike the iPhone 11 and 11 Pro.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paulmonckton/2020/04/28/new-iphone-se-2-teardown-camera-iphone8-ifixit-deep-fusion/#4ac9a4b7683a|title=New iPhone SE 2 Reports Cause Serious Questions To Be Asked|work=[[Forbes]]|last=Monckton|first=Paul|date=28 April 2020|accessdate=28 April 2020}}</ref> The SE's implementation of Portrait Mode differs from the iPhone XR, as the camera cannot produce depth maps through the use of focus pixels, and relies on software-based machine learning instead.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.halide.cam/iphone-se-the-one-eyed-king-96713d65a3b1|title=iPhone SE: The One-Eyed King?|work=[[Medium (website)|Medium]]|last=Sandofsky|first=Ben|date=April 27, 2020|access-date=April 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Software===\nThe iPhone SE initially shipped with [[iOS 13|iOS 13.4]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ios.gadgethacks.com/news/apples-ios-13-4-1-fixes-facetime-bug-now-available-for-2020-iphone-se-0284197/|title=Apple's iOS 13.4.1 Fixes FaceTime Bug, Now Available for 2020 iPhone SE|last=|first=||website=Gadget Hacks|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 26, 2020}}</ref> and supports [[Apple Pay]] and [[Apple Card]].<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\"/>\n\n== Timeline of iPhone models ==\n{{Timeline of iPhone models}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|IPhone SE (2nd generation)}}\n* {{Official site|https://www.apple.com/iphone-se/}}\n* {{|https://www.live-tv.in/2020/04/new-iphone-se-2020-specifications.html iphone-se 2020 specifications/}}\n\n{{iOS}}\n{{Apple hardware since 1998}}\n{{Apple Inc. hardware}}\n{{Apple}}\n[[Category:IPhone|*]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2020]]\n[[Category:iOS]]\n[[Category:Mobile phones introduced in 2020]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 2nd generation iPhone SE|its predecessor|iPhone SE (1st generation)}}\n{{pp-move|small=yes}}\n{{short description|thirteenth-generation Apple smartphone}}\n{{lowercase title}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox mobile phone\n| name         = iPhone SE\n| codename     = \n| logo         = IPhone SE (2nd generation) wordmark.svg\n| logosize     = <!-- include \"px\" - Uses users default image size if omitted -->\n| image        = IPhone SE (2nd generation) white vector.svg\n| imagesize    = \n| alt          = \n| caption      = iPhone SE in white, with black bezels\n| brand        = [[Apple Inc.]]\n| manufacturer = \n| slogan       = ''Lots to love. Less to spend.''<ref name=\"Apple official webpage\" >{{Cite web |url = https://www.apple.com/iphone-se/ |title = iPhone SE |website = Apple |language = en-US |access-date = April 15, 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200415160521/https://www.apple.com/iphone-se/ |archive-date = April 15, 2020 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n| serieslabel  = [[History of iPhone|Generation]]\n| series       = 13th\n| modelnumber  = A2275 (United States/Canada)<ref name=\"Official LTE networks\" >{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/iphone/LTE/|title=iPhone - View countries with supported LTE networks|website=Apple|language=en-US|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><br /> A2296 (Global)<ref name=\"Official LTE networks\" /><br />A2298 (China)<ref name=\"Official LTE networks\" /> \n| networks     = \n| released     = {{Start date and age|2020|04|24}}\n| available    = <!-- Country {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} (Retailer) -->\n| discontinued = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| unitssold    = \n| unitsshipped = \n| predecessor  = [[iPhone SE (1st generation)|iPhone SE (1st)]]<br>[[iPhone 8|iPhone 8 / 8 Plus]]\n| successor    =  \n| related      = [[iPhone 11]]<br>[[iPhone 11 Pro|iPhone 11 Pro/Pro Max]]\n| type         = [[Smartphone]]\n| form         = [[Slate phone |Slate]]\n| size         = H: {{convert|138.4|mm|in|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\">{{Cite web |url = https://www.apple.com/iphone-se/specs/ |title = iPhone SE - Technical Specifications |website = Apple |language = en-US |access-date = April 15, 2020 }}</ref><br />W: {{convert|67.3|mm|in|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\"/><br />D: {{convert|7.3|mm|in|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\"/>\n| weight       = {{convert|148|g|oz|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\" />\n| os           = '''Original:''' [[iOS 13|iOS 13.4]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ios.gadgethacks.com/news/apples-ios-13-4-1-fixes-facetime-bug-now-available-for-2020-iphone-se-0284197/|title=Apple's iOS 13.4.1 Fixes FaceTime Bug, Now Available for 2020 iPhone SE|last=|first=|website=Gadget Hacks|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 26, 2020}}</ref><br />{{Current iOS}}\n| soc          = [[Apple A13|Apple A13 Bionic]]<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\"/>\n| cpu          = [[Hexa-core]] (2\u00d7 high power Lightning cores at 2.65 GHz + 4\u00d7 low-power Thunder cores at 1.82 GHz)\n| gpu          = \n| modem        = [[Dual SIM]] with [[eSIM]]<br>Gigabit-Class LTE with 2x2 MIMO\n| memory       = 3 [[Gigabyte|GB]] of [[LPDDR#LP-DDR4X|LPDDR4X]] [[Random-access memory|RAM]]<ref name=\"iFixit>{{cite web|url=https://www.ifixit.com/Teardown/iPhone+SE+2020+Teardown/133066|title=iPhone SE 2020 Teardown|work=[[iFixit]]|access-date=April 27, 2020}}</ref>\n| storage      = 64, 128, or 256 GB<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\"/>\n| memory_card  = None\n| battery      = 1,821 [[mAh]], 6.96 [[Watt-hour|Wh]], 3.82 [[Volt|V]] <br /> Internal [[rechargeable battery|rechargeable]] [[li-ion]] <br /> Non removable<ref name=\"iFixit\"/>\n| charging     = Fast charging up to 18W<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\"/><br />[[Qi (standard)|Qi]] wireless charging<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\"/>\n| input        = \n| display      = {{convert|4.7|in|mm|abbr=on}} [[Retina display|Retina HD display]] with [[IPS panel|IPS]] technology, 1334 \u00d7 750 pixel resolution (326 [[pixels per inch|ppi]]), 1400:1 contrast ratio (typical), 625&nbsp;cd/m\u00b2 max. brightness (typical), with dual-ion exchange-strengthened glass and {{nowrap|[[Force Touch|Haptic Touch]]}}<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\"/>\n| ext_display  = \n| rear_camera  = 12 MP with six-element lens, quad-LED [[Flash (photography)|\"True Tone\" flash]] with Slow Sync, [[autofocus]], [[IR filter]], [[Burst mode (photography)]], f/1.8 [[F-number|aperture]], [[4K resolution|4K]] video recording at 24, 30, or 60 [[Frame rate|fps]]; [[1080p]] at 30 or 60 fps; [[720p]] at 30 fps, [[Slow-motion|slow-motion video]] (1080p at 120 or 240 fps), [[timelapse]] with stabilization, [[panorama]], [[face detection]], Smart [[High-dynamic-range imaging|HDR]], [[Image stabilization#Digital image stabilization|digital image stabilization]], [[Image stabilization#optical image stabilization|optical image stabilization]], cinematic video stabilization (4K, 1080p, and 720p), Portrait mode and Portrait lighting\n| front_camera = 7 MP, f/2.2 [[F-number|aperture]], [[Burst mode (photography)|burst mode]], [[Camera#Exposure control|exposure control]], [[face detection]], auto-HDR, auto image stabilization, Retina flash, 1080p HD video recording, cinematic video stabilization (1080p and 720p), Portrait mode and Portrait lighting\n| sound        = Stereo speakers\n| connectivity = [[Bluetooth#Bluetooth_5|Bluetooth 5.0]]<br />[[Lightning (connector)|Lightning connector]]<br />[[Wi-Fi|Wi-Fi 6]] ([[IEEE 802.11ax|802.11ax]]) \n| other        = [[FaceTime]] audio- or video-calling, [[IP Code|IP67]] IEC standard 60529 (splash, water, and dust resistant)\n| sar          = \n| hac          = M3, T4\n| website      = {{URL|www.apple.com/iphone-se/}}\n| references   = \n}}\n{{iPhone models}}\nThe '''second-generation iPhone SE''' (also known as the '''iPhone SE (2020)''' and the '''2020 iPhone SE''') is a [[smartphone]] designed, developed, and marketed by [[Apple Inc.]] It is part of the 13th generation of the [[iPhone]], alongside the [[iPhone 11]] and [[iPhone 11 Pro|11 Pro/Pro Max]] models. Announced on April 15, 2020, the iPhone SE directly replaced the [[iPhone 8]] series, while also being the successor to the [[iPhone SE (1st generation)|first-generation iPhone SE]]. Pre-orders began on April 17, 2020, and the phone was subsequently released on April 24, 2020.\n\nThe second-generation SE shares the dimensions and form factor of the iPhone 8 (including its bezel and physical home button with [[Touch ID]]), but shares hardware components from the iPhone 11 lineup, including the [[Apple A13|Apple A13 Bionic]] processor (instead of the [[Apple A11|A11]], which is found in the iPhone 8).<ref>{{Cite news|last=Peters|first=Jay|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/4/15/21221293/iphone-se-vs-11-pro-specs-comparison-price-camera-size|title=How the second-gen iPhone SE compares to the iPhone 11|date=15 April 2020|work=The Verge|access-date=18 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> This follows the pattern set by the [[iPhone SE (1st generation)|first-generation iPhone SE]] (which shared the dimensions and form factor of the older [[iPhone 5]] and [[iPhone 5S|5S]] but shared most of its internal hardware with the higher-end, larger [[iPhone 6S|6S]]).\n\nAs with the previous SE, the new phone is positioned as an entry-level iPhone, lacking for instance the edge-to-edge display, gesture navigation, and [[Face ID]] of the higher-end iPhone 11 and 11 Pro/Pro Max.\n\n== History ==\nA successor to the first-generation iPhone SE had been a source of rumor since 2017, the year after the device was released.<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.macrumors.com/2017/11/22/iphone-se-2-release-date-first-half-2018/ |title = iPhone SE 2 Again Rumored to Launch in First Half of 2018 |website = MacRumors |language = en |access-date = April 15, 2020 }}</ref> The name was also subject to speculation. Guesses included (most prevalently) '''iPhone SE 2 / iPhone SE2''', '''iPhone''', '''iPhone SE (2020) / iPhone SE 2020''', and '''iPhone 9''', due to design similarities with the iPhone 8.\n\nIn March 2020, cases for the phone were reportedly being shipped to [[Best Buy]],<ref name=\"9to5mac\">{{Cite web |url = https://9to5mac.com/2020/03/30/iphone-9-case-inventory-best-buy/ |title = iPhone 9 case inventory arriving at Best Buy, other retailers with April 5 merchandising date |last = Miller |first = Chance |date = March 30, 2020 |accessdate = April 3, 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200403181051/https://9to5mac.com/2020/03/30/iphone-9-case-inventory-best-buy/ |archive-date = April 3, 2020 |url-status = live }}</ref> showing an iPhone with an [[iPhone 8]]-sized body and a single camera lens.<ref name=\"9to5mac\" /> [[Belkin]] screen protectors for the iPhone SE were also listed on the online [[Apple Store]], cross-compatible with the base models of the [[iPhone 6]], [[iPhone 6S]], [[iPhone 7]] and [[iPhone 8]]. However, references to the iPhone SE were quickly removed.<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.tomsguide.com/news/apple-iphone-9-will-be-the-new-iphone-se |title = iPhone 9 will be called iPhone SE and could launch soon (Update) |website = Tom's Guide |accessdate = April 3, 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"9to5mac\" />\n\n== Design ==\nThe iPhone SE has an aluminum frame and glass front and back. The phone's dimensions and external design are nearly identical to that of the [[iPhone 8]] except for a centered Apple logo and no iPhone branding. Like the its predecessor, the iPhone 8, the second-generation iPhone SE has the same top and bottom bezels on the front and a home button integrated with the same second-generation [[Touch ID]] found in the iPhone 8.<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/iphone-se/ |title = iPhone SE 2020: Everything We Know |website = MacRumors |language = en |access-date = April 15, 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180805112853/https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/iphone-se/ |archive-date = August 5, 2018 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nThe iPhone SE is available in three colors \u2014 white, black,<!-- colors are not proper nouns --> and a [[Product Red]] edition.<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\"/> Though the offered colors line up with those of the iPhone 8 (silver, Space Gray, and Product Red respectively with no equivalent to the gold model), the iPhone SE uses a noticeably brighter shade of white, deeper shade of black, and lighter shade of red. Unlike the silver iPhone 8 (and all prior silver or white iPhones since the [[iPhone 4]]), the white iPhone SE features black bezels around the display like the black model and red model, in line with the color schemes of the iPhone 11 and [[iPhone XR|XR]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Color !!Name      <!-- hex codes from product selection page -->\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#262529\"| ||Black \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"F3F3F3\" |  ||White \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"B41325\"  |  ||Product Red\n|}\n\n== Specifications ==\n=== Size ===\nWith a screen diagonal of {{cvt|4.7|in}}, the second generation of the iPhone SE was among the smallest major in-production smartphones at the time of its release.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Axon|first=Samuel|url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2020/04/why-apple-has-stopped-making-small-phones-and-why-it-should-start-again/|title=Why Apple has stopped making small phones\u2014and why it should start again|date=18 April 2020|work=Ars Technica|access-date=18 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> However, it was still thirty percent larger than the SE's first generation, whose screen diagonal measured in at {{cvt|4|in}}. This led to one journalist declaring that the second-generation iPhone SE was the \"nail in the coffin\" for small phones after rapid increases in size in smartphones of all models in recent years.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Seifert|first=Dan|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/4/15/21222642/iphone-se-2-size-comparison-small-phone-trend-galaxy-oneplus|title=Even \u2018small\u2019 phones are big now|date=15 April 2020|work=The Verge|access-date=18 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Hardware===\nThe iPhone SE incorporates the Apple A13 Bionic system-on-chip (SoC) with an [[Apple motion coprocessors|M13 motion coprocessor]] and a third-generation neural engine. It is available in three internal storage configurations; 64&nbsp;GB, 128&nbsp;GB and 256&nbsp;GB.<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\" /> The SE has the same [[IP Code|IP67]] (dust-tight/30 minutes at 1m depth) rating for dust and water resistance as the iPhone 8.<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\" /> The phone lacks the [[ultra-wideband]] hardware (Apple U1 chip) found in the iPhone 11 and 11 Pro.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://appleinsider.com/articles/20/04/15/apples-new-iphone-se-doesnt-have-a-u1-ultra-wideband-chip|title=Apple's new iPhone SE doesn't have a U1 Ultra Wideband chip|website=appleinsider|last=Peterson|first=Mike|date=April 15, 2020|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"iPhone Hacks\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.iphonehacks.com/2020/04/2020-iphone-se-misses-features.html|title=2020 iPhone SE Misses Out On These 5 Features|last=|first=|date=|website=iPhone Hacks|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 26, 2020}}</ref>\n==== Display ====\nThe iPhone SE features the same Retina HD display found on the iPhone 8, with True Tone and wide color gamut ([[DCI-P3#Display P3|Display P3]]). The [[Force Touch|3D Touch]] found on the iPhone 8 has been replaced with Haptic Touch on the iPhone SE, which does not work for notifications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macrumors.com/2020/04/27/iphone-se-haptic-touch-notifications/|title=PSA: iPhone SE's Haptic Touch Doesn't Work With Notifications and It's Not a Bug|website=MacRumors|date=27 April 2020|accessdate=28 April 2020}}</ref> It can play [[HDR10]] and [[Dolby Vision]] content despite not having an HDR-ready display, done by down-converting the HDR content to fit the display while still having some enhancements to dynamic range, contrast, and wide color gamut compared to [[standard-dynamic-range video|standard]] content.\n\n==== Camera ====\nThe iPhone SE features a single 12 MP rear camera, similar to the single camera system of the [[iPhone 8]], capable of recording 4K video at 24&nbsp;fps, 30&nbsp;fps, or 60&nbsp;fps, 1080p HD video at 30&nbsp;fps or 60&nbsp;fps, or 720p HD video at 30&nbsp;fps. The camera has an <!-- MOS:NOSYMBOLS -->aperture of f/1.8, autofocus, optical image stabilization, and a quad-LED True Tone flash. The phone can also take panoramas up to 63&nbsp;MP, and shoot photos in burst mode. The front camera is 7&nbsp;MP with an aperture of f/2.2 and autofocus, capable of shooting 1080p HD video at 30 fps.<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gsmarena.com/apple_iphone_se_(2020)-10170.php|title=Apple iPhone SE (2020)|last=|first=|date=|website=GSMArena|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 26, 2020}}</ref> The camera interface adopts \"QuickTake\" from the 11 and 11 Pro, which allows the user to long-press the shutter button to take a video.<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\" />\n\nBoth the front and rear cameras of the iPhone SE support Portrait mode and Portrait Lighting, and Smart HDR is featured on the rear camera.<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\" /> Compared to the iPhone 8, the new processor of the SE adds support for extended dynamic range video up to 30 fps, stereo recording and cinematic video stabilization. However, the usage of older hardware for the sensor results in some limitations; the iPhone SE does not support Night Mode or Deep Fusion unlike the iPhone 11 and 11 Pro.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paulmonckton/2020/04/28/new-iphone-se-2-teardown-camera-iphone8-ifixit-deep-fusion/#4ac9a4b7683a|title=New iPhone SE 2 Reports Cause Serious Questions To Be Asked|work=[[Forbes]]|last=Monckton|first=Paul|date=28 April 2020|accessdate=28 April 2020}}</ref> The SE's implementation of Portrait Mode differs from the iPhone XR, as the camera cannot produce depth maps through the use of focus pixels, and relies on software-based machine learning instead.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.halide.cam/iphone-se-the-one-eyed-king-96713d65a3b1|title=iPhone SE: The One-Eyed King?|work=[[Medium (website)|Medium]]|last=Sandofsky|first=Ben|date=April 27, 2020|access-date=April 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Software===\nThe iPhone SE initially shipped with [[iOS 13|iOS 13.4]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ios.gadgethacks.com/news/apples-ios-13-4-1-fixes-facetime-bug-now-available-for-2020-iphone-se-0284197/|title=Apple's iOS 13.4.1 Fixes FaceTime Bug, Now Available for 2020 iPhone SE|last=|first=||website=Gadget Hacks|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 26, 2020}}</ref> and supports [[Apple Pay]] and [[Apple Card]].<ref name=\"Apple official website: specifications\"/>\n\n== Timeline of iPhone models ==\n{{Timeline of iPhone models}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|IPhone SE (2nd generation)}}\n* {{Official site|https://www.apple.com/iphone-se/}}\n\n{{iOS}}\n{{Apple hardware since 1998}}\n{{Apple Inc. hardware}}\n{{Apple}}\n[[Category:IPhone|*]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2020]]\n[[Category:iOS]]\n[[Category:Mobile phones introduced in 2020]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications]]\n", "name_user": "20001610debjit", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPhone_SE_(2nd_generation)"}
